<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-US     09-30 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-US,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Tries To Stop Anti-American Outbursts</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alarmed by outbursts of
anti-Americanism during the Olympics, South Korean officials are
trying to defuse the criticism and halt growing admiration for the
Soviet Union.
   President Roh Tae-woo and other top officials Thursday called on
South Koreans to stop criticizing the United States for a series of
incidents during the Games and to remember the nations' close ties.
   ``We should not let one-time feelings damage the traditionally
friendly relations between the United States and our nation,'' said
Prime Minister Lee Hyun-jae.
   The anti-American sentiment was sparked by the behavior of some
U.S. athletes during the Olympics and U.S. media coverage of the
Games.
   South Koreans have pointed to the unruly behavior of the U.S.
team at the Games' opening ceremony and to what they called the
``rude and arrogant'' manner of many Americans. They expressed
resentment that the American media didn't play up the arrest of two
U.S. Olympic swimmers for removing a lion's head ornament from a
Seoul hotel lobby.
   Some Koreans also complain that their main ally is unwilling to
recognize South Korea's achievements.
   South Korean newspapers and television networks bristled with
angry denounciations of the NBC television network for playing up a
boxing incident last week in which South Korean boxing officials
attacked a referee who awarded a match against a local favorite.
   Some commentators said NBC and other U.S. media covered the
brawl to embarrass the Olympic host nation, claiming the Americans
had organized a conspiracy against the South Korean boxers.
   But President Roh defended NBC coverage, saying, ``Even if the
reports of NBC included something that hurt our self-esteem, we
should put up with it, since most of the network's reports were
affirmative.''
   The anti-American outbursts have been confined to the press and
popular opinion and there has been no apparent impact on relations,
but leaders warned the anti-American sentiment could endanger South
Korea's interests.
   The vehemently anti-communist officials, who initially played a
role in criticizing American behavior, became alarmed when South
Koreans showed a growing public interest in the Soviet Union _ one
of Seoul's main enemies in the past.
   Citizens seemed enraptured by their first encounter with Soviet
athletes and officials _ Soviet ballet and cultural offerings
during the Olympics sold out, Soviet goods disappeared in minutes
at stores and Soviet athletes were praised for their dignified
conduct.
   ``The spread of anti-U.S. and pro-Soviet sentiment may have a
serious impact on relations between South Korea and the United
States,'' said Yoon Giel-joong, chairman of the government's
Democratic Justice Party.
   Government officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
it was hard to believe South Koreans would admire the Soviet Union,
a long-hated enemy that shot down a South Korean jetliner in 1983.
   ``We should think seriously about what kind of country it was to
us in the past,'' said government spokesman Kim Zoong-wie Kim, who
reminded his countrymen that the Soviet Union backed North Korea
during the Korean war in the 1950s and was still the North's main
ally.
   Worried government officials also reminded Koreans that the
United States still has 42,000 troops in the country under a mutual
defense treaty and is Seoul's main market and vital to its
continued prosperity.
   ``It would be just like cutting off our own feet if Korea
destroys its trade with the United States,'' The Korea Economic
Daily said.
   ``This is the time to confirm once again that U.S.-Korean
relations are so valuable that they cannot be ruined carelessly,''
the newspaper added.
</TEXT>
