<1ST_LINE>r a PM-QuakeAnniversary     09-30 0761</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quake Anniversary,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Still Trying To Rebuild A Year After Destructive Earthquake</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITTIER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after the brunt of a violent
earthquake hit this quiet Los Angeles suburb, vacant lots gape,
many shops remain boarded up and homes are still undergoing repairs.
   Business operators and homeowners complain about the difficulty
of getting loans to rebuild, and at the same time, earthquake
repairs have generated business for some.
   The quake struck at 7:42 a.m. Oct. 1, 1987, unleashed by a fault
lurking 46,000 feet beneath Whittier Narrows, a flood control area
10 miles east of downtown Los Angeles.
   Measuring 5.9 on the Richter scale, the shock spread scattered
damage across more than 100 square miles. But the greatest
concentration of destruction was just to the south of the epicenter
in the quaint Uptown business district of Whittier, former
President Richard Nixon's boyhood home, and surrounding
neighborhoods.
   Brick stores collapsed, windows showered sidewalks and roofs
fell in. Walls split, and street lights and merchandise crashed to
the ground.
   The tremor and a 5.3-magnitude aftershock three days later
caused $358 million in damage throughout metropolitan Los Angeles,
killed eight people and injured 200.
   There were no deaths and few injuries among Whittier's 71,000
residents, but damage was severe enough to ensure that recovery
will be a long process.
   ``It's going to take an estimated 10 to 20 years before the
majority of the areas are rebuilt,'' said Sonny Morkus, city
emergency services coordinator and director of personnel.
   The town's structural damage amounted to $71 million. In all,
4,762 buildings were damaged, including 80 businesses and more than
300 residential units that had to be shuttered because they were
hazardous.
   About 36 of those 300 residences were razed and more may be,
Morkus said. Thirty of the businesses have been demolished and
others are awaiting the wrecker's ball, including a supermarket, a
theater and multistory department store.
   ``We're concerned about leaving them there, because we are in
earthquake country,'' he said.
   Throughout Uptown, signs posted on empty lots and fences give
addresses for relocated businesses, offer to lease, or announce
``Rebuilding At This Site.'' Atop one shattered building, a stopped
clock declares: ``Time To Invest.''
   ``There's a lot of frustration,'' said Mimi Campion, 24, working
behind a counter in a temporary trailer where the family business,
Uptown Mail & Parcel Services, reopened a month after the quake
shattered its store.
   ``We're way down. The only big period we had was Christmas, but
even that was down 30 percent,'' she said.
   The trailer is among a dozen that the city allowed to be set up
in parking lots. Some are vacant now, but it will be months before
they all are empty. The parcel service hopes to open in a new
building in March.
   After the quake, the Federal Emergency Management Agency and
state Office of Emergency Services set up centers for victims to
apply for aid, including low-interest loans from the Small Business
Administration. But there's a common feeling that loans aren't as
forthcoming as victims had expected.
   ``The SBA loans are what's fouling it up,'' Ms. Campion said.
``A lot of people aren't getting financed.''
   Ironically, interior designer Paulette Adams has seen her
business grow 30 percent since the quake, partly from people
redoing their homes because they were damaged.
   But she said government red tape kept her from getting any
federal help for the damage to her own home and business. She
credits loyal customers, understanding creditors, good neighbors,
hard work and God for putting her back in business after a
three-month shutdown.
   Ms. Adams said she got a grant of several thousand dollars from
the city, but the SBA would not loan her any amount. Her accountant
estimated that producing the paperwork to get a federal loan would
have cost at least $2,000, she said.
   ``I just said, anything. They said, `We don't care. You don't
have any income coming in,''' Ms. Adams said.
   ``I'm totally frustrated with them. ... The people who got money
had money,'' she said. ``The red tape was unbelievable.''
   George Camp, SBA deputy district director in Sacramento, took
issue with assertions that the vacant lots remaining in the city
are the result of rejected SBA applications.
   ``We do have to establish a reasonable assurance that the loan
can be repayed,'' he said.
   The SBA approved 8,400 loan applications in the region for
damage stemming from the quake, for a total of $149.6 million, Camp
said. The average was around $18,000.
</TEXT>
