<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Judge     09-30 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Judge,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``Last Emperor'' Team Working On New Film In China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Italian film company that produced the
Oscar-winning movie ``The Last Emperor'' is at work on a new film
portraying a detective drama about China's 7th century master
sleuth, Judge Di.
   Italian producer Franco Giovale of RVC Productions, who also
made the ``Marco Polo'' television series, signed a contract in
Aug. 1987 with the China Film Coproduction Corp., said Ann Roddy, a
production assistant for the project, in a recent interview.
   Judge Di combines elements of James Bond and Sherlock Holmes as
he braves China's remote and treacherous landscape to solve
baffling crimes in a world of bandits, prostitutes, monks and cult
worshippers.
   The Tang dynasty detective was popularized in the West by Dutch
sinologist Robert Van Gulik through his series of Judge Di novels.
   No director or filming schedule has been announced for the film.
``The Last Emperor,'' directed by Bernardo Bertolucci, took five
years to make.
</TEXT>
