<DOCNO> AP880930-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0404EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Argentina-Economy     09-30 0935</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina-Economy,0964</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economic Woes Erode Support For Argentina's Civilian President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul Alfonsin, the
civilian who won office on a wave of popularity in 1983 after
nearly eight years of military rule, is seeing his support erode
under an onslaught of inflation and unemployment.
   Eroding, too, is support for his Radical Civil Union, which must
face the Peronists in a presidential election in eight months.
   Inflation in August exceeded 25 percent for the second month in
a row.
   Argentines have seen the value of their currency, the austral,
plunge from $1.20 in 1985 to 7 cents now.
   Personal incomes have declined by 20 percent or more in the past
12 months, according to private estimates.
   Unemployment and underemployment at a combined 14 percent are
the highest since 1974.
   ``Every day, there's less work, and my family can't live on what
I earn,'' said Daniel Rio, a truck driver.
   ``We make $200 a month,'' said 33-year-old school teacher Alicia
Lupo, converting her austral salary into dollars. ``We want the
government to spend more on education and pay higher salaries.''
Several colleagues nearby nodded in agreement.
   Tensions were vented dramatically Sept. 9 when fighting broke
out among 20,000 people demonstrating against austerity measures
imposed by Alfonsin's government. Riot police used tear gas and
water cannons to restore order. More than 130 people were injured.
   More and more, Argentines are blaming their misfortunes on
Alfonsin, who until recently appeared immune from the criticism
aimed at members of his Cabinet.
   The 61-year-old president was booed when he inaugurated the
nation's annual livestock fair in August. Shouting above his
hecklers, an angered Alfonsin decried their ``fascist attitudes.''
   Hardly a week goes by that some group _ doctors, nurses,
teachers, mail carriers, train engineers _ does not strike to
demand pay increases. The 3.5-million-member General Labor
Confederation staged general strikes on Sept. 9 and 12.
   The first was to protest ``the hunger and misery the government
is trying to impose on us,'' said Saul Ubaldini, the
confederation's leader. The second, he said, was to denounce ``the
unusual and ferocious attack'' on demonstrators by riot police at
the first.
   Argentines of all classes have had to make concessions. They
wash clothes at home instead of sending them to the cleaners. The
customary weekly movie and dinner out have become biweekly. People
take buses and the subway instead of taxis.
   That irritates taxi driver Juan de la Larramendi.
   ``The Alfonsin government is the worst I've seen,'' he said.
``He says everything is OK, but it's not. Nobody has any money. How
can they take a cab? I guess my business is off 40 percent since
last year.''
   Prices have risen 20 to 30 percent in the past month. Beefsteak,
always cheap in this cattle-raising and agricultural nation, has
risen to the equivalent of $1 a pound. A quart of milk is up to 64
cents, a movie ticket to $1.65, and a bus token to 17 cents.
   The monthly minimum wage is 924 australs ($66). A secretary
might earn the equivalent of $150 a month, an engineer $400, a
bilingual college graduate with a degree in business administration
$500 and a tenured university professor $600 to $700 a month.
   Many Argentines have taken second jobs, and shoppers are buying
cheaper cuts of meat. Some buy lentils instead of meat and more
flour to bake bread and cookies at home.
   Ovidio Bolo, president of the Argentine Chamber of Supermarkets,
said total sales at member stores have dropped 10 to 15 percent
since July. New car sales dropped 15 percent in August, according
to the Association of Automobile Manufacturers.
   Many Argentines line up on pay day at banks and foreign exchange
houses to buy U.S. dollars or certificates of deposit (CDs) as
hedges against inflation. In July, banks offered one-month CDs with
a 27-percent interest rate.
   With an eye to the national elections set for May, Alfonsin
devalued the austral in August to spur exports and discourage
imports and financial speculation. He also implemented voluntary
wage and price controls, cut government spending and made plans to
borrow abroad.
   The government currently is negotiating with international
lending institutions for $5 billion to finance development projects
or structural reforms, and to help pay interest on Argentina's $56
billion foreign debt through the end of 1989.
   Preliminary results from the anti-inflation plan have been
positive. Short-term interest rates have declined, the austral has
stabilized against the dollar, and prices appear to be increasing
less rapidly.
   But organized labor and the opposition Peronist Party say the
measures are forcing workers to bear the brunt of the hardship by
accepting reduced purchasing power, or being laid off.
   Union leader Ubaldini said high unemployment ``is not a natural
cataclysm that is impossible to predict or control, it is the fruit
of a perverse socio-economic policy that benefits financial
interests and speculators ahead of the common good, the dignity of
man and the necessities of the family.''
   No independent polls have been published as yet on how voters
feel about the presidential candidates _ the Radical Civic Union's
Eduardo Angeloz and the Peronists' Carlos Menem, two provincial
governors nominated in July.
   But the trend appears to favor the Peronists.
   Votes for the Radicals dropped from to 5.9 million in
congressional and provincial elections in September, 1987, from 7.1
million in the national elections that sent Alfonsin to the
presidency in 1983.
   Votes for the Peronists, who now control 17 of Argentina's 22
provinces, increased to 6.6 million last year from 5.7 million in
1983.
</TEXT>
