<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSChild     09-30 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Child,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Boy With AIDS-Related Complex Enters New School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH ROXANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jason Robertson grabbed his new
backpack and walked into a new school Thursday, past protesting
parents who don't want a student with AIDS-related complex
attending classes with their children.
   Despite the placard-waving demonstrators, the 8-year-old had a
good start, said his mother, Tammie Robertson. School officials had
suggested that her son enter school by a side door.
   ``I insisted on walking right down the sidewalk, right in
front,'' Mrs. Robertson said. ``He's going to go like a normal kid.
I just felt he had to.''
   Wearing a fresh set of clothes and shoes, Jason was met by a
pack of reporters when he arrived to start second grade.
   The Robertsons moved to Roxana last month from Granite City, 15
miles north, where Jason went to court to win the right to attend a
public school.
   Jason suffers from AIDS-related complex, a disease that often
precedes a full case of acquired immune deficiency syndrome, which
is fatal.
   ``Things went very smoothly,'' Superintendent Charles Conner
said. ``We're going about our business of teaching children.''
   Conner said the youngster seemed ``somewhat bewildered'' by all
the attention, but Mrs. Robertson says her son handles it ``better
than I do.''
   Conner said at least 47 of the 358 pupils at South Roxana
Elementary School were absent Thursday. Seven absences were for
legitimate medical reasons, but the rest were probably linked to
parents' concerns about Jason, he said.
   ``They're going to have some time to think through their
situation clearly, to speak to some people that they have
confidence in, giving them advice,'' he said.
   The district has tried to allay the fears of parents through
information sessions about AIDS. Still, not everyone is convinced
that their children are risk-free.
   Jason became infected from a transfusion of tainted blood
products to treat his hemophilia, in which the blood fails to clot
properly.
   AIDS, both incurable and fatal, cripples the body's defenses
against disease, leaving the victims prey to infections and cancer.
   The Robertsons successfully fought in federal court to get Jason
in a regular classroom at Prather Elementary School in Granite
City. Before the judge's ruling last May, the boy had been schooled
alone in a one-room trailer on school ground.
</TEXT>
