<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatalFire     09-30 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fatal Fire,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire That Killed Five Youths Intentionally Set</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fire that killed five children in a house
whose back doors and windows were blocked by burglar bars was
deliberately set, fire officials said Thursday.
   ``It was not an accidental fire,'' said fire Capt. William D.
Young.
   The five children who died Wednesday ranged in age from 2 to 18.
They died even as firefighters sawed through padlocked burglar bars
on the back door and windows. A sixth child survived and remained
in critical condition Thursday.
   One of the victims was 16-year-old football player Bernard
Jordan who relatives and friends said received several threatening
phone calls.
   ``They said, `I know where you live and I know what room you're
in,''' said Mollie Jordan, 52, the children's grandmother and legal
guardian. ``They talked about burning the house down.''
   Officials found an empty gasoline can inside the house. Also,
officials said, a small sofa had been pushed against the front
door, hampering the victim's escape.
   Officials went to Wilmer questioned classmates of the
16-year-old victim on Thursday.
   Authorities went to Wilmer-Hutchins High School Thursday to
investigate the reports of threats to the 16-year-old boy.
   Bryant Pearl, who said he was a close friend of Bernard Jordan,
told the Dallas Times Herald that the boy had spoken as recently as
Tuesday night of fears that ``something bad is going to happen to
me.''
   The youth was found slumped over two younger children he
apparently was trying to protect from the fire, according to fire
reports.
   Mollie Jordan said she had left the burglar bars unlocked to
avoid a fire hazard and could not explain why the sofa blocked the
front door.
</TEXT>
