<TEXT>
   Arkady N. Shevchenko, the
highest-ranking Soviet official to defect to the United States, was
listed in fair condition after he collapsed during a speech.
   Shevchenko, an undersecretary general at the United Nations for
the Soviet Union from 1973 to 1978, was taken to St. Vincent's
Medical Center for treatment of intestinal bleeding after he became
ill during a talk Wednesday night at Florida Community College.
   Doctors worked on Shevchenko, 57, for three hours before he was
moved to the intensive care unit in fair condition, said hospital
spokesman Bob Arnold. His defection 10 years ago was hailed as a
coup for U.S. intelligence officials, who employed the diplomat as
a spy from 1976 to 1978.
   Shevchenko has been a U.S. citizen since February 1986 and is
the author of the 1985 best seller ``Breaking With Moscow.''
