<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0504EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Honduras-Nicaragua     09-30 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-Nicaragua,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Denies Its Aircraft Penetrated Nicaraguan Airspace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras denied a report in a
Nicaraguan pro-government newspaper that Honduran aircraft drew
fire while penetrating Nicaraguan airspace.
   ``The reports are totally false,'' armed forces spokesman Juan
Sierra Fonseca said on Thursday. He called the reports ``alarming
because they generate tensions in Central America.''
   Barricada, the newspaper of Nicaragua's governing Sandinista
party, said on Wednesday that Nicaraguan troops fired artillery and
rockets at Honduran military aircraft in Nicaraguan airspace near
the border. It said the Honduran planes were not hit.
   A Nicaraguan Defense Ministry spokesman, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said Honduras, which is a key U.S. ally in Central
America, ``provoked'' Nicaraguan troops into shooting at the
aircraft.
   Barricada also said the Defense Ministry reported two shooting
incidents Tuesday between Nicaraguan and Honduran troops. It said
Honduran troops ``harassed'' two Nicaraguan border observation
posts with 50- and 60-caliber machine-gun fire.
   Eugenio Castro, spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, denied the
Barricada reports and called them ``absurd.''
   Barricada said a helicopter gunship and an F-5 fighter jet from
the Honduran air force and a twin-engine plane without
identification recently flew over the border towns of Santo Tomas
del Nance, San Pedro de Potrero Grande and Somotillo. It did not
say when the incident took place.
   The report quoted Maj. Leonel Martinez, military commander for
Chinandega and Leon provinces in Nicaragua, as saying Sandinista
soldiers fired artillery shells and rockets at the intruders but
failed to hit them.
   Barricada said the incident heightened the possibility of a
military confrontation between Honduras and leftist Nicaragua.
   Honduras has permitted U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels known as
Contras to use its territory to launch attacks against Sandinista
forces.
   The bulk of Contra forces holed up in camps inside Honduras
after U.S. military aid for the rebels ended in February and a
truce in the 7-year-old civil war began in March.
   Martinez said the navy sank six Honduran boats trying to enter
Nicaraguan waters in the Gulf of Fonseca on Aug. 20, but that a
Sandinista army officer, Lt. Pablo Blanco Torres, died in the
incident. The gulf is shared by Honduras, Nicaragua and El Salvador.
   Barricada quoted another regional military commander, Col.
Carlos Brenes, as saying Contras have tried to cross into Nicaragua
near the town of Palo Grande in Chinandega province.
   Brenes was quoted as saying Honduran troops have been harassing
the border post at Palo Grande to provide cover for Contras
sneaking into Nicaragua from Honduras. He also was quoted as saying
that the Hondurans have increased their troop strength in the area.
   He said the Sandinista army has not responded with ``any unusal
military mobilization,'' according to Barricada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
