<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-DeathSquads     09-30 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Death Squads,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duarte Sees Rightist Intent to Reactivate Death Squads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
said death squads could return to his war-torn country after a
rightist leader warned of renewed guerrilla war if the right fails
to win presidential elections.
   Duarte was responding to comments made Tuesday by legislator
Sigifrido Ochoa Perez of the right-wing party Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena.
   Ochoa, a retired army colonel, predicted rightist guerrilla
groups might form to fight Duarte's Christian Democrats if Arena
``is deprived of its rightful victory'' in presidential elections
next March.
   ``Someone asked me if it was true that if we did not win the
election we would resort to nationalist guerrilla warfare. And I
say, a frustrated people could do just that,'' Ochoa said.
   Duarte said the comment demonstrates Ochoa's ``violent mentality
and how little he believes in democracy.''
   ``They (Arena) still believe in imposing themselves by force,''
Duarte said. ``By speaking of rightist guerrilla struggle what he
really is saying is that they have to reactivate the death squads,
and that is grave.''
   Duarte spoke with journalists Thursday at Ilopango airport
outside the capital following a skydiving exhibition to mark
Paratrooper Day.
   Local and international human rights groups blame right-wing
death squads for the abduction and summary execution of thousands
of suspected leftists in the early 1980s. The human rights groups
and the government say Roberto D'Aubuisson, Arena's founder,
masterminded the death squad campaign.
   D'Aubuisson, currently a legislator, denies the accusations.
   Arena trounced the Christian Democrats in legislative and
municipal elections last March, taking control of the unicameral
legislature. The rightists are favored by most to win the
presidential race.
   Duarte, 62, is prohibited by the constitution from seeking
another term and has been diagnosed as having liver cancer.
   The defense minister, Gen. Carlos Vides Casanova, also at
Ilopango, said he saw little possibility of rightist guerrilla
warfare but added: ``Whether guerrilla struggle comes from the left
or the right, the government must be prepared to combat violence.''
   A 9-year-old civil war pitting leftist guerrillas against the
U.S.-backed government has killed an estimated 65,000 people, most
of them civilians.
</TEXT>
