<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shuttle-World     09-30 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-World,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Millions Worldwide _ Minus Soviets _ Watch Shuttle Launch Live</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions worldwide watched the United States return to space
with the blastoff of the shuttle, but state-run Soviet television
showed only a music and aerobics program as Discovery hummed
skyward.
   Thursday's dramatic liftoff interrupted afternoon children's
shows in Britain, broke into ``Hill Street Blues'' in France, and
propelled Japanese to their television sets after midnight.
   It also sent up cheers from people in many allied nations.
   ``With this, America has reclaimed manned space flight. NASA has
shown that it can again launch with safety and regain its lost
confidence,'' said Franz Buob, a commentator for West Germany's ZDF
television network.
   Many countries had announced plans for live coverage several
days in advance and billed it as a major television event. Despite
a 98-minute delay in the launch, most networks kept their promise
to broadcast it live.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. as well as its main rival,
Independent Television, did so. People also saw the liftoff live in
Holland, Italy, and Switzerland.
   Soviets, however, did not see the liftoff. The official news
agency Tass moved a brief dispatch on the blastoff within four
minutes. In a newscast several minutes later, an announcer reported
the blastoff against a backdrop of pictures taken of Discovery on
its Florida launch pad on Wednesday.
   Tass' two-sentence report said the shuttle, with five astronauts
aboard, blasted off sucessfully. The dispatch noted that it was the
first shuttle launch since the space shuttle Challenger exploded
Jan. 28, 1986.
   The news agency also chose Thursday to release the first
pictures of the new Soviet space shuttle, a winged craft that looks
just like its U.S. counterpart. The timing appeared calculated to
steal some of the thunder from Discovery's launch.
   A Tass story accompanying the pictures said the Soviet shuttle,
at the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Soviet Central Asia, would be
launched on an unmanned mission to test its design and systems. The
report gave no date, but Soviet officials have said the liftoff
will take place sometime later this year.
   The Challenger disaster that killed its seven crewmembers was
also seen live in many countries. Thursday, many viewers abroad
said they were hoping for the success of the new mission.
   ``Thank God! Now let's keep our fingers crossed,'' said Elfriede
Haunold, a secretary in Vienna, Austria, after watching the shuttle
disappear into the sky.
   Workers at the headquarters of the European Space Agency in
Noordwijk, Netherlands, broke into applause as Discovery's main
rockets detached from the shuttle, ending the most dangerous phase
of the launch.
   ``It's quite a relief for everybody,'' said Dutch former
astronaut Wubbo Ockels, who flew on a Challenger mission in
November 1985.
   State-run Spanish television commentator Nuria Ribo told viewers
from the Cape Canaveral launch site: ``The successful launch of the
shuttle means a lot to Americans, and the important thing now is
that it's up and flying.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
