<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deaver Prosecutor Offers To Hit College Talk Circuit for Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that he isn't prosecuting former public
officials the independent counsel who conducted the case that ended
in former presidential aide Michael K. Deaver's perjury conviction
is ready to hit the college speaking circuit.
   A former Justice Department official says Independent Counsel
Whitney North Seymour Jr. circulated a letter to colleges and
universities in July _ before Deaver's sentencing this month _
offering to speak as a paid expert on government ethics.
   ``If he's so concerned about ethics, let him take his expenses
and speak for free,'' said Gary L. McDowell, a research fellow at
the National Legal Center for the Public Interest. McDowell said he
received the letter from a friend, whom he wouldn't identify.
   ``As a result of my indoctrination in the ways of Washington as
independent counsel in the Deaver case, I have developed quite
strong views on how to achieve a higher standards of ethics in
government,'' Seymour wrote under the letterhead of his New York
law office.
   Seymour refused to comment about the letter to The Associated
Press, but in an interview published in Thursday's editions of The
New York Times, Seymour defended the speaking engagements, saying
his fee of $2,500 to $5,000 per appearance was ``way below
market.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Steps Seen Likely to Prevent Future Buildup of Dead Trees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel says he
expects the recommendations of an interagency review committee to
help prevent the century-long buildup of dead trees that made this
summer's fires in Yellowstone National Park so destructive.
   But the National Park Service's chief ranger in Yellowstone said
controlled burning hasn't been done there before because the park's
most prominent tree, the lodgepole pine, is almost impossible to
burn under control.
   Hodel told two Senate subcommittees on Thursday that he and
Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng had asked a panel of experts to
propose changes in the Park Service ``let it burn'' policy that had
led to this summer's disaster y Dec. 15.
   ``I would expect them to come back with a recommended means of
trying to reduce the fuel. I don't think anybody can tell me what
that will be,'' Hodel said at a hearing of the agriculture,
nutrition and forest subcommittee of the Agriculture Committee and
