<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Peacemakers     09-30 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Peacemakers,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Peace-Keeping Force Left Out of Nobel Equation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nobel-Soldiers, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 Nobel Peace Prize, awarded to U.N.
peacekeeping groups, does not include one of the world's major
peacekeeping forces, which was kept from the honor by the politics
of the Middle East.
   The 2,500 men and women of the Multinational Force and Observers
police the border between Egypt and Israel. If not for political
considerations, they would be wearing the powder blue berets of the
United Nations peacekeeping forces instead of their burnt orange.
   The force was organized by the United States to man the border
between Egypt and Israel after Israeli troops evacuated the Sinai
Peninsula on April 25, 1982, under the Arab world's first peace
treaty with the Jewish state.
   Then-President Jimmy Carter, who interceded with the unfriendly
neighbors to negotiate first the Camp David Accords in 1978, then
the 1979 treaty, wanted a U.N. force to legitimize the pact.
   Faced with an expected veto by the Soviet Union in the U.N.
Security Council, however, Carter decided to set up the force
himself.
   U.S., Colombian and Fijian infantrymen patrol the 250-mile
length of the Sinai in white pickup trucks or stand guard in
whitewashed watch towers.
   Italian members in revamped, white-painted minesweepers based at
Sharm el-Sheikh on the southern tip of Sinai chug about in the
Strait of Tiran at the strategic southern entrance of the Gulf of
Aqaba.
   Former Director General Peter D. Constable wrote in his 1988
annual report that their mission, simply stated, is: ``Observe and
report.''
   There has been no serious breach of the peace in the more than
six years that the force has been in place. But in November 1985, a
plane carrying 248 U.S. servicemen, who had just finished their
tour of duty in the Sinai, and eight crewmen crashed in Gander,
Newfoundland, killing all on board.
   In Oslo, the Norwegian Nobel Committee announced Thursday that
it was honoring U.N. peacekeepers in the Middle East, Cyprus and
the Indian subcontinent for their help in ``reducing the level of
conflict even though the fundamental causes of the struggles
frequently remain.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
