<DOCNO> AP880930-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0515EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Taba     09-30 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Taba,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taba Decision Causes Fight Among Israeli Parties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision of an international arbitration
panel to back Egypt on a disputed beachfront has created a major
issue in Israel's election campaign.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, head of the hardline Likud bloc,
used the panel's ruling to push his view that Israel should not
agree to an international conference on Middle East peace.
   ``It was proven yet again that an international arbitrage always
harms Israel's interests, and Taba is not an exception,'' Shamir
said on Israel Television Thursday.
   ``This is a lesson for the future,'' said Shamir. He said the
rival left-leaning Labor Party has wrongly pushed for arbitration
rather than talks with Egypt to resolve the dispute.
   However, Energy Minister Moshe Shachal of the Labor Party said
at a news conference in Tel Aviv that Shamir ``preferred narrow
party interests to national and ... to the real solution of the
Taba problem.''
   ``We could have reached a compromise, but he preferred to ignore
the problems and to bring the situation to the point of no
return,'' Shachal said Thursday.
   Shamir fears an international forum would force Israel to make
territorial concessions on the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
territories the Jewish state has occupied since the 1967 Middle
East war. Labor favors such an international conference.
   The future of the West Bank and Gaza with their 1.5-million
Palestinian population is the focal point of the Parliament
elections scheduled for Nov. 1. The territories have been torn by
an anti-Israeli uprising since December.
   The international arbitration panel, in its decision published
Thursday in Geneva, awarded five key disputed border points to
Egypt.
   The five-member arbitration team is made up of members from
Sweden, France, Switzerland, Egypt, and Israel. They ruled 4-1 with
the Israeli member opposed. An arbitration agreement signed on
Sept. 11, 1986, commits Egypt and Israel to carry out the ruling.
   However, the decision does not actually give Taba, a 250-acre
beachfront resort, to Egypt. Though Egypt won key boundary markers,
Israeli officials said more bilateral talks are needed to draw the
actual border line.
</TEXT>
