<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-IMF-WorldBank     09-30 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IMF-World Bank,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Berlin Brings Home Third World Ills to Finance Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's top officials on financial aid to poor
countries have left an annual congress for home with memories of
police sirens and demonstrators' chants.
   The officials from 151 countries say they are working at home
for exactly what the demonstrators in West Berlin demanded: an end
to hunger, poverty, illiteracy and damage to the environment in the
Third World.
   At the joint annual meeting of the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund, which ended Thursday, the staff's
final ``Urgent Notice'' said:
   ``The German authorities have advised that a demonstration is
scheduled to take place in the downtown area of (West) Berlin in
the late afternoon today. ... Participants who plan to leave .. .
are advised to check out of their hotels as soon as feasible to
avoid delays and missed flights.''
   Every night since Sunday, demonstrators poured into major
streets in downtown West Berlin, sometimes fighting riot police.
But most of the protesters just chanted slogans against the two
organizations.
   Many protesters were injured, but no serious casualties have
been reported. About 500 demonstrators were briefly detained and at
least one vehicle was set afire.
   The demonstrators made their point with slogans like ``Murder
Meeting!'' and signs that told the participants to go home and
count their money.
   At least one, Finance Minister J. B. Sumarlin of Indonesia,
agreed in a speech that some programs of the monetary fund did more
harm than good.
   The World Bank is the chief source of aid loans on easy
financial terms for Third World countries. The fund also lends
money to them and organizes loan packages.
   Borrowers and critics complain the austerity programs often
imposed with the loans hurt poor people.
   Michel Camdessus, managing director of the fund, says
governments inflict even more suffering on their people if they
refuse to make the policy changes it asks in return for loans.
   Many participants in the meeting were impressed by the
atmosphere in Berlin. They have never had so much public attention.
Meetings usually take place in Washington, a city not given to
street confrontations.
   Barber B. Conable, president of the bank, told reporters that he
had no time to make contact with the opposition.
   ``I realize that they question the effectiveness of World Bank
programs,'' he said. ``I think we must carry a burden of
explanation as to our use of public moneys.''
   The opposition was organized by left-wing groups.
   But there was no sign of participation by the German Democratic
Republic on the other side of the Berlin wall. Its Communist
leaders are reported to want to join the bank and fund and secure
loans in hard currency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
