<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo on Friday, while stock prices rose moderately.
   The dollar closed the week at 134.30 yen, down 0.05 yen from
Thursday's close of 134.35 yen. After opening higher at 134.57 yen,
the currency ranged between 134.25 yen and 134.60 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
51.88 points Thursday, rebounded 223.54 points or 0.81 percent to
finish the day's trading at 27,923.67.
   The gain in Tokyo stock prices followed an overnight rise in the
Dow Jones industrial average on Wall Street.
   ``Participants traded a wide variety of issues, including steels
and leisure-related stocks,'' said an analyst with Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   Although investors were still concerned about the condition of
ailing Emperor Hirohito, ``they are confident about Japan's
economic outlook,'' he said.
   On the foreign exchange market, many corporate players remained
on the sidelines because of the end today of the first half of the
Japanese fiscal year and the lack of significant market-affecting
news, dealers said.
