<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShuttleBriefs     09-30 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Briefs,0850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Does a Little Flag-waving of its Own</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Without much fanfare, a new
tradition was initiated at Kennedy Space Center in the hours before
the shuttle Discovery lifted off.
   An American flag was unfurled in the firing room as the rotating
service structure was rolled away from the spacecraft Wednesday
afternoon. It will remain there in the launch control center until
the astronauts return to Earth on Monday and leave Discovery.
   ``It was not a very formal sort of thing,'' said NASA spokesman
Hugh Harris. ``You don't take time out of the countdown. It was
just as the announcement was made that the rotating service
structure was being retracted that the string was pulled and the
flag rolled down.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Reach Out and Touch _ An Astronaut?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BASKING RIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People across the country will be
able to listen to live space-to-ground communications throughout
the shuttle Discovery's flight.
   The ``Dial-a-Shuttle'' service is sponsored by the National
Space Society. AT&T's DIAL-IT 900 Services will be used to
establish the earth-to-space link, Harry Baumgartner, a spokesman
for the company, said Thursday.
   The service became available at 7:59 a.m. Thursday, two hours
before the launch had been scheduled, to callers who dialed
900-909-6272, said Kip Tarpley, a spokesman for the society.
   Callers can hear live conversations between the five astronauts
and mission control in Houston, Tarpley said. During quiet time,
news updates, commentary, taped interviews and highlights of the
day's activities can be heard, he said.
   It costs $2 for the first minute and 45 cents for each
additional minute callers spend listening to the conversations.
Money earned from the service will be spent on space-related
programs, he said.
   The service is scheduled to end about two hours after the
shuttle lands Monday at Edwards Air Force Base in California.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Flying the Crowded Skies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the many satellites crowding
the orbital skies above the Earth briefly threatened to affect the
launch of space shuttle Discovery.
   When liftoff of the spacecraft was delayed Thursday morning,
engineers in launch control at Cape Canaveral announced that though
the shuttle could be launched as late 2:30 p.m. EDT, there were two
brief periods that were restricted because of satellites passing
near Discovery's flight path.
   Officials at the Johnson Space Center said they received a
Collision Avoidance warning from the Air Force Missile Command,
which keeps track of the hundreds of satellites in orbit.
   Flight Director Gary Coen said the warning had no effect on the
Discovery mission because the shuttle was launched at 11:37 a.m.
EDT, almost a half hour before the first of the two resticted times.
   The satellites that triggered the warnings were not identifed by
the Air Force.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Space Pioneer Says Unmanned Flight Still the Ticket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Physicist James A. Van Allen said he was
rooting for a safe launch for the shuttle Discovery, but its
successful liftoff does not change his outlook that manned space
travel is slighting science.
   Van Allen, a pioneer in unmanned exploration from the earliest
days of ventures into space, grumbled even before the Challenger
disaster 32 months ago that the United States was putting too much
emphasis on manned flights and letting scientific experiments that
could fly on unmanned rockets languish.
   Van Allen, discoverer of the radiation belts that surround the
Earth and are named for him, and a team of University of Iowa
scientists designed instruments for the Jan. 31, 1958, launch of
Explorer 1, the first U.S. satellite.
   Van Allen also directed the Pioneer 10 program, a flyby probe to
Jupiter that continues to send back information.
   After 16 years, Pioneer 10 is 4 billion miles away from Earth
and traveling at 28,400 miles an hour. It is the most remote
man-made object in the universe.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Banished Journalists Loved Launch, Wish They Were Closer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 journalists at a
remote press site cheered Discovery's majestic liftoff but
expressed disappointment that new safety rules prevented them from
a closer view.
   Prompted by Air Force concerns that the Complex 39 press site
could be bombarded by falling debris if the solid rocket boosters
malfunctioned, only 1,800 reporters were allowed to work from the
main press site, just over four miles from the launchpad. Daily
newspapers were allowed to have just two people at the main press
site.
   The alternate press site was more than six miles from the
launchpad.
   Despite the spectacular liftoff, reporters at the remote site
were envious of their colleagues who were closer to the launch pad
and expressed fears that additional restrictions may follow.
   Most of the journalists arrived at the mosquito-infested site
before dawn after driving in bumper-to-bumper traffic for up to two
hours from Titusville and Cocoa Beach.
   Reporters complained the lack of telephones, electricity and
work space limited their usefulness at the remote site.
</TEXT>
