<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0419EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Korea     09-30 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Korea,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Says US Troop Reduction Could Follow North-South Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's foreign minister says his
government would be willing to discuss withdrawal of U.S. military
forces from its territory only after serious negotiations with
North Korea on reducing tension.
   Rejecting familiar North Korean demands, Choi Kwang-soo said
Thursday night that ``the withdrawal of American forces from Korea
cannot be a precondition ... cannot be an obstruction to serious
serious negotiations between the two parts of Korea.
   ``But we are prepared to consider the reduction ... in
consultation with your (U.S.) government if we have successful
negotiations with North Korea for reduction of tension,'' the
minister said in reply to questions from an audience of 300 at the
Washington World Affairs council.
   Choi said South Korea had expressed its sentiments to North
Korea, the Soviet Union and China, and he hopes the two communist
powers will influence their ally toward dialogue.
   The United States has an estimated 40,000 ground and air forces
based in South Korea.
   Describing U.S. forces in Korea as a deterrent threatening no
one, Choi said, ``We have made it known to North Korea, to the
Soviet Union, to the Chinese that withdrawal of American forces ...
is one of the main topics that has to be tackled in negotiations
for peace and stability'' _ but only after ending tension and
mistrust between the two Koreas and reaching an accord.
   ``The vast majority of (South) Korean people'' want them to stay
as a vital deterrent against resumption of hostilities by the
North, Choi said of U.S. troops that have been in South Korea since
the 1950-53 Korean War. Choi described recent anti-American
flareups in his country as the work of ``a few radical students.''
   ``Public airing of anti-American sentiments is a testament to
the new pluralism, and political liberalization in full swing in
(South) Korea,'' he said in a prepared speech preceding the
30-minute question-and-answer session.
   Choi confirmed reports of Seoul's expanding contacts with
Beijing and Moscow. U.S.-Soviet relations ``have reached a new
plateau,'' and this is ``good news for Korea,'' he said, describing
a trend of ``substantial progress in unofficial relations'' with
China and increasing contacts with Moscow.
   The Soviet Union, despite providing vast amounts of military aid
including sophisticated weapons to North Korea, and China are
demonstrating today that they have a stake in peace and regional
stability, Choi said. ``In this spirit, we are trying our best to
improve our relations with these two powers,'' with one of the
goals being ``to influence North Korea,'' he added.
   Choi said South Korean President Roh Tae-woo's July 7 proposals
on reducing tension and ending confrontation between North and
South Korea and their respective allies already have helped produce
a Hungarian-South Korean agreement to pursue full diplomatic
relations. But South Korean is waiting for a positive response from
North Korea he said.
   The minister flew to Washington for his appearance and was
returning to New York to prepare for the planned appearances of
both South and North Korea before the U.N. General Assembly.
</TEXT>
