<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea-USAttack     09-30 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-US Attack,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Hurl Firebombs At U.S. Army Headquarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters hurled firebombs into U.S.
Army headquarters in Seoul today and fled before riot police could
intervene, authorities said.
   Police and U.S. military authorities said the firebombs did not
cause any damage when they were hurled over a wall into a motor
pool at the headquarters of the 8th U.S. Army in a central district.
   South Korea has been hit by a burst of anti-American sentiment
provoked by several incidents during the Olympics. Radical students
have staged anti-American protests to try and play up the issue.
   Police said nine people were involved in the attack and police
officers chased the attackers, but failed to catch any of them.
   Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, said more than 20 youths
were involved in the incident and they appeared to be students. The
agency said four firebombs were hurled and the attackers left 15
more behind.
   A U.S. military spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said it was the second firebomb attack on U.S. military facilities
following a similar incident earlier this year. A window was broken
in the first incident.
   Shortly before the attack, police broke up a group of about 30
students from Dongguk University who scattered anti-American
leaflets near the U.S. base. Police arrested seven of the students
who scattered leaflets saying ``Punish the Yankees.''
   About 42,000 U.S. troops are based in South Korea under a mutual
defense treaty.
   About 50 students with firebombs and clubs later held a rally at
Dongguk to denounce the United States. They brandished the weapons
at riot police outside the school, but there was no clash and
students dispersed peacefully.
   A group of students presented a letter today to the U.S. Embassy
protesting the behavior of American athletes and journalists during
the Olympics.
   ``The incidents are clear evidence that Americans are slighting
the Korean people,'' the letter said.
   U.S. athletes and media have been criticized by some South
Koreans for their conduct during the Olympics, which end Sunday.
   South Korean newspapers have attacked NBC for its coverage of an
attack by South Korean boxing officials on a referee who awarded a
match against a local favorite. The lax conduct of the U.S. team at
the Games' opening ceremony and the arrest of three American
athletes have spurred further criticism.
   The United States and South Korea are close allies and the
government has moved to defuse the anti-American outbursts by
reminding Koreans of the close ties between the two nations.
</TEXT>
