<DOCNO> AP880930-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0516EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Addams     09-30 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Addams,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Yorker Cartoonist Who Inspired Addams Family TV Show Dies</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK _ Cartoonist Charles Addams, whose macabre characters
and morbid humor haunted the pages of The New Yorker magazine for
half a century and spawned ``The Addams Family'' TV show of the
1960s, has died. He was 76.
   Addams died Thursday in the emergency room at St. Clare's
Hospital and Health Center, said Mary Alice Gregg, a hospital
administrator.
   He suffered a heart attack in his car in front of his Manhattan
apartment building, said his wife, Marilyn.
   ``He's always been a car buff, so it was a nice way to go,''
said Mrs. Addams, who married her husband in a pet cemetery in 1980.
   ``He thought it would be nice and cheerful,'' she said of the
wedding.
   His first cartoon was published in The New Yorker in 1935, but
his first major one was published there on Jan. 13, 1940. It showed
a woman skier whose tracks passed neatly but inexplicably on both
sides of a large tree.
   ``I can't imagine the magazine without him,'' said Robert
Gottlieb, the magazine's editor.
   Addams, born in Westfield, N.J., doodled skulls and bones for
his high school newspaper before studying further at Colgate
University, the University of Pennsylvania and the Grand Central
School of Art in New York.
   His ghoulish characters, whose rundown Victorian mansion was
crowded with infernal devices and lurking creatures, was the
inspiration for ``The Addams Family'' television show of the 1960s.
   The Addamses, from Morticia the black-gowned matriarch, to Lurch
the giant butler and Thing, a hand that popped out of a box, were
directly inspired by Addams cartoons.
   Addams has produced 10 cartoon collections that have together
sold more than 460,000 copies.
   The New York Times art critic John Russell called Addams ``an
American landmark, one of the few by which one and all have learned
to steer.''
   But Russell said: ``Ghouls and ghosts are not the whole of
Addams. The jokes are so good that we do not notice the sturdiness
of the line, the rock-solid composition, the eye for scale and
placement, the calculated ordinariness that lures us into the
trap.''
   Some of Addams' cartoons take a moment to figure out.
   In one, a bus driver looks disquieted because the next stop
buzzer has just been pulled. After a moment, the reader usually
notices that the bus is approaching a rain-swept graveyard and no
one but the driver is on board.
   In another, four scouts cross a brook on a fallen tree carrying
a banner that says ``Beaver Patrol.'' Each of the scouts has buck
teeth and the reader is left to wonder whether the tree fell
because of beavers or the patrol.
   Although he profited immensely from his work, Addams said he did
not reap large direct benefits from the television show.
   ``They gave me money each week, but after the first runs ended I
didn't get anything. No residuals. This was a mistake made by the
big, old, fat law firm I let represent me,'' Addams once said.
   John O'Hara, a friend of Addams, said his drawings belied his
personality.
   ``I don't think he'd hurt a fly,'' he said. ``I never have seen
him lose his temper, although that is not to say he doesn't get
mad. He happens to be what is called easygoing, and has a decent
contempt for the opinions of mankind.''
   New Yorker spokeswoman Rhonda Pinzer said the magazine still has
some covers and cartoons that Addams had submitted, and probably
will run in the future.
   Mrs. Addams said the funeral would be private.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880930-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-WVaGovernor Bjt   09-30 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WVa Governor, Bjt,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>W.Va. Race Pits Three-Term Governor, Political Newcomer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A free-spending insurance executive
making his first bid for office holds a commanding lead over
three-term Republican Gov. Arch Moore, who has made a career of
overcoming political hardship.
   Gaston Caperton spent a record $2.1 million in the primary in a
state where fellow Democrat and former Gov. Jay Rockefeller made
deep-pocket politics common. He won't say how much he'll spend on
the general election.
   Moore has been unusually successful in a state where registered
Democrats have a 2-to-1 advantage, but a poll in late August and
early September gave Caperton a 60-31 percent lead, and many
Democrats whose support Moore needs expressed reluctance to cross
party lines again.
   In a speech earlier this month, Moore said the poll, conducted
for The Associated Press, Charleston Daily Mail and WSAZ-TV, gives
him ``one heck of a heartburn.'' But he called it an ``aberration.''
   A feisty campaigner who defies categorization as a conservative
or liberal, Moore often fares poorly in early polls. He trailed
John Raese early in the race for the GOP nomination this year and
still won, by a 53-47 percent margin.
   Caperton, whose McDonough Caperton Insurance Group is the
nation's 18th-largest insurance company, suggested Moore is in
trouble in this financially ailing state, where coal and other
backbone industries are in a slump.
   ``The story in the primary was not that Arch Moore came from
behind and won. The story is that an incumbent governor only got 53
percent of the vote,'' Caperton said.
   Moore, 65, has portrayed the 48-year-old Caperton as a rich kid
who's trying to buy the election, referring to him once as ``Cash
and Spend-a-ton.''
   But Moore also is spending freely, starting his TV advertising
in early summer, far before the traditional Labor Day start of the
political season. He spent $716,000 on the primary.
   Moore served six straight terms in Congress, then won election
as governor in 1968. In 1972, using a just-approved constitutional
amendment, he became the first West Virginia governor to succeed
himself, defeating Rockefeller.
   Before leaving office under a constitutional provision barring a
third straight term, Moore was indicted on charges of trying to get
a charter for a new bank in exchange for $25,000. He was acquitted.
   He lost a bid for the U.S. Senate in 1978 and lost the
governor's race to Rockefeller in 1980 before making a comeback in
1984 against Clyde See.
   Revenue during Moore's third term has slumped, and the governor
was forced to borrow $80 million this year to keep the state
running. West Virginia didn't send out its 1987 income tax refunds
until last week.
   Moore said the Democratic-controlled Legislature has rebuffed
many of his efforts to improve the economy. He maintains that the
state is in recovery, and his schedule is filled with plant
openings and announcements of grants.
   ``I don't think the people are going to be fooled by ribbon
cuttings,'' Capterton said. ``He cannot fool the people of West
Virginia that he's done a good job when the reality is different
from what it is in his ads.''
</TEXT>
