<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-30 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Shares Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices rebounded moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average recouped 223.67 points, or
0.81 percent, to close at 27,923.67. The index quickly gained
143.82 points to move to 27,843.98 shortly after the market opened
and gradually rose.
   The dollar finished the week's trading at 134.30 yen, down 0.05
yen from Thursday's close of 134.35 yen. The U.S. currency opened
higher at 134.57 yen before falling slightly, and it ranged between
134.25-134.60 yen.
   The dollar's strength on Wall Street boosted the currency in
Tokyo, but it did not rise further in thin trading. Traders stayed
on the sidelines because today was the last day of the first half
of the fiscal year, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   The release of Japanese trade figures today did not affect the
market, and the yen rose slightly toward the end of trading when
some investors sold dollars on profit-taking, the dealer said.
   The Finance Ministry said Japan's trade surplus for August
shrank to $5 billion from $6.5 billion.
   ``Share prices were higher almost across the board,'' said
Toshiyuki Nishiguchi with Daiwa Securities. ``Ever since the new
fiscal year started Tuesday, participants have been trading a wide
variety of issues,'' he said.
   ``Investors became optimistic because Japan's current economic
outlook is pretty good,'' Nishiguchi added.
   Trading was moderate with volume on the first section estimated
at 1 billion shares. Steel and shipbuilding stocks as well as
chemicals and oils that have been slow movers attracted
participants, Nishiguchi said.
</TEXT>
