<HEAD>ACLU Advertises To Defend Its Image</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union says
despite attacks by Vice President George Bush its only cause is the
Bill of Rights, and it will embark on a $250,000 effort to tell
Americans just that.
   Dan Goldberg, chairman of the ACLU Foundation of Southern
California, announced the campaign Thursday at a news conference
and played two commercials taped for the organization by actor Burt
Lancaster, who tells viewers: ``I have a confession to make. I'm a
card-carrying member of the ACLU.''
   The reference to being a ``card-carrying member'' is the same
one the George Bush has used to describe his Democratic rival for
the presidency, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis. Bush claims
Dukakis' ACLU membership shows how out of touch he was with
Americans.
   Dukakis has not defended the organization, even during last
Sunday's presidential debate. The day afterward his campaign issued
a list of ACLU positions with which he disagrees.
   Other commercials for the 68-year-old ACLU will be made next
week by Jill Eikenberry and Michael Tucker, the husband-and-wife
actors who portray married lawyers on the ``L.A. Law'' television
series.
