<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabyNaming     09-30 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Naming,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Challenges Rhode Island Policy On Surnames</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman separated from her husband has
sued the state, saying she shouldn't be forced to have a judge
determine the father of her 2{-year-old daughter before she can
choose the girl's last name.
   At stake in the lawsuit filed Thursday in U.S. District Court is
whether Betty Virella, who hasn't seen her husband in more than
seven years, can name her daughter Jacqueline after the girl's
father, James Aponte.
   Virella, 30, of Providence said the state Health Department has
refused to issue a birth certificate unless she agrees to use the
surname of her estranged husband, Victor Andino.
   ``I don't have a birth certificate for my daughter and she's 2{
years old now,'' Virella said. ``It's like Jacqueline is not in
this world.''
   Mary Ellen McCabe, the Health Department's chief legal counsel,
said the department seeks to protect the rights of the legal
father, who may not be the same as the biological father.
   Under Rhode Island law, a woman's husband is the legal father,
and her child must have the husband's surname unless there is a
court ruling that another man was the father, said McCabe, who
would not comment directly on Virella's case.
   Jean Rosiello, an American Civil Liberties Union attorney who
represents Virella, said Virella had not sought a court order on
paternity and should not be forced to do so.
   ``Our point is that whether she can afford the expense of going
to Family Court, she has the right to choose the name of her
child,'' Rosiello said.
   Virella, who uses her maiden name, said she had to produce
records showing she had been pregnant, had given birth and that the
child was still alive to enroll Jacqueline in Aid to Families with
Dependent Children.
   An expert on vital statistics said policies dictating a child's
surname are becoming rare.
   ``There are not that many states that do it anymore,'' said Mary
Anne Freedman, director of health statistics in Vermont and past
president of the Association for Vital Records and Health
Statistics.
   ``Over the course of the past 20 years, parents have been naming
their childen with surnames that bear no relation to either the
father's or mother's names,'' she said.
   In a 1986 letter to Women & Infants Hospital, where Jacqueline
was born, the Health Department said that if a mother is married at
conception or birth, ``the parents may give the child any name they
wish as long as both parents sign the worksheet.''
   Virella said she was worried her estranged husband could someday
claim custody if the child bore his name.
   The choice of a surname ``is a legal matter which has a lot of
bearing on the rights of the child,'' said George Gay, chief of
registration methods at the National Center for Health Statistics.
   In most states, a court order on paternity would be the easiest
way to clear up the situation, he said.
   Virella said she left Andino 12 years ago when she moved to New
York City from Puerto Rico. She said she last saw Andino, who still
lives in Puerto Rico, more than seven years ago.
   She said her other daughter, Jennifer, 4, was born in New York
City and was allowed to have Aponte's surname.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880930-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0724EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BridalRacer     09-30 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bridal Racer,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bridal Shop Owner Races Stock Cars at Night</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here comes The Bride.
   And there she goes, around the far curve and past the checkered
flag _ driven by Camille Connolly, bridal shop owner by day, stock
car racer by night.
   The Bride, a 1983 Mercury Capri, sports a 2-foot bride doll
peeking out her rear window. It's to remind spectators at Santa Fe
Speedway in suburban Hinsdale just who is behind the wheel.
   Connolly says her shop customers often are shocked when they
make the connection between the 5-foot-2, 110-pound woman who
designed their wedding gown and the helmeted figure rocketing into
a curve like some kind of speed demon.
   ``They say, `We could never picture anybody like you doing
something like that,''' she said. ``I guess I don't have dirt under
my fingernails, or something.''
   Connolly, 52, began racing in 1977 in a 14-year-old Lincoln
Continental that her husband had bought for $35 and painted pink.
   ``This was going to be a one-night thing _ let's all have a big
laugh,'' Connolly said.
   ``It's one of those things that just has snowballed. ... Maybe
we just got lucky. We both hit on something we really enjoy,'' said
her husband, Bob, a used-car dealer who maintains his wife's racing
car. ``It beats playing bingo.''
   Connolly started racing in ``Powder Puff'' races reserved for
women, but soon graduated to the more competitive Lightning Rod
class, where she finished third last season. Results from this
season's races still are being tallied, but she has won several
times.
   The Lightning Rod class is one in which few women venture and
fewer remain.
   ``Probably because they don't realize how competitive it is, or
their cars didn't hold up, or they were afraid,'' she said.
   But for her fear is no problem.
   ``With anything like this there's a risk,'' she said. ``But we
do a lot to protect me in the car.''
   Danger is half the fun, added her husband, who is confident his
maintenance of the car will keep her safe.
   ``It's like people who jump out of airplanes,'' he said.
``Everybody knows that the risk is there. It's part of the
magnetism of the sport.''
   That hasn't stopped the couple's five children, ages 23 to 29,
from worrying.
   ``When I go to the track they'll say `Mom, be careful,'''
Camille Connolly said. ``I used to say that to them when they
started driving.''
   She has the name of her suburban Berwyn bridal shop, which she
took over from her mother, painted across the back of her car. But
what grabs attention is the doll, which Connolly adorns with a new
bridal dress three or four times a year _ only to see it muddied
the first time out.
   ``Some races you can't see her face _ it's all covered in mud,''
she said.
   But other drivers don't seem to care whether Connolly owns a
bridal shop or a muffler shop.
   ``You ride around the track and you look in your mirror, and
there's Camille,'' said George Hayes, who has raced against
Connolly for seven years. ``You can't shake her. She's always
competitive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
