0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola-South Africa, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0509, a0526,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nations at Odds Over Cuban Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `In Kinshasa ...,' with 1 graf to CORRECTLY
identify ``Pik'' Botha as foreign minister, not prime minister.
PICKS up 10th graf, `The meeting ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa and Angola could accept a
withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola within 24 months, but Cuba
wants more time, sources at U.S.-mediated talks said.
   As a result of the disagreement, the talks, which began Monday
with high expectations, ended Thursday without an agreement, the
sources said.
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, they said delegations from
South Africa and Angola appeared to back the 24-month withdrawal
plan. Cuban diplomats demanded more time, the sources said.
   A communique from the negotiating teams in this central African
city said a new meeting would be scheduled again here at an
unspecified date.
   The timetable for withdrawal of the estimated 50,000 Cuban
troops again was the obstacle to an agreement, the sources said.
   South Africa withdrew its troops from Angola under a cease-fire
negotiated during the talks. It had demanded withdrawal of Cuban
troops within 12 months if it was to go ahead with its stated aimed
of granting independence to South-West Africa, Angola's southern
neighbor.
   Angola and Cuba initially demanded four years for the withdrawal.
   The communique released after the Brazzaville talks said the
participants would recommend to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar that plans for independence for South-West Africa, also
called Namibia, go ahead.
   In Kinshasa, Zaire, President Mobutu Sese Seko said today he
would meet with South African President P.W. Botha on Saturday in
Gdabo-Lite, his ancestral village in northern Zaire, to discuss
peace initiatives for southern Africa. South African Foreign
Minister Roelof ``Pik'' Botha was also to fly there for the talks,
which South Africa had requested, according to Zaire government
sources.
   The meeting was being billed as part of an African-led
initiative to negotiate an end to the Angolan civil war.
   U.S. diplomats had clearly hoped the Brazzaville talks would end
in a peace agreement which would clear the way for Angola's Marxist
government to begin talks with its anti-Marxist guerrillas.
   President Reagan told the United Nations on Monday that an
agreement that would result in the Cubans withdrawing from Angola
was near.
</TEXT>
