<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-CornToxin     09-30 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Corn Toxin,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testing Shows Presence of Toxin in Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A toxin produced by mold that is common
in corn during drought has been found in this year's Illinois corn
crop, preliminary test results indicate.
   State Agriculture Department officials said Thursday that 34
percent of the samples analyzed have been found to have aflatoxin
in levels higher than the federal Food and Drug Administration
permits without restricting use.
   Mark Randal, a spokesman for the state agency, said none of the
samples tested so far has shown levels higher than allowed for
restricted use by the FDA.
   He said corn prices shouldn't be affected if the levels stay
within the range allowed for restricted use.
   There are no restrictions on corn that contains less than 20
parts per billion of the toxin, he said.
   Randal said the FDA has issued temporary standards that limit
corn with aflatoxin levels ranging from 20 parts per billion to 100
parts per billion to use as feed for mature livestock such as beef
cattle, swine or poultry.
   The department so far has tested 58 of the 327 samples collected
from across the state by grain inspectors.
   ``A true indicator of statewide aflatoxin trends will not be
possible until all of those samples have been analyzed,'' according
to a department statement.
</TEXT>
