<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-Soviet     09-30 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Soviet,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Businessmen To Visit Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwan business organization will send
an 80-member delegation to the Soviet Union next week in the first
such visit to the communist nation, a trade leader said today.
   Lin Tzy-ching, chairman of the Taiwan Importers and Exporters
Association, said the private group planned to buy raw materials
from Moscow and promote sales of Taiwan products to the Soviets.
   The visit has been sanctioned by the government, Lin said.
   ``We will see how good business opportunities are in the Soviet
Union and make suggestions to the government,'' he said.
   The group will leave Monday for Bangkok where it will fly to
Moscow for a 14-day visit, he added.
   Taiwan still bans direct trade with Soviet Union and Albania.
However, authorities have said this island's economic policies
should be independent from the government's anti-communist stance.
   Earlier this year, the Taiwan government announced measures to
encourage trade with seven East European countries, easing
restrictions and permitting direct imports of consumer goods from
East Germany, Poland, Hungary, Romania, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia
and Yugoslavia.
   Industrialists have long urged the government to allow direct
trade with the Soviet Union, noting indirect trade with the Soviets
has accounted for more than half the total trade with East Europe.
   Last year, Taiwan's exports to East Europe totaled $7.5 million,
nearly double that of 1986. Imports from East European countries
totaled $190 million, a 119 percent increase from 1986.
</TEXT>
