<HEAD>Small Plane Crashes In Hudson River; Three Aboard Hitch To
Hospital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lead to clarify; UPDATES with plane's itinerary.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EDGEWATER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane with three people aboard
crashed into the Hudson River near here, but the three were able to
swim ashore and hitch a ride to a hospital, officials said.
   The crash occurred late Thursday a few miles north of the George
Washington Bridge to New York City, officials said.
   The woman and two men walked into Palisades General Hospital's
emergency room around 10 p.m. and said they had hitched a ride in a
van, according to Tom Urban, the hospital's assistant vice
president.
   Police say the plane, a single-engine Cessna 172, was rented at
a Teterboro airport and originally was headed to Atlantic City. But
the pilot had changed direction and headed north to the Hudson
River for a sightseeing trip when the aircraft lost power about 200
yards off Edgewater, according to police.
   The three suffered abrasions.
   The woman also was treated for exposure and released from the
hospital early today, said Diane Pollock, a hospital spokeswoman.
The men were held for observation, she said.
