<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-MortonThiokol     09-30 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Morton Thiokol,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Sees Launch As First Step To Rebuilding Reputation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The performance of Morton Thiokol's
booster rockets as they helped lift the space shuttle Discovery
into orbit drew cheers of relief from proud employees who saw it as
a first step toward rebuilding the company's reputation.
   ``Reputations are very fragile. Once they are damaged, it takes
a long time to fix them,'' said Dick Davis, vice president. ``The
way to put them back together is to have successful launches,''
   Employees at the rocket-maker's Wasatch Operations 25 miles west
of here erupted in cheers as they watched the launch on television
monitors. The jubilant scene Thursday was in stark contrast to 32
months before when a faulty seal on a Morton Thiokol booster caused
Challenger's destruction and grounded the nation's manned space
program.
   Morton Thiokol was held partly to blame for the accident. At one
point in the launch deliberations, a company official was ordered
to take off his engineering hat and put on his management hat.
Senior managers then overrode the objections of some engineers to a
cold-weather launch.
   Thursday, hundreds of Morton Thiokol officials and engineers
were at Cape Canaveral for the launch. Reporters were barred from
company premises in Utah, in part so employees could watch the
launch in private, said spokesman Rocky Raab.
   Davis spoke by telephone to the company's Utah employees minutes
after launch.
   ``I really want to thank the 3,000 people in Utah who put
themselves into the program and worked so hard, working in a
fishbowl environment on the booster,'' Davis said. ``There was a
very definite sense of relief and pride that our motors had
worked.''
   In the wake of the Challenger disaster, Morton Thiokol
redesigned its booster, the largest solid-fuel rocket ever built,
at a cost of $500 million. Most changes were aimed at improving the
critical joint seals.
   ``When you work on a program as long as we have, whenever a
space shuttle flies it does bring a tear to your eye,'' said Mike
Ayers, director of finance for space operations. ``Any space
shuttle launch is an emotional experience, especially for the
employees that worked so hard to put the shuttle back into flight.''
   Mel Rogers, who works on the booster's nozzles, said that if
something had gone wrong Thursday, ``I'd have had to move.''
   ``It felt good to hit something positive for once,'' Rogers
said. ``The things are hard enough to make, let alone be
criticized.''
   Thursday's launch was hailed by Brigham City Mayor Peter
Knudson. Most of Morton Thiokol's 8,000 Utah employees live in and
around his city.
   The mayor, a dentist, did not watch the launch because he was
with a patient. When informed by a reporter it was a success he
struggled to speak.
   ``That's fantastic. I'm near tears. It's a very emotional moment
for me. I've personally lived with this for so long. I just can't
tell you what this means to me,'' Knudson said.
   Wes Boman, Brigham City Chamber of Commerce director, said that
while the shuttle program was on hold, there was a sense of anxiety
in the town. Residents put off large purchases and the housing
market went at a slower pace, he said.
   Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah, who experienced a seven-day space flight
aboard Discovery in April 1985, attended Thursday's launch.
   ``It was hot down there in Florida, but I had goose bumps and
was crying,'' Garn said after returning to Washington. ``I really
would like to go up again...''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
