<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrushFires     09-30 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brush Fires,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wind-Whipped Blazes Scorch More Than 10,000 Acres</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters battling an
arson-set blaze that has burned more than 10,000 acres of mountain
brush and destroyed two homes got a break today as hot, dry winds
died down.
   ``Things are looking pretty good,'' California Department of
Forestry spokeswoman Kathy Reiboldt said early today as winds
calmed to 5 mph from as high as 60 mph Thursday.
   But she cautioned, ``If the winds come up again, we could be in
trouble.''
   Elsewhere, the forecast called for little wind and warm, dry
weather at Yellowstone National Park, and officials said more snow
will be needed to extinguish the three fires still burning there.
   ``Containment is dependent upon weather conditions at this
point,'' park spokeswoman Sandi Robinson said Thursday.
   The number of firefighters in the park has dropped to 1,841 from
a peak of more than 9,600 on Sept. 5, and Robinson said the number
will continue to drop gradually.
   The 10,660-acre Texas fire in the San Gabriel Mountains about 55
miles east of downtown Los Angeles was 60 percent contained early
today, Ms. Reiboldt said. She would not make any prediction on when
the fire would be extinguished.
   More than 1,000 firefighters aided by 10 air tankers and
helicopters were battling the blaze, one of 30 arson-caused fires
in the area in recent months.
   Three people were injured including two prison inmates on a
firefighting crew who suffered minor burns. A resident also was
treated for smoke inhalation Wednesday, Ms. Reiboldt said.
   The fire destroyed two homes and some chicken coops Thursday,
and winds ripping through mountain canyons pushed the flames toward
1,800 homes near the town of Etiwanda and within 100 yards of
evacuated Summit Elementary School. The school remained closed
today but about 150 residents who were forced to evacuate Thursday
morning were allowed to return to their homes in the afternoon,
state Department of Forestry spokeswoman Mary Grisamore said.
   A 670-acre fire in Glen Helen that had been started by
firefighters to destroy overgrown brush was contained at 6 p.m.
Thursday. The fire had roared out of control when the winds picked
up.
</TEXT>
