<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Britain     09-30 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Britain,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Cancels Visit at Polish Request</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of
Britain has postponed a three-day visit to Poland at the request of
Polish authorities, who are forming a new government, a government
spokesman said today.
   Parliament named Mieczyslaw Rakowski as prime minister on
Tuesday. Rakowski immediately asked for two weeks to form a new
government to be presented for approval to the parliament on Oct.
13 and 14.
   Thatcher was scheduled to visit Poland from Oct. 16 to 18.
   ``The Polish authorities asked the British side to postpone the
date because of the reconstruction of the government,'' said
assistant government spokesman Ryszard Strauss.
   No new dates have been announced, but the spokesman said the
visit would still take place.
   ``I don't think it is going to be that far away. It is just a
question of fitting the schedule of both sides,'' he said.
   On the final day of her visit, Thatcher planned to travel to
Gdansk, the birthplace of the banned Solidarity trade union
movement. She was scheduled to set a wreathe with Polish leader
Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski at a monument commemorating the outbreak
of World War II.
   Later she was to meet with Soldarity leader Lech Walesa before
returning to London.
   The state-controlled press did not directly attack the planned
meeting with Walesa, but it printed letters from the British press
criticizing the meeting as well as calls from Labor Party officials
urging her not to meet Walesa.
</TEXT>
