<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DyingDaughter-Arrest     09-30 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dying Daughter-Arrest,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Arrested After Struggling With Officers To Reach Dying
Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of one of five victims of a house fire
was arrested as he tried to reach an ambulance where his dying
2-year-old daughter was being treated, police and witnesses say.
   Dallas police said Thursday they wrestled Homer Hutchins to the
ground and placed him in a neck restraining hold after he illegally
parked his truck and tried to break away from two officers to reach
his daughter.
   Hutchins, 19, was arrested because ``he had refused to calm
himself'' and ``fought them violently'' as he tried to reach his
daughter, Jasmas Jordan, according to the arrest report. He was
charged with obstructing a police roadway.
   ``They had him in handcuffs while his daughter was dying. That
has to hurt,'' said Hutchins' brother, Jimmie Hutchins. ``You think
he won't carry that with him every day for the rest of his life?''
   Also killed in the fire were the girl's mother; a sister of the
mother; and a brother and sister of Hutchins.
   Investigators said Thursday that arson was the cause of the fire
and said they were looking into reports that the blaze might have
been set as an act of revenge against one of the victims.
   An internal investigation also has been ordered by Police Chief
Mack Vines to determine whether departmental procedure was violated
by officers who prevented Hutchins from reaching his daughter.
   Southeast Patrol Division Sgt. Steve Umlor would not comment on
the arrest but said in general, a police officer's role at a fire
is to make sure civilians do not interfere with firefighters or run
into burning buildings.
   The father told the Dallas Times Herald he arrived at the
burning house about 5 a.m., parked his truck in the street and was
running toward the house when he was grabbed by two officers who
told him to move his truck.
   ``I said, `My daughter's in there,''' Hutchins said. ``They said
I still had to move my truck.''
   When officers refused to let Hutchins beyond the police line, he
tried to run between them, but they wrestled him to the ground, he
said. He was arrested and released 30 minutes later.
</TEXT>
