<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SovietInspectors     09-30 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Inspectors,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Depart After Checking Missile Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet missile experts completed
their inspection of a U.S. military base from which nuclear
missiles were recently removed and left West Germany today, the
U.S. Air Force said.
   It was the third Soviet group to inspect U.S. missile bases in
West Germany to verify compliance with the Intermediate Nuclear
Forces treaty. The treaty called for the scrapping of all
intermediate-range nuclear missiles.
   The 10-man team took off from Frankfurt's Rhein-Main Air Base,
Air Force spokesman Sgt. Larry Clavette told The Associated Press.
They had been in West Germany since Tuesday.
   The Soviet team performed what the superpower treaty terms
``short-notice inspections.''
   Both the Soviet Union and the United States have the right to
conduct 20 such inspections each year, giving 16 hours' notice.
   The Soviets inspected a U.S. military base at Heilbronn, near
Stuttgart, from which nine Pershing 2 missiles were removed on
Sept. 1.
   It was the first removal of nuclear missiles from West Germany
under the terms of the treaty.
</TEXT>
