<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Roces     09-30 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Roces,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prominent Philippine Newspaper Publisher Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joaquin ``Chino'' Roces, a prominent
newspaper publisher who persuaded Corazon Aquino to run for
president, died today of complications from cancer, his doctor
announced. He was 75.
   The doctor, Cynthia Dominquez, said Roces was admitted to a
hospital Sept. 13 for treatment of a pulmonary infection.
   Roces, dean of the Philippine press corps, launched a campaign
in 1985 to solicit 1 million signatures on a petition asking Mrs.
Aquino to run against President Ferdinand Marcos in February 1986.
   Mrs. Aquino, the wife of slain opposition leader Benigno Aquino
Jr., at first rejected all suggestions that she run, saying she
knew nothing about being president. The signature drive changed her
mind, and Mrs. Aquino went on to claim victory in the election Feb.
7, 1986.
   Protests of massive fraud triggered the civilian-military
uprising that toppled the Marcos administration on Feb. 25, 1986
and forced him to flee to exile in Hawaii.
   Roces left journalism in 1972 when Marcos closed The Manila
Times, then the Philippines' largest newspaper, and other media
when he declared eight years of martial law.
   The Manila Times resumed publication after Mrs. Aquino took
office. Because of family differences, Roces first served as
publisher of The Manila Chronicle from 1986 until this year, when
he returned to The Manila Times.
   Roces came from one of Manila's oldest and wealthiest families.
   As publisher of The Manila Times, he was among an elite group
known as the ``kingmakers'' because of the influence they exerted
over officials and politicians.
   Roces gave Benigno Aquino his first job as a correspondent for
The Manila Times during the Korean War after the young Aquino
promised to pay his own fare to Korea.
   Despite failing health, the wiry chain-smoker led street
demonstrations against Marcos that were frequently broken up with
tear gas and club-carrying police.
   Roces remained a strong supporter of Mrs. Aquino. But last July,
he lectured the president about the alleged failure of her
administration to stamp out corruption and bring ``justice'' in the
wake of the Marcos era.
   Roces is survived by his wife, Pacita, and two sons, Joaquin
Jr., and Edgardo. His daughter, Rocio, died in a landslide in 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
