<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Abrahamson     09-30 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abrahamson,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Star Wars Head Wants Freedom to Defend Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The departing head of the Star Wars research
program said today he decided to leave that job in order to be free
to come to the defense of the project.
   The retirement of Lt. Gen. James A. Abrahamson was announced
earlier this week by the Pentagon.
   Abrahamson said on ABC TV's ``Good Morning America'' that the
new administration to be elected in November _ whichever candidate
wins _ will undoubtedly want to re-assess many programs, including
the Strategic Defense Initiative, the formal name for Star Wars.
   ``When it's re-examined with a new administration, no matter
who, I believe that I'll be in the best position to explain the
progress of the program, the promise of the program, if people
think that I'm not fighting for my job,'' Abrahamson said.
   Asked the effect of suggestions by Democratic presidential
candidate Michael Dukakis that Star Wars spending should be cut to
$1 billion a year, about one-fourth of the current level,
Abrahamson responded:
   ``I think that would have a tragic result. It would
fundamentally erase the real progress that we've made.''
   ``The important thing is that he and other critics around the
country feel that research should go ahead,'' Abrahamson added.
   ``That's a fundamental reaffirmation. The fact that they may not
feel they need to put the amount of money into it is perhaps a lack
of understanding of the promise of the program and the progress.''
   As for Republican George Bush, Abrahamson said that ``the vice
president understands the program. He has been strongly committed,
he has given both his moral (support) and his support in the
government.''
   In the next administration, the program needs to be represented
well, he said, and ``I'd like to make that argument without people
thinking that I'm trying to enhance my own personal position.''
   Abrahamson, who took command of the Star Wars program in 1984,
will be succeeded by Lt. Gen. George L. Monahan Jr.
</TEXT>
