<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BaggageBomb     09-30 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baggage Bomb,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Leave Powerful Explosive in Couple's Suitcase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airline will no longer allow unclaimed luggage
to be used by police to train bomb-sniffing dogs after a stick of
powerful explosives was inadvertently left in a couple's suitcase.
   Police, who say the stick of ammonium nitrate gel could not have
exploded without a blasting cap, have apologized to Gregorio and
Esther Martinez of Miami.
   ``We admit our mistake and apologize to the family for the
inconvenience and scare they had,'' said Detective Al Hidalgo-Gato,
a Metro-Dade spokesman. ``For all they knew, they had a real bomb.
... This had never happened before.''
   Eastern Airlines officials tracked down the couple after they
found their suitcase, which had been left behind at Miami
International Airport earlier this month.
   Mrs. Martinez discovered the explosive when she opened the
suitcase at home.
   If exploded, the bomb was powerful enough to have blown up the
couple's home and damaged two homes nearby, police said.
   Eastern Airlines spokesman Robin Matell said the carrier will
continue to cooperate with the training exercises, but will no
longer provide lost luggage. Instead, the airline will use dummy
suitcases for the tests.
   During a training session Tuesday, officers apparently failed to
retrieve the explosive when they cleared the area, Matell said.
   ``The luggage was used with the understanding it had been
unclaimed for some time,'' said police spokeswoman Lucy Fitts.
   The explosive was slightly larger than a highway flare and
marked ``High Explosives.''
   ``I was scared,'' Mrs. Martinez said. She gingerly placed the
device on her dresser, then waited for her husband to come home.
   ``I said, `Look what I found,''' Mrs. Martinez said.
   ``That's a bomb!'' her husband cried, snatching the device from
the dresser and taking it out to the back yard before calling
police.
   Metro-Dade officials will review training procedures in the wake
of the incident, Matell added.
   The K-9 unit's weekly training exercises are required by the
Federal Aviation Administration.
</TEXT>
