<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSConference     09-30 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Conference,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Second Wave' of AIDS Infection May Hit Gay Community, Official
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Because AIDS is more easily spread the
longer a person is infected with the disease, a ``second wave'' of
AIDS infection may hit the homosexual population, a public health
official warns.
   Participants at the three-day Second National AIDS Conference
were also told Thursday that AIDS prevention and education programs
aimed at minority groups will have to come from within the minority
community to be effective.
   Efforts to stop transmission among the gay community need to be
intensified, said George Rutherford, medical director of the AIDS
office in the San Francisco Public Health Department.
   AIDS is more easily spread the longer a person has been infected
with the virus, he said. Because the disease has been present in
the San Francisco gay community for almost eight years, the number
of victims in the terminal phase of the disease is increasing.
   ``The risk to gay men per episode of intercourse may be
increasing,'' said Rutherford, adding that failure to practice safe
sex may represent a ``substantially greater risk'' as the
population ages.
   ``This is no time to have a 10 percent failure rate,'' he
emphasized.
   More than 1,200 people attended the first day of the conference,
which is designed to provide local public health officials and
community health advocates with an exchange of information on how
best to fight the epidemic.
   Minority communities lack the financial resources and volunteer
time that have marked the gay community's response to the crisis,
Patricia Evans, branch chief of education and prevention in the
AIDS Office of the San Francisco Department of Public Health, said
at the conference.
   One-third of blacks live in poverty, she said, adding that it's
``very difficult for those individuals to volunteer when they are
trying to take care of the basic necessities of life.''
   To be successful, AIDS prevention and education programs aimed
at minority groups will have to ``come from within that
community,'' Evans said.
   The Centers for Disease Control reported this week that 74,447
cases of AIDS have been diagnosed since 1981. A total of 41,925
people had died of the disease.
   Rutherford said a total of 365,000 AIDS cases are expected by
the end of 1992. More than 263,000 people will have died by then,
he said.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a generally
deadly virus that devastates the body's immune system, leaving
sufferers susceptible to infections and cancer. Gay men and
intravenous drug users have been the primary victims of the
epidemic.
</TEXT>
