   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) _ NASA, criticized in the Challenger
investigation for routinely granting waivers to its own safety
guidelines, bent its standards again to launch Discovery into
lighter-than-expected winds.
   ``The team threaded the needle without violating any rules,
without backing off any of our safety criteria,'' NASA shuttle
director Richard Truly said on ABC today.
   ``The winds did not violate our safety factor,'' said Thomas
Utsman, deputy director of the Kennedy Space Center. But he
confirmed that launching in those conditions did require a waiver
of launch rules.
   ``It wasn't taken lightly,'' he said. ``It was not a result of a
judgment, but a refined engineering analysis.''
   Truly said he wasn't completely confident of a Thursday launch.
   ``I wasn't at all sure we were going to lift off until we got to
T-minus-zero (the end of the countdown,'' he said. ``You know, even
coming out of the nine-minute hold there are thousands of parts of
the hardware and software to check and the engines as they come up
to speed. So, until we lit those solids (the booster rockets), I
wasn't confident that we were going to go.''
