<HEAD>PM-Student Riot,0220</HEAD>
<HEAD>Student Leaders Accuse Police Of Excessive Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Student leaders say police broke up
demonstrations at two universities by firing tear gas and beating
up demonstrators. The students were protesting alleged high-level
corruption in the government.
   By today, police had freed most of the 478 students arrested in
the protests Thursday at the University of Zimbabwe and the Harare
Polytechnic.
   Witnesses said students began hurling stones at police when they
were barred from leaving the two campuses to carry their protests
through the streets of dowtown Harare.
   Student leaders told The Associated Press the paramilitary units
fired tear gas and rubber bullets and beat others with batons. They
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Hospital officials reported surgical teams worked late Thursday
night treating injured students, mainly for cuts and bruises.
   Several thousand students began demonstrating early Thursday at
the two institutions to protest alleged corruption among cabinet
ministers, leaders of the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union
(Patriotic Front) and bureaucrats.
   They marched with banners saying ``National Looters Must Go''
and ``Weed Out Political Thieves.''
   President Robert Mugabe was visiting Britain at the time.
   In previous demonstrations against South Africa's racial
policies students have set fire to cars, smashed office windows and
beaten up shoppers and workers.
