<HEAD>Hundreds Attend Funeral for Slain Gunman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 700 people paid their last respects at the
funeral of a Vietnam veteran who was shot to death by a policeman
after killing another officer and three other people near a school.
   ``He wasn't as messed up as people thought,'' said a niece of
the slain gunman, Clem Henderson, 40.
   ``The media didn't really get to the true Clem,'' said the
niece, Brenda Robinson, 29. ``He was always supportive to family.
He was active in painting (church murals), and he was active in the
community.''
   A folded American flag lay next to the body of Henderson.
   Henderson had a history of strange behavior and arrests before
the Sept. 23 shooting spree, which began at an auto parts store.
   The store's manager and an employee were killed, along with a
custodian at the nearby Montefiore School for troubled boys, before
Henderson encountered two police officers at the school's door.
Officer Irma Ruiz was killed before her partner, Gregory Jaglowski,
shot and killed Henderson in an exchange of gunfire. Jaglowski was
wounded in the legs.
   At Mrs. Ruiz's funeral Monday, the Rev. James Maloney told
mourners that anger over the killings perhaps should be directed
``at those who are cutting and continue to cut resources for our
mentally ill.
   ``Perhaps that is what killed Irma, because there was a person
(Henderson) who needed more help, more love and more understanding
than our institutions provided him,'' Maloney said.
   Ms. Robinson said her uncle was basically a good man.
   ``He just kept trying to get out of the ghetto,'' she said,
``but he just kept winding up there again and again.''
   The service at the House of Branch funeral home was attended by
about 700 people, said funeral director L.C. Branch. Burial was
scheduled for today.
