<HEAD>Mother Says Adams Propositioned Her; Tests In Daughter's Case
Showed No Sexual Activity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP 10 grafs new to include comments from mother and sister,
move up Adams' denial; picks up 3rd graf pvs, They also, deleting
pvs grafs 10-12, Adams has.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a 26-year-old woman who accuses
Sen. Brock Adams of sexual assault says Adams earlier made a pass
at her, while newly released police records in the daughter's case
show no medical evidence of sexual activity or drugs.
   Sylvia Tupper, mother of Kari Tupper who has accused Adams,
D-Wash., of drugging and then sexually assaulting her during an
overnight stay in his Washington home, said Adams propositioned her
in 1986, the Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported today.
   The incident occurred during a period when she had lunch with
him several times with her husband's knowledge, the newspaper
quoted Mrs. Tupper as saying. Adams and Mrs. Tupper have been
friends since they both were in student government at the
University of Washington 40 years ago.
   Kari Tupper's sister, Kathie Buckham of Seattle, said Thursday
night that Tupper first told her Adams had made a sexual advance
toward her after a 1985 fund-raiser.
   On the night in question, March 27, 1987, Ms. Tupper said she
had accepted an invitation to go to a restaurant with Adams after
she plotted a strategy to tell the senator to stop propositioning
her.
   ``I knew the dinner was going to take place ... the motives
behind it,'' Mrs. Buckham said. ``We rehearsed it, how she was
going to say it.''
   Adams has denied he made any sexual advances toward Ms. Tupper
and said she came to his house to discuss her search for a job in
Washington. He contends Tupper tried to blackmail him for $400,000.
   But Adams said he made a mistake by letting Tupper, a longtime
family friend, spend the night at his house when his wife was out
of town.
   Adams issued a statement to reporters about the episode on
Tuesday. He did not accept questions and has refused further
comment.
   Police records released Thursday in response to a Freedom of
Information Act request were compiled as part of the District of
Columbia police department's investigation into Kari Tupper's
allegations against Adams.
   They also indicate that prosecutors declined to charge Adams in
part because ``there were problems with the victim's credibility.''
   The record also shows there were apparently questions raised
about ``medical and physical corroboration.''
   The police file contains a detective's interview with Tupper and
others, reports from two hospitals and a statement reflecting the
decision of the U.S. attorney's office.
   Much of the file is blacked out to protect the witnesses'
privacy.
   Tupper, a former secretary on Capitol Hill, made a complaint
against Adams in July 1987, nearly four months after she claimed
that Adams put a drug in her drink, took her to bed and fondled her
on the night of March 27, 1987, and the next morning.
   That morning Tupper went to the Arlington Hospital in suburban
Virginia for tests. Those tests proved negative for sperm or an
enzyme found in semen, the record shows. A urine-analysis
drug-screening test found only traces of anti-inflammatory drugs.
   Three days later Tupper admitted herself for an examination by
doctors at George Washington University Medical Center, claiming
she had been sexually assaulted. A test for semen was not performed.
   Joseph DiGenova, the U.S. attorney at the time, said in an
interview that the case was handled in a routine fashion by
prosecutors who determined it had ``absolutely no merit whatsoever
_ zero, zip _ it was nothing.''
   Tupper, who is now married, has been unavailable for comment
since the Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported the story early in
the week. But her father, Dr. James Tupper, said his family feels
betrayed by Adams.
   ``Kari trusted and respected this man,'' the woman's father said
on Wednesday. ``She never believed he would try to hurt or take
advantage of her.''
   Tupper claimed in her interview with Detective Patrick Shine
that Adams had made sexual advances towards her nearly two years
before March 27, 1987. On that night, she wanted to get together
with Adams to ask him to stop ``harassing me and making me feel
uncomfortable at receptions,'' the police report said.
   Adams has said Tupper wanted to talk about her employment.
   Adams and Tupper were supposed to meet at a restaurant, but
Adams did not show up because her office had told him she was ill
that day. When Tupper called his house, Adams invited her over,
Tupper said.
   After three drinks, Tupper said she went to the bathroom feeling
nauseated. That was the last thing she recalled, she said.
   ``The next thing that I know for sure happened was that I woke
up in the morning between 6 and 6:30. ... I did not have my clothes
on. ... He was laying down on my side and he was laying behind
me,'' she said.
   ``I remember him touching my bare breast and buttocks and I
tried to sit up and he was pulling me back down into the bed with
him,'' she said. ``He was turning me over to face him and he was
kissing me on the lips. He was continuing to touch me. I was
crying,'' she said.
   After leaving Adams' house, Tupper said, she had trouble driving
home. She later went to the airport to meet friends who took her to
the hospital for the tests.
</TEXT>
