<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TraciLords     09-30 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Traci Lords,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Producers Can Argue Porn Actress Used Fake Birth Certificate,
Court Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two film producers charged with child
pornography can argue that a 16-year-old actress used a phony birth
certificate and other papers that said she was over 18, an appeals
court has ruled.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals voted 2-1 Thursday to
reject a government appeal that the producers of ``Those Young
Girls,'' starring actress Traci Lords, not be allowed to use a
``mistake defense'' when they go to trial.
   The producers have argued they didn't know Lords was only 16
when they filmed the movie.
   Beverly Hills attorney John Weston, who represents the
producers, called the ruling a ``very important opinion and very
important result'' reflecting constitutional guarantees of freedom
of speech and due process.
   The government went to the 9th Circuit after a U.S. district
judge in Los Angeles refused in a pretrial hearing to dismiss the
charge or strike down the law, but ruled that the producers could
be acquitted if they could prove they reasonably believed Lords was
an adult.
   Producers Ronald Kantor and Rupert Macnee, along with talent
agent James Souter Jr., were charged with violating a federal law
against production of materials that show a juvenile in sexually
explicit conduct. The crime carries a penalty of up to 10 years in
prison and a $100,000 fine.
   Souter pleaded guilty but his attorney said he planned to
withdraw his plea if Kantor and Macnee got a favorable ruling.
   Attorneys for the defendants have said Lords showed them a
genuine-looking birth certificate and state identification card
that indicated she was over 18. They also said they relied on
Lords' sophisticated appearance and demeanor.
   The two-judge majority said the First Amendment is as close to
an absolute as exists in United States jurisprudence and ``distaste
we may feel as individuals toward the content or message of
protected expression'' shouldn't sway the courts.
   The decision, written by Judge Alex Kozinski, cited a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling striking down an ordinance imposing criminal
penalties on a bookseller for possession of an obscene book, saying
knowledge of the alleged obscenity was required. Not allowing a
reasonable mistake of age defense, the 9th Circuit said, would
result in a chilling effect on free speech.
   Lords, an Ohio runaway, has appeared in more than 100 adult
videos and films.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880930-0084 </DOCNO>
