<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba Crash,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Plane Crashes Into Mountain in Cuba, Six Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Piper aircraft carrying Spanish travel agents
from the Dominican Republic to Havana smashed into a mountain in
southeastern Cuba, killing all six people aboard, Havana Radio
reported today.
   The wreckage from Thursday night's crash was found in a heavily
wooded area near the city of Santiago de Cuba, hampering recovery
of the bodies, according to the report monitored in Miami.
   The passengers were identified as Carlos San Basilio, president
of Iberia Transmediterranean Co.; his wife Carmen, and company
executives Guillermo Garcia Velasco, Javier Isogrudo Alsona and
Carmen Vidal.
   The pilot was identified as Eli Rodriquez of the Dominican
Republic.
   The Spanish ambassador flew from Havana to inspect the crash
scene, the report said.
   The small aircraft had refueled at Santiago de Cuba and had
taken off to fly on to Havana when the pilot asked permission for
an emergency landing, the broadcast said. It did not give a cause
for the accident, but said the terrain around the airport might
have contributed to the crash.
   ``The Santiago de Cuba airport is considered one of the most
difficult to reach because it is encircled by mountains,'' said the
broadcast.
</TEXT>
