<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0553,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>76 Killed in Burma Violence, Communist Attacks Reported Repelled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 4 beginning `By official ...' to CLARIFY official
death toll. Picks up graf 5 pvs, `The new ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government forces killed at least 76
people in suppressing unrest this week and today recaptured Chinese
border outposts overrun by communist rebels who back the protests,
a government spokesman said.
   Also today, a representative of rebels of the Karen ethnic
minority said nearly 2,000 students and others have fled to areas
under their control along the Thai-Burmese border. The
anti-government refugees hope to receive military training at Karen
bases.
   Kyaw Sann, a spokesman for the military government, said from
Tuesday to Thursday that 76 people were killed as the government
put down unrest. He said 24 others were wounded and 269 were
arrested.
   By official count, at least 425 people have been killed since
hardline Gen. Saw Maung seized power Sept. 18 and ordered troops to
quell pro-democracy demonstrations throughout the country. The
government says some of those killed were looters.
   The new government has promised multiparty general elections.
But opposition leaders have urged people to continue a general
strike begun Aug. 8 and fight the government through other peaceful
means.
   Anti-government unrest has swelled this year against
military-backed one-party rule. The latest wave began in July when
it forced Ne Win from power after 26 years.
   Kyaw Sann also told a news conference that three army outposts
that fell to rebels of the outlawed Burma Communist Party were
recaptured today with support from air strikes.
   One week ago, more than 1,500 insurgents attacked and occupied
positions at Lamingone, Yanshingone and Payagone near the Chinese
border about 340 miles northeast of Rangoon. Clashes in the area
killed at least 131 rebels with 48 government troops dead and
another 104 wounded, the government spokesman said.
   Kyaw Sann said government troops were still carrying out
mopping-up operations against the rebels, who have an estimated
total of 20,000 fighters.
   The Burma Communist Party earlier issued a statement supporting
the popular pro-democracy uprising. But it was not clear if the
reported attacks were designed to take pressure off the protesters.
   Asked about arrests of students, who spearheaded the protests,
Kyaw Sann said 86 remained in custody. Some students who fled to
Karen outposts said they saw authorities execute protesters.
   The Karen are among a dozen ethnic groups fighting for greater
autonomy from the central government. The Karens, who number about
2 million people, first rose up against Rangoon in the late 1940s.
   The state radio said Thursday that about 800 students have
``landed on the wrong path'' and fled to areas controlled by Karen
as well as other insurgents.
   Official media, meanwhile, said conditions were returning to
normal after the weeks of unrest that crippled the already weak
economy.
   The United Nations Children's Fund today began a six-day airlift
with 103 tons of emergency medical supplies for hospitals in Burma.
   The government said regular passenger service between Rangoon to
the country's second largest city, Mandalay, would resume Sunday.
Both local and international air service by Burma's government
airline were to resume Saturday.
</TEXT>
