<DOCNO> AP880930-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC--Pneumonia-AIDS     09-30 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC--Pneumonia-AIDS,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Increase in Pneumonia Deaths Attributed to AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS, the deadly disease that allows other
infections to ravage the body, is believed responsible for an
increase in pneumonia deaths among young adults in New York and
possibly other cities.
   The national Centers for Disease Control reported Thursday that
the mortality rate for men 25-44 from pneumonia increased in New
York from four deaths per 100,000 people in 1978, before the advent
of AIDS, to 19 per 100,000 in 1987.
   For women, the rate increased from two per 100,000 in 1978 to
seven in 1987. Actual fatality counts were not included in the CDC
report.
   ``Most pneumonia-attributable deaths occur among the elderly,''
the CDC said in its weekly report. ``In New York City, however, the
number and rate of such deaths among younger persons have increased
in association with (AIDS) infections in intravenous drug abusers.''
   The records of 192 New Yorkers ages 25-44 who died with
pneumonia in 1986 showed that 153, or 80 percent, were at high risk
for AIDS, including 126 intravenous drug abusers. Fifty had
possible symptoms of AIDS, and 26 were diagnosed as having AIDS.
   ``Similar trends may be occurring in other cities,'' the CDC
said.
   According to data from 121 large U.S. cities surveyed, the
percentages of deaths attributable to pneumonia and influenza in
persons 25-44 _ the group most affected by AIDS _ increased
beginning in 1981 in cities with the highest prevalence of AIDS,
the Atlanta-based health agency said.
   CDC researchers said the number and percentage of pneumonia@flu
deaths in people 25-44 have more than doubled in the cities in the
top 10 percent for rate of AIDS cases: San Francisco; Miami; Jersey
City, N.J.; New York; Newark, N.J.; Washington; Paterson, N.J.; New
Haven, Conn.; Trenton, N.J.; Atlanta; Elizabeth, N.J.; and Los
Angeles.
   The increases could be due in part to Pneumocystis carinii
pneumonia, a rare pneumonia that often strikes AIDS patients, the
CDC said. However, seven of the top 12 AIDS cities did not count
such deaths among their increase in pneumonia@flu fatalities, the
agency noted.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, weakens the body's
immune system, allowing a variety of diseases to attack, including
pneumonia. AIDS is transmitted most often through sex and through
contaminated drug needles. More than 74,000 AIDS cases have been
reported in the United States, including nearly 20,000 in drug
abusers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
