<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Defectors     09-30 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defectors,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Businessman Offers To Send Couple Back To USSR</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man angered by a couple's claim that the
government should give them a home and jobs is offering them
airfare back to the Soviet Union, where they lived on the U.S.S.R's
tab for 10 months.
   ``The check is in my pocket. I'll make it out to any airline,
but I won't make it out to them,'' Tom Hogan said Thursday.
   Hogan, owner of Marty's Used Auto Parts, a salvage yard based in
Deptford, N.J., said he decided to make the offer after reading a
newspaper story about Theodore Branch, 41, and his wife Cheryle,
41, of Erie.
   But Branch said in an interview with WJET-TV in Erie he wasn't
interested.
   ``He must be some guy trying to get some free publicity,''
Branch said, calling the offer ``garbage.''
   Branch said he is now looking for work. Phone calls were not
answered at the Erie motel where the Branches had been staying.
   The Branches flew to the Soviet Union after losing their jobs
with a Florida broadcaster. They blame the federal government for
not helping them win back wages and for devaluing property they own
in Pennsylvania by declaring it a flood plain.
   They recently returned from Moscow, claiming that after the
Soviet government had housed and employed the couple, officials at
the U.S. Embassy in Moscow offered to match those benefits. The
couple also said embassy officials promised to reimburse them for
their air fare if they returned to the United States.
   State Department officials denied making the offer. A government
spokesman said the embassy offered the Branches a loan to get home,
which any U.S. citizen can get.
   Hogan said he was amused to read Branch's complaint that no one
from the State Department greeted them when their plane landed in
Washington, D.C. Hogan offered to give them a personal send-off.
   ``I'll put them in my car and deliver them to an international
airport,'' he said.
</TEXT>
