<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EverestClimb     09-30 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Everest Climb,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>30-Year-Old Becomes 1st U.S. Woman To Scale Mt. Everest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-year-old has become the first
American woman to climb to the top of Mt. Everest, the world's
tallest peak, the Nepalese Tourism Ministry said today.
   Stacy Allison, of Portland, Ore., reached the peak of the
29,028-foot mountain Thursday along with an American expedition and
a sherpa guide, the ministry said.
   ``She's in fine shape and on the way down,'' said Dan McConnell,
expedition spokesman in Seattle.
   The 13-member group led by James Frush, a writer and attorney
from Seattle, climbed Everest via the traditional southeast ridge,
the ministry said.
   The chief goal of the expedition was to put the first American
woman at the peak. Allison, a building contractor, is one of three
women on the team, McConnell said.
   Only six other women have ever scaled Everest. The first, Junko
Tebei of Japan, reached the summit in 1975. The most recent was two
years ago by Sharon Wood of Canada.
   Four of the women scaled Everest via the southeastern route, and
two by the little-traversed North Face.
</TEXT>
