<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefenseSecretaries     09-30 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Secretaries,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Secretaries Of Defense Discuss Glasnost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six former secretaries of defense agreed
today the new openness in the Soviet Union may provide an
opportunity for the United States to rethink defense strategies.
   But the six said any change in U.S. policy must be done from a
position of strength.
   Robert McNamara, Melvin Laird, Elliot Richardson, James
Schlesinger, Donald Rumsfeld and Harold Brown participated in a
discussion moderated by television broadcaster Edwin Newman.
   The forum, sponsored by the Atlanta-based Southern Center for
International Studies, was taped and will be shown Nov. 6 by the
Public Broadcasting Service.
   McNamara said the United States could reconsider its strategies
in light of statements by Mikhail Gorbechev that war between the
superpowers is no longer an acceptable means of reaching Soviet
goals.
   But McNamara, who served as secretary of defense in the Kennedy
and Johnson administrations, said the United States must probe the
extent to which the Soviets are willing to reduce political tension
in the Western Hemisphere and around the world.
   ``We have had enticing statements from Mr. Gorbachev ... indeed
enticing statements go back to Lenin,'' said Schlesinger, who
served under presidents Nixon and Ford.
   It would be ``imprudent'' for the United States to reduce its
forces as long as Soviet power needs to be matched, he said.
   ``We can't take mere statements by the Soviet leadership and
bank them,' agreed Laird, who also served under Nixon.
   Laird said one way the United States could know whether the
Soviets were serious would be to verify a reduction in Soviet
defense spending.
   ``We do have to be careful of how we proceed,'' Brown said. But
the United States could also take the initiative in making arms
reduction proposals, said Brown, who served under President Carter.
   ``Gorbachev has been making the pace. He has been getting the
credit,'' he said.
   It was the second time the former secretaries of defense have
gathered for a discussion of foreign policy and defense issues in a
forum sponsored by the Southern Center for International Studies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880930-0093 </DOCNO>
