<2ND_LINE>PM-Kidnapping Arrest,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Rescued But Money Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police rescued a kidnapped woman from the trunk
of a car and arrested a man in the incident, but they were still
searching today for a $20,000 ransom left at a phone booth,
authorities said.
   Jung-Ok Chung, 28, who spent about 14 hours in the trunk of a
stolen Cadillac, was treated for trauma at Booth Memorial Hospital
and released Thursday, said Sgt. Peter Sweeney, a police spokesman.
   She was abducted at gunpoint in front of her apartment building
in Queens about 11:30 p.m. Wednesday and placed in the trunk of a
car, Sweeney said.
   The victim's family was contacted numerous times and a ransom
demand was made.
   ``He said he wanted $50,000 or he was going to kill her,'' said
Capt. Charles Alifano.
   A deal was reached for the ransom to be paid Thursday afternoon
at a Queens phone booth. The victim's restaurateur father, whose
name was not released, went there with $20,000 in cash _ ``all he
could raise,'' Sweeney said.
   Watched by detectives, he left the money in the booth.
   A man pulled up in a car. When an officer approached him, the
man reached for the glove compartment, where a gun was hidden,
Alifano said.
   ``We immediately arrested him after a brief struggle,'' Sweeney
said.
   Chung was found in the car's trunk, but the money was forgotten.
   A half hour after the arrest, Chung's father remembered he had
left it in the phone booth, Sweeney said.
   Police went back to the corner, but it was gone.
   Anje Lee, 28, who refused to give police an address, was charged
with kidnapping and criminal possession of a deadly weapon, Sweeney
said. He had four fully loaded guns with him, Alifano said.
</TEXT>
