<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SatanicRumors     09-30 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Satanic Rumors,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Satanic Sacrifice Rumors Sweep W. Virginia School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than three dozen children were
kept home from an elementary school today amid rumors that a
satanic cult was looking for a blond, blue-eyed child to kidnap and
sacrifice.
   ``Yesterday we had 52 students out,'' said Principal Freddie
Keen of Wallace Heights Elementary School in Kanawha County.
``Today we're down to 43, and six of them their parents called to
say they are sick.''
   The rumors have spread into adjacent Putnam County, where the
sheriff's department reported receiving 50 calls from worried
parents. One elementary school secretary said she had received
numerous calls from parents who wanted to make sure teachers
watched while students were on the playground or boarded buses.
   Police say they've found no evidence to support the rumors, but
some parents say they've heard rumors that a satanic cult has been
mutilating dogs and is searching for a blond, blue-eyed child to
sacrifice.
   ``I've heard them. The parents have heard them,'' Keen said.
   ``Obviously, there are some very concerned and frightened
children,'' Kanawha County Schools Superintendent Richard Trumble
said after Thursday's absences from Wallace Heights.
   ``There's no physical evidence,'' Keen said. ``The rumors have
been going on for weeks.''
   Police agree there is no evidence of a satanic cult.
   ``All the calls we get are checked out,'' said a sheriff's
deputy. ``But it keeps going back to rumors and rumors. We can't
validate any of this garbage.''
   Trumble met with Wallace Heights staff Thursday and said
security has been tightened.
   ``We're attempting to secure the doors of the school by putting
locks on them,'' Trumble said. ``The reality is public schools were
never really designed to be secure places. Even in locking the
doors, we're concerned about violating the fire codes.''
   Police in neighboring eastern Kentucky said in mid-September
that they fielded thousands of phone calls from residents spooked
by tales of devil worship and abduction. Rumors had been reported
in 25 counties since late July.
   Most of the rumors were similar to the West Virginia ones, that
Satan worshipers were looking for blond, blue-eyed children to
sacrifice. Some versions said followers needed to round up several
children before Halloween.
   Many Kentucky officials thought the rumors may have been sparked
by a July grave robbery in Breathitt County, in which four adults
and two juveniles were arrested. A pentacle, or five-pointed star,
and videotapes and books on the occult were found in a trailer the
defendants allegedly used for satanic ceremonies.
   Kanawha County Sheriff's Capt. W.T. Markham said today he was
unaware of the eastern Kentucky rumors and knew of no connection.
</TEXT>
