<2ND_LINE>PM-Judge Resignation,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Criticized Judge Submits Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district judge criticized for the way he treated
women in some domestic abuse cases has resigned.
   Somerville District Judge Henry A. Tempone termed it a
``decision to retire'' in his letter Thursday to Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis. The effective date is Dec. 31.
   Tempone, appointed to the bench in 1970, became eligible for
retirement when he turned 65 in 1987, but under state law could
serve until he reached the age of 70 in 1992.
   A one-paragraph statement from the state Supreme Judicial Court
announcing Tempone's departure said, ``From now until the date of
his retirement, Judge Tempone will not sit on any ... domestic
abuse cases.'' Court spokeswoman Joan Kenney said she could not
elaborate.
   A secretary for Tempone said the judge would not answer
questions on his resignation.
   In July, advocates for battered women had called for Tempone's
immediate removal or, at the least, an order for him to stop
presiding over domestic cases.
   The Commission on Judicial Conduct had investigated complaints
against Tempone. The commission's report remains sealed by the high
court.
   Tempone had been openly rebuked by chief trial court presiding
Judge Samuel Zoll in November for acting impatiently and
insensitively in cases where women were seeking protection orders.
   Thursday's announcement came one day after the Supreme Court
censured another Somerville district judge, Paul A. Heffernan, for
``discourtesy, rudeness and sarcasm'' in a domestic abuse case.
</TEXT>
