<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0459 09-30 0912</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Police Groups Endorse Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 15 grafs new with New Jersey appearance; pick up 7th graf
pvs bgng ``Meanwhile Bush...; Delete final 4 grafs to shorten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush received
endorsements today from northern New Jersey law officers and told
them that a criminal who kills a policeman should ``pay with his
life.''
   The Bush campaign hastily added an afternoon stop in
Springfield, Mass., where Bush expected to win the support of yet
another police group in rival Michael Dukakis' home state.
   ``We should have much more sympathy for the victims of crime
than we have for the criminals and that's the kind of judge I'll
appoint to the federal bench,'' he said.
   Bush criticized Massachusetts' prison furlough program again,
and said Dukakis had a ``basic revolving door program for murderers
who have not even served enough time for parole.''
   Bush said someone convicted of a drug-related murder or killing
police officers ``should pay with his life.''
   Bush's sentiments were echoed by those endorsing him today.
   ``Under a Bush administration, criminals won't get weekend
furloughs so they can go out and commit more crimes,'' said Mike
Adamo, president of the Paterson Policeman's Benevolent Association.
   Also endorsing Bush were the Passaic County Sheriff's Officers
and Correction Officers and two small police groups and a firemen's
association.
   Bush was also scheduled to pick up the endorsement of two
municipal police unions in Springfield. A week ago, Bush was
endorsed by Boston police; Dukakis countered with a law
officer-packed rally of his own.
   Bush praised New Jersey Gov. Tom Kean for his work on
environmental problems in New Jersey and blasted Dukakis on that
issue.
   ``You try to drink the water out of Boston Harbor lately? Don't
do it,'' he said. He did not mention that Boston Harbor is salt
water, but he poked fun at one of his earlier gaffes.
   ``I may have a little trouble remembering Pearl Harbor, but I
don't have any trouble remembering Boston Harbor,'' he said.
   Bush said Thursday that the American people have a right to know
whether Dukakis would heed the advice of the ACLU in choosing
judges for the high court.
   ``I just asked him (Dukakis) to clarify that for us,'' said
Bush, who for the first time suggested that the Democrat might
follow the ACLU's advice. ``I think it's a good question to ask.
All he has to say is, no, they won't have any influence on him.''
   Bush, in a speech to a community college in Mount Clemens,
Mich., said he wants judges on the court who have ``a little more
compassion for the victims of crime and a little less for the
criminals.''
   Meanwhile, Bush dismissed as ``demagoguery'' Dukakis' contention
that the Republican candidate would ``raid'' the Social Security
trust fund to help trim the deficit.
   Dukakis has cited Bush's tie-breaking vote in the Senate in 1985
on a budget resolution that backed a six-month freeze on
cost-of-living adjustments for Social Security recipients.
   Bush said Dukakis supported ``exactly the same thing'' in a 1985
meeting of the National Governor's Conference.
   Dukakis voted against a resolution backing such a freeze the
first time around, but then voted for the overall package of
resolutions on a final vote.
   Sheila Tate, Bush's press spokeswoman, acknowledged that
Dukakis' first vote was cast against the proposed freeze, but she
called that just ``preliminary skirmishing.''
   Bush said he would keep the Social Security fund ``sound and I
will not permit it to be raided for social spending programs.''
   The vice president also defended anew his running mate, Sen. Dan
Quayle of Indiana.
   ``I think it's rather demeaning for their head of the ticket to
keep going after Dan Quayle,'' Bush said. ``It shows a certain
insecurity, a certain weakness on his (Dukakis') part.''
   In another development, the Los Angeles Times reported today
that Bush, during his tenure as CIA director, fought the Justice
Department's criminal investigation of senior CIA officials,
including former director Richard Helms, and an inquiry into the
agency's operations in Chile during the early 1970s.
   The newspaper, citing newly released files in the Gerald R. Ford
presidential library in Ann Arbor, Mich., said Bush sought to
prevent some documents from being declassified and witnesses from
being called before a federal grand jury. Former President Ford
later instructed Bush to let federal prosecutors have what they
needed.
   In 1977, Helms pleaded no contest to two criminal charges of
failing to testify ``fully, completely and accurately'' to Congress.
   Mark Goodin, a Bush spokesman, had no comment on the report.
   Earlier Thursday, Bush applauded the successful launch of the
space shuttle ``Discovery'' and pledged his support for space
programs. But the GOP nominee said, if elected, he would not engage
the Soviets in a race to the planets.
   ``I don't think we just need to race: if they (the Soviets) go
to planet X, we have to be at planet X sooner,'' Bush said. ``I
think the next major responsibility of the president is to sit down
with the specialists after this flight and talk about what should
the priority be.''
   Bush told reporters he opposes a manned flight to Mars at this
time, given current budget constraints.
   Bush plans to attend the return of ``Discovery'' on Monday.
Aides to the vice president said Bush made the decision after a
phone call to President Reagan on Thursday shortly after the launch.
</TEXT>
