<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0512 09-30 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0512,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Of Man Charged In School Shooting Says It `Tore Me Apart'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, bgng `Dr. Joseph Bevilacqua ...' with 1 graf
to UPDATE with comment from mental health spokeswoman. Funeral at 2
p.m. EDT; lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of the man accused of killing
two children and wounding nine people in an elementary school
shooting rampage says her heart goes out to the victims' families.
   ``It has just really been hard on all of us,'' said Shirley
Bordnor, mother of 19-year-old James William Wilson. ``It has just
torn me apart inside. It has broken my heart inside.''
   She said her sympathy goes out to ``all of those families'' of
the victims.
   As a second schoolgirl died Thursday, the father of the other
dead girl said he still couldn't believe this week's events.
   ``Anyone that would harm innocent little children, they are
really deranged, I mean something is absolutely wrong,'' Moses
Bradley said after arranging for this afternoon's funeral for his
8-year-old daughter, Shequila.
   ``This week has been really terrible,'' he said, his eyes red
from tears.
   Tequila Thomas 8, lost her battle for life Thursday after
undergoing two operations. Her funeral was set for Sunday.
   Police Chief James Coursey said Wilson was charged Thursday with
a second count of murder, along with nine counts of assault and
battery with intent to kill.
   Police say Wilson quietly entered Oakland Elementary School on
Monday morning and began shooting at students and teachers in the
cafeteria and in a third-grade classroom.
   Wilson is undergoing psychological testing at the State Hospital
in Columbia.
   The Greenville News reported today that a state mental health
center rejected two attempts since 1986 by Wilson's relatives to
have him involuntarily committed for psychiatric care. Relatives
have described him as a hyperactive recluse who has been in and out
of a hospital psychiatric unit during the past eight months.
   Retired Probate Judge Rosemary M. Trakas said Wilson's family
filed affidavits for involuntary commitment and Wilson was
evaluated by a state mental health center.
   She told the newspaper that, after the evaluation, officials
declined to admit Wilson into the state mental hospital system.
   The Department of Mental Health ``can't confirm or deny that a
person has been a patient or has received treatment from the
department,'' spokeswoman Susan Craft said today. ``That's the law.
It's a confidentiality statute.''
   Wilson told The State newspaper of Columbia that during the
shooting he was thinking about crimes he had read about, and about
the teasing he received while in school for being overweight and
dressing strangely.
   Wilson said he had stayed up all night before the shootings,
reading a book about John Wayne Gacy, who is on Illinois' death row
for killing 33 men and boys. He also mentioned a magazine article
about Laurie Dann, the 30-year-old baby sitter who shot six
children in a Chicago-area elementary school in May.
   Most of Oakland's 600 students returned to school Thursday for
the first time since Monday's shootings, and Principal Eleanor Rice
said things ``went extremely well.''
   But ``certainly anything of this magnitude, it's going to take
some time to recover,'' Mrs. Rice said.
   Schools Superintendent Robert Watson said teachers did not tell
children of the second death because they felt it would be better
if the parents broke the news.
   Watson said 30 students were identified as needing counseling.
   ``There were a variety of different activities in the classroom
where they allowed the children to act out some of their
feelings,'' he said. ``Several teachers felt they saw a lot of
anger.''
   Leah Holmes, 8, her arm in a sling from a gunshot wound, shook
her head emphatically and said ``Nope,'' when asked Thursday
morning if she was scared to go back to school. But other children
and parents arriving at the school were less sure.
   ``We're a little nervous, but it's just been a shock
primarily,'' said Alan Maxwell, as he walked his daughter Katy to
school. Katy said she didn't hear the gunshots but remembers a
teacher coming into her classroom and telling everyone to duck
under the desks.
   Two teachers wounded remain hospitalized in good condition,
Linda Miller, Self Memorial Hospital nursing supervisor, said
today. She also said one student was readmitted Thursday in fair
condition. The others were released.
</TEXT>
