<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WardFirepower     09-30 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ward Firepower,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYPD Lifts Ban on Plastic Handgun</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Police Department has lifted a four-year ban
on the Glock handgun, which critics have called a potential
terrorist weapon out of fear that its plastic parts would make it
difficult to detect.
   Department tests indicated that ``this is not one of the
undetectable plastic weapons,'' said Robert Goldman, deputy
commissioner for legal matters.
   The department, which has tested the lightweight, semiautomatic
pistol for several years, made the decision Thursday in connection
with an appeal filed in March by a gun enthusiast, Goldman said.
   The department's top lawyer admitted the timing of the decision
was precipitated by the publicity generated by an Associated Press
report Wednesday that Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward was
licensed to carry the 9mm weapon.
   ``Perhaps I would have made this decision next week,'' Goldman
said. ``Rather than keep a controversy going, you know, why this
and why that, we'll give you the answers up front.''
   City residents will now be able to apply for permits to own the
guns, and they may also be issued to police officers in the
department's Narcotics, Intelligence and Emergency Service units.
   The gun's clip can hold up to 17 rounds of ammunition, compared
to the police-authorized .38-caliber revolvers, which hold six
rounds.
   The department originally banned the gun because ``it seemed
very prudent not to jump and summarily authorize something that on
its surface appeared to be a plastic weapon,'' he said. ``That's
the way the Glock was advertised, that's the way it was perceived.''
   The department started testing the Austrian-made weapon, which
retails for about $500, in 1986. It has a plastic frame but the
barrel and some other parts are metal. It has a 4}-inch barrel and
weighs about 24 ounces with an empty clip.
   Initially, there was concern that the weapon could not be
detected by magnetic and X-ray devices such as those used at
airports.
   Police sources, speaking on the condition they not be
identified, described the commissioner as embarrassed and upset
after the AP reported that a copy of Ward's gun license, dated July
6, showed he had a Glock.
   Ward said Tuesday that death threats prompted him to carry a
weapon and ``sometimes a machine gun'' wherever he goes.
   So far, Ward is the only person in the Police Department
authorized to carry the department-owned weapon, and the only
person in New York City registered to possess the Glock, one of a
dozen owned by the department.
</TEXT>
