<HEAD>Reagan Warns Weakness Invites War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs from prepared remarks; picks up 6th graf
pvs: In Chicago ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan warned today that military
weakness ``is to invite war'' as he called on political leaders to
shun ``far-out group on the left.''
   In remarks prepared for delivery to community leaders in
Chicago, Reagan recalled the Munich agreement of a half-century ago
that was hoped to achieve peace, but was followed by war within a
months.
   ``To be weak is to invite war,'' Reagan said, yet ``even today
there are those who have forgotten the ancient principle of peace
through strength.''
   ``And their innocence and neivete would put in questiom all that
we have achieved ... all the progress toward ending the twin evils
of totalitarianism and nuclear terror,'' said Reagan.
   His speech was scheduled only a few hours after he signed a $300
billion defense appropriation bill, after Congress voted changes
that caused him to veto the measure in August.
   Taking up Vice President George Bush's anti-liberal cudgel,
Reagan said that Democrat Michael Dukakis' performance in last
Sunday's debate was what could be expected from an American Civil
Liberties Union member: ``He didn't have a prayer.''
   Questioning the positions of the ACLU, Reagan added: ``You
recall a few years back, political figures had to disassociate
themselves from groups on the right with far-out views.
   ``Isn't it now time for responsible people to do the same thing
with far-out groups on the left?''
   In Chicago, Reagan's first stop was Wozniak's Casino, a Polish
social hall on the city's southwest side.
   The president was to address some 1,200 local and community
supporters at the establishment, which features one of the oldest
bowling alleys in the country.
   Tonight, Reagan speaks at a $250-per-ticket GOP rally on the
floor of the Mercantile Exchange. He also planned to attend a
private reception for major GOP donors, where the president
traditionally poses for pictures with big-money contributors.
   With 24 electoral votes, Illinois is one of the richest prizes
in the presidential race. Republicans hope to win it by keeping in
the fold moderate Democrats that voted for Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
   Bush took a 120-mile bus tour through rural Illinois on
Wednesday, painting Dukakis as ``an inexperienced liberal'' out of
sync with Middle America.
   The Massachusetts governor, who has made much during the
campaign of his Greek immigrant parentage, targeted the same voters
during campaign stops Tuesday in Peoria and the Chicago area.
   Dukakis accused his GOP rival of threatening the Social Security
system, declaring that the issue in 1988 ``isn't just what will
paly in Peoria; the issue is what will work in Peoria.''
</TEXT>
