<1ST_LINE>r p AM-LouisianaPrimary     09-30 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Louisiana Primary,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sports May Get In Way Of Voter Turnout For Louisiana Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hunting and football are expected to
produce a low turnout Saturday when Louisiana voters cast ballots
in congressional primary races, including one in which Gov. Buddy
Roemer's mother is the challenger.
   ``It's the opening of squirrel season, and that's important in
rural areas,'' Secretary of State Fox McKeithen said. ``The LSU
(Louisiana State University) Tigers are on afternoon television
against the University of Florida, and in many areas of the state
there doesn't seem to be much interest.''
   The primary balloting will attract only about 38 to 42 percent
of the registered voters, the state's chief elections officer
predicted.
   McKeithen said he expected a higher turnout in the 4th
Congressional District, where incumbent Republican Rep. Jim McCrery
is being challenged by Adeline Roemer, the governor's mother, and
Robert Briggs, a retired military officer. Both challengers are
Democrats.
   McCrery won the seat in a special election last spring after
Roemer, the district's former congressman, took office as governor
on March 14.
   Under Louisiana's open primary system, all candidates run in the
same primary, regardless of party affiliation. If no candidate in a
race wins a majority Saturday, the top two contenders will meet in
a Nov. 8 runoff.
   McKeithen said more voter interest also is expected in the 8th
District, where incumbent Republican Rep. Clyde Holloway faces four
Democratic opponents, including Faye Williams, who he defeated in a
runoff two years ago, state Sen. J.E. Jumonville Jr., former Lt.
Gov. Bobby Freeman and former Alexandria Mayor John ``Tillie''
Snyder.
   Two of the state's eight House members delegation are unopposed:
Republican Richard Baker and Democrat Jimmy Hayes. The other
incumbents _ Democrats Jerry Huckaby, Lindy Boggs and Billy Tauzin
and Republican Bob Livingston _ were not expected to face serious
opposition.
   Voters also will judge one proposed amendment to the state
constitution, a tax break for owners who improve residential
property occupied by low- and moderate-income families. The
amendment would allow owners to pay taxes for five years based on
the pre-improvement assessed value.
</TEXT>
