<HEAD>Two Men Escape To West Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two East Germans escaped uninjured
over their communist homeland's border fortifications to West
Germany Friday, authorities said.
   In the first escape, a 28-year-old crane driver fled over East
German border fortifications to Lower Saxony state in northern West
Germany, Hanover police said in a statement.
   The man entered West Germany near the border town of Osterode,
about 50 miles east of Hanover, said the statement.
   Later Friday, a 24-year-old East German man fled to the southern
state of Bavaria, police said.
   The man scaled frontier barriers apparently unnoticed by border
guards, Bavarian state police said.
   Police did not give further details and did not release the
men's names.
   Nearly 330 East Germans have escaped to West Germany or West
Berlin so far this year, according to federal statistics.
