<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Helms-Evict     09-30 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helms-Evict,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`We're Here for the Furniture,' Homeless Activists Tell Helms
Aides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homeless activists served a homemade
``eviction notice'' on the office of North Carolina Sen. Jesse
Helms on Friday, removed the furniture from his outer office and
were led off in handcuffs.
   ``Ooohhh, this chair feels good,'' chortled a homeless man
identified as Lou Juluke, 56, settling into a brown leather
upholstered, brass-studded chair in the middle of an upstairs hall
in the Dirksen Senate Office Building.
   Minutes later, a team of Capitol Hill civil disobedience
specialists in blue sleeveless sweaters, baseball-style caps and
disposable rubber gloves moved in and arrested three other
demonstrators who had removed the furniture.
   The demonstrators said Helms voted for budget cuts that left
thousands homeless and deserved a symbolic taste of his own
medicine. But there was no sign that the conservative lawmaker was
upset by the 30-minute episode.
   Helms' press secretary, Barbara Lukens, said she was unsure of
the whereabouts of the senator when the episode began. ``All I know
is that he's in his office now,'' she said. She was asked if he
would have anything to say about the matter.
   ``Has he ever issued many press statements?'' she asked.
   Those arrested identified themselves as Stewart Gurnsey, 37, of
Boston, a former Harvard divinity student and head of a nonprofit
housing company, and Jennifer Thompson, 22, and Jerry Jones, 21,
both originally from Chapel Hill, N.C., but now living in
Washington.
   Capitol Hill police spokesman Dan Nichols said they were charged
with unlawful entry and demonstrating in the Capitol. He said both
counts were misdemeanors punishable by $500 fines and six months in
jail. He said they would face arraignment Friday or Saturday in
D.C. Superior Court.
   All three said they were associated with Washington activist
Mitch Snyder whose fasting and feuding with the Reagan
administration over shelter for the homeless has captured the
national spotlight.
   A number of members of Snyder's Community for Creative
Nonviolence, including Juluke, looked on as the three demonstrators
were led away.
   The three activists arrived at Helms office at 11 a.m. and
served a ``notice of eviction'' that blasted the senator for
supporting budget cuts that have resulted in ``thousands of people
leading lives of quiet desperation'' in North Carolina ``on our
streets, in cars and abandoned tobacco barns.''
   Two receptionists said they were nonplussed as the three began
to pick up tables, chairs and potted plants and carry them into the
hallway.
   ``You better get somebody up here right away,'' said
receptionist Judity Jones into a telephone. Police began to arrive
a few minutes later.
</TEXT>
