<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Tibet Bjt   09-30 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet, Bjt,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Year After Violent Protests, China Maintains Firm Grip On
Tibet</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's grip on Tibet appears firmer than ever
one year after long-suppressed hatred of Chinese rule erupted in a
violent protest that left at least 14 people dead.
   One year ago Saturday, about 2,000 Tibetans led by Buddhist
monks burned a police station in Lhasa, capital of the Himalayan
nation, and attacked police in the bloodiest uprising since an
abortive bid for independence in 1959.
   A second violent protest broke out at a Buddhist ceremony on
March 5, with 24 killed by unofficial count in day-long clashes
with police. Small peaceful protests, quickly ended by police, also
were held Sept. 26, Oct. 6 and several times since.
   But it was the violence of Oct. 1, China's National Day, that
brought the greatest international criticism of Communist China's
38-year rule in Tibet, including a condemnation by the U.S. Senate.
China appears determined to head off any commemoration.
   A few monks who tried to chant pro-independence slogans in
Lhasa's main square on Tuesday were quickly hustled away, and the
area was briefly closed to foreigners, Western travelers in Lhasa
reported. No other details were available.
   ``Nobody is allowed to use religious activities to disrupt
public order, damage people's health or disturb education,'' Mao
Rubai, vice chairman of the Tibetan regional government, said last
week in an interview with two foreign reporters.
   Religion and nationalism are inseparable in Tibet, which before
China's Red Army entered in 1950 was effectively ruled by Buddhist
monks headed by the Dalai Lama, Tibetan Buddhism's holiest figure.
The independence protests have been led by monks demanding the
return of the Dalai Lama, who fled to India in 1959.
   Mao's two interviewers, from the U.S. Cable News Network and the
Sydney Morning Herald of Australia, were among the few foreign
journalists allowed to visit Tibet since the protests. Authorities
expelled from Lhasa 14 foreign reporters who were covering last
year's Oct. 1 protest, and since have barred dozens of journalists
from entering.
   Sketchy reports from Lhasa indicate the Chinese plan to be
prepared this year.
   An Asian diplomat based in Beijing, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said additional Chinese troops recently were posted to
the already heavily garrisoned region in what he said was
``obviously a law-and-order measure.''
   Western travelers in Lhasa, who also spoke anonymously, said
security forces have been posted at night in Buddhist monasteries
for the past few weeks to keep watch over the nationalist monks.
   They said an 11:30 p.m. Curfew took effect last Saturday for
foreign tourists, mostly restricted to group tours since the
protests.
   There were no signs that Tibetans planned any action on Oct. 1 _
only the usual whispers from monks and pilgrims in broken English:
``We hate Chinese. Dalai Lama come back.''
   In April, China invited the Dalai Lama to come back and live in
Tibet if he renounced independence for the region.
   Last week, China made a second overture, inviting the Dalai Lama
to hold a ``direct dialogue'' at the place of his choice. It still
insisted he renounce independence, and made no new concessions.
   The Dalai Lama agreed to talks. But the matter stalemated when
he said they should be based on his June proposal in Strasbourg,
France, that China give Tibet domestic autonomy while still
handling its foreign affairs and stationing troops there.
   China, unwilling to compromise on its 700-year-old claim to
sovereignty over Tibet, rejected the Strasbourg plan.
   China's latest overture appeared timed to assure Tibetans and
foreigners of its peaceful intentions before the Oct. 1
anniversary. But it also highlighted one result of the past year's
protests.
   The violence could not shake Chinese control. But it apparently
did convince Chinese leaders that real calm in Tibet cannot be
achieved without some kind of settlement with the man they long
denounced as a separatist.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
