<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     09-30 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Receives More Blood, Carter Visits Palace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors gave Emperor Hirohito blood for the eighth
straight day Friday as he continued to bleed internally. Former
President Jimmy Carter visited the Imperial Palace to wish the
monarch a speedy recovery.
   Doctors said the world's longest reigning living monarch was in
stable condition.
   Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, were among thousands of
well-wishers who braved a cold rain to visit the palace. Carter
signed his name in a registry but did not see the 87-year-old
emperor.
   The former president arrived in Japan Wednesday for a five-day
visit to attend the Japan Junior Chamber of Commerce's annual
convention.
   Hirohito has been under intensive care by a team of court
physicians since he vomited blood Sept. 19. Few people other than
family members have been allowed to see him.
   Since that day, the emperor has received more than eight pints
of blood, or more than two-thirds the normal amount of blood in his
body, news reports said.
   Doctors on Thursday began administering blood with the white
corpuscles removed. Such transfusions are aimed at preventing a
reaction to the white blood cells, Imperial Household Agency
spokesman Kenji Maeda said.
   ``The emperor remains in stable condition as a whole, though
slight traces of blood were detected Friday morning,'' Maeda told
palace reporters.
   Maeda said Hirohito's temperature was 99.7 degrees, compared
with his normal reading of 95.9 degrees.
   Gray skies and rain once again blanketed Tokyo, as they have
every day since the emperor's condition worsened, and Hirohito
asked a visitor what the weather was like in South Korea, where the
Olympics are being held, Maeda said.
   The imperial spokesman said the emperor also complained of
feeling hungry. He has not been able to eat or drink anything for
10 days, except for two small ice cubes Sept. 22, and is being fed
intravenously.
   Local news reports have said the emperor has intestinal cancer,
but palace officials have neither confirmed nor denied the reports.
They have urged the media to refrain from such speculation.
   Throughout Japan, organizers continued to cancel dozens of local
festivals, concerts and fall athletic meets because of the
emperor's illness, but government officials said such cancellations
should not be overdone.
   At the U.S. Air Force's Yokota Air Base, officials said they
were postponing the annual Japanese-American Friendship Festival
because of the emperor's health.
   ``The essence of the annual event is to express our friendship
for our Japanese hosts,'' Col. Richard T. Swope, 475th Air Base
Wing Commander, said in a statement. ``As an extension of that
friendship, we are postponing the festival until further notice.''
   But Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita urged that a national
athletic meet be held in Kyoto as scheduled, and sports officials
said each school should decide whether to hold sports events, news
reports said.
   Organizations opposed to the emperor system, such as the Japan
Communist Party, have criticized what they say is pressure on
groups to cancel normally scheduled events.
   Under Japan's postwar constitution, the emperor is a symbolic
head of state with little real power. His duties include placing an
official seal on documents and government appointments on the
advice of the Cabinet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
