<1ST_LINE>r p AM-AbsenteeGreeks     09-30 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Absentee Greeks,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Americans in Greece Register to Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Greek-Americans who have
returned to their ``patrida'' _ or homeland _ are signing up for
absentee ballots, aided by an organization backing Democrat Michael
Dukakis for president.
   ``It's touching to see elderly people coming in fill out the
form. The oldest we had was a 101-year-old man who said he'd never
voted in a presidential election before,'' said Catherine
Carnatios, one 20 volunteers for the ``Friends of Michael Dukakis''
organization.
   Since the pro-Dukakis organization started up in August, more
than 20,000 Americans of Greek descent have filled out ballot
applications at 14 offices scattered around mainland Greece and the
islands, its members said.
   ``They're not looking to help elect a Greek president who'll
solve the problems of the `patrida' but they do have the idea of
the American dream coming true _ the son of immigrants becoming
president,'' Nikos Rezevoulis, the group's chairman, said in an
interview.
   The Massachusetts governor, whose parents both were born in
Greece, has stressed his immigrant background thorughout his
presidential campaign, earning approval from Greeks and Greek
Americans, even if they're not Democrats.
   ``Win or lose, Dukakis has given the Greek image a boost. He's
shown Greeks can be hardworking and efficient, which hasn't been
part of their image outside the United States,'' said Dimitris
Katsoudas, who heads a conservative think tank in Athens.
   Dukakis' candidacy has encouraged many older Greek Americans to
apply for ballots. Retirees make up at least one-third of an
estimated 75,000 American citizens living in Greece, according to
the Dukakis organization.
   The organization provides would-be voters with ballot forms and
volunteers help make sure they are correctly filled out.
   The forms also are available at the American Embassy, but Mrs.
Carnatios said ``people can be a bit shy about requesting
assistance from officials so they often prefer to ask us about the
details.''
   Other Greece-based voters are mostly students, and businessmen
and their families who divide their time between Greece and the
United States, and some are registered Republicans.
   ``I registered as a Republican back in the Sixties. But now I
want to vote for Dukakis, both for his policies and because I'm
proud of him,'' said Apollo Sakell, a 53-year-old former civil
servant from Leroy, New York.
   ``Mike Dukakis _ President'' bumper stickers can be seen around
residential districts of the capital where many Greek Americans
live, but Dukakis T-shirts and crockery haven't been selling well,
according to store clerks in downtown Athens.
   Such a lack of enthusiasm may reflect a reluctance among Greeks
to be seen backing a candidate who has been trailing in the polls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
