<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1522EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     09-30 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goverment Says It Recaptured Rebel Posts, Killed 76 More People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army recaptured outposts along the
Chinese border from communist rebels and killed at least 76 people
in suppressing unrest elsewhere this week, a government spokeman
said Friday.
   By official count, at least 425 people have been killed since
hard-line Gen. Saw Maung seized power Sept. 18 and ordered troops
to put down demonstrators throughout the country.
   Three army outposts that fell to rebels of the outlawed Burma
Communist Party were recaptured Friday with support from air
strikes, government spokesman Kyaw Sann told a press conference.
   More than 1,500 insurgents on Sept. 23 attacked and occupied
positions at Lamingone, Yanshingone and Payagone near the Chinese
border about 340 miles northeast of Rangoon. In ensuing clashes at
least 131 rebels and 48 soldiers were killed and 104 wounded,
officials said.
   Kyaw Sann said mopping-up operations were continuing. The
communists are believed to have some 20,000 guerrillas under arms.
   The Communist Party earlier issued a statement supporting the
mass pro-democracy uprising in Burma that began in late July. But
it was not known whether the reported attacks were designed to
alleviate anti-government pressure.
   Also Friday, the leading opposition group denounced the military
government for threatening to punish striking workers and said
Burma's leaders were trying to ``destroy the movement for
democracy.''
   The government has ordered all civil servants and workers in
state-run factories to return to their jobs by Monday or face
dismissal. Most government employees have been on strike since Aug.
8, paralyzing the country's administrative and economic machinery.
   A press release from the National League for Democracy said the
general strike was ``the major force at the forefront of the
movement for democracy'' and urged all people to stay away from
work.
   ``Actions such as removal from service, eviction from official
residence, demotion and transfer of government servants for
continuing the general strike amount to opposing and denial of
democratic rights,'' the release said.
   A spokesperson for the Karen ethnic minority rebels said Friday
that nearly 2,000 students and others have fled to areas under
their control along the Thai border. Some of the escapees, who hope
to receive military training at Karen bases, claim to have seen
authorities executing students and other protesters.
   The Karen are among a dozen ethnic groups fighting for greater
autonomy from the central government. The Karens, who number about
2 million, first rose up against Rangoon in the late 1940s.
   The new government has promised multiparty general elections but
the National League for Democracy has yet to decide whether to
contest them.
   The league, headed by former army general Aung Gyi, has urged
that people continue to fight the autocratic system through
peaceful means. Two other political parties have emerged to oppose
the government which western diplomats say is squarely behind the
National Unity Party.
   This military-backed party, under its former name of the Burma
Socialist Program Party, has wielded control since strongman Ne Win
seized power in a 1962 military coup.
   The United Nations Children's Fund began a six-day airlift of
103 tons of emergency medical supplies for hospitals in Burma. A
chartered C-130 aircraft will shuttle between Bangkok, Thailand,
and the Burmese capital to deliver the supplies for 50 hospitals
and 23 dispensaries, a UNICEF release said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
