<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MormonConference     09-30 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mormon Conference,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Gather for Semiannual Mormon Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably mild weather greeted
thousands of Mormon Church leaders and members gathering Friday for
the faith's 158th Semiannual General Conference.
   President Ezra Taft Benson was to be the keynote speaker at the
first of four general sessions Saturday morning, as well as to fill
a vacancy in the church's Quorum of the Twelve Apostles.
   The Twelve is an advisory body to the governing three-member
First Presidency of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints, headed by the 89-year-old Benson, a former U.S. agriculture
secretary.
   The vacancy was created May 20 at the death at age 90 of Marion
G. Romney, the quorum's president. He was replaced by the
next-most-senior member of the Twelve, Howard W. Hunter, next in
line to be church president.
   Vacancies in the all-male hierarchy usually are filled during
the general conferences held on the first weekends of April and
October.
   The two-day conference is held in the 6,000-seat Tabernacle on
Temple Square, but hundreds of thousands more will view the
sessions on television and over the church's satellite network. The
latter reaches more than 2,000 church centers in the United States,
Canada and Puerto Rico.
   The church has 6.5 million members and missionaries in 80
countries and 17 territories.
</TEXT>
