<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Ramstein     09-30 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Ramstein,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises; Police Seeking Man in Ramstein Fraud Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from the crash at the
Ramstein air show disaster increased Friday to 68, and police
searched for a man posing as an orphan from the Aug. 28 crash in a
scheme to bilk the elderly.
   Juergen Dietzen, a spokesman for Rhineland-Palatinate state,
said a 36-year-old West German man died in a Kaiserslautern
hospital of injuries sustained in the tragedy at the Ramstein U.S.
Air Force base.
   Dietzen said 61 people remained hospitalized.
   The accident occurred when three Italian stunt planes collided
while performing at an annual air show. One jet crashed into the
crowd and exploded.
   Authorities said 60 West Germans, three Americans, one Dutch
citizen, one French citizen and the three Italian pilots died in
the disaster.
   Police in Cologne searched for a young man who asked several
elderly people for large sums of money after telling them he lost
his parents in the air show accident.
   Police said the man tried the scheme in Cologne, Dortmund and
Duesseldorf.
   An 83-year-old woman who heard the man's story but refused to
give him money later saw the man with another elderly woman at a
bank, authorities said.
   The second woman was about to withdraw several thousand marks
from her account to give to the man, police said.
   Police said the man fled after the first woman approached him.
</TEXT>
