<HEAD>List of Members of the Politburo of the Soviet Communist Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 20-end to CORRECT numbering</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Kremlin-Shake-up, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of members of the Communist Party
Politburo, the Soviet Union's ruling body, following changes by the
party's Central Committee on Friday. The dates shown after each
official's name are their dates of election to the Politburo seats
they now hold.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FULL MEMBERS
   1. Mikhail S. Gorbachev, October 1980, Soviet leader as party
general secretary since March 11, 1985. Born March 2, 1931.
   2. Nikolai I. Ryzhkov, April 1985, named Soviet prime minister
on Sept. 27, 1985. Born Sept. 28, 1929.
   3. Vitaly I. Vorotnikov, December 1983, chairman of Russian
federation Council of Ministers. Born Jan. 20, 1926.
   4. Lev N. Zaikov, March 1986, specialist on defense industry,
economics, replaced Boris N. Yeltsin as Moscow party chief in
November 1987. Born April 3, 1923.
   5. Yegor K. Ligachev, April 1985, Central Committee commission
chairman for agriculture. Born Nov. 29, 1920.
   6. Viktor P. Nikonov, June 1987, Central Committee secretary.
Born Feb. 28, 1929.
   7. Nikolai N. Slyunkov, June 1987, Central Committee commission
chairman for socio-economic policy, member of Supreme Soviet
Presidium. Born April 26, 1929.
   8. Viktor M. Chebrikov, April 1985, head of Committee for State
Security (KGB) and Central Committee commission chairman for
legal-judicial policies. Holds rank of general. Born April 27, 1923.
   9. Eduard A. Shevardnadze, July 1985, Soviet foreign minister.
Born Jan. 25, 1928.
   10. Vladimir V. Shcherbitsky, November 1979, party chief in the
republic of the Ukraine, member Supreme Soviet Presidium. Born Feb.
17, 1918.
   11. Alexander N. Yakovlev, June 1987, Central Committee
commission chairman for international policy, former ambassador to
Canada. Born Dec. 2, 1923.
   12. Vadim A. Medvedev, September 1988, Central Committee
commission chairman for ideology. Born March 29, 1929.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CANDIDATE (NON-VOTING) MEMBERS
   1. Yuri D. Maslyukov, February 1988, replaced Nikolai V. Talyzin
as chairman of the powerful State Planning Committee, deputy
chairman of the Council of Ministers. Born Sept. 30, 1937.
   2. Georgy P. Razumovsky, February 1988, Central Committee
secretary and commission chairman for personnel issues and party
construction. Born Jan. 19, 1936.
   3. Yuri F. Solovev, March 1986, Leningrad regional party chief,
member Supreme Soviet Presidium. Born Aug. 20, 1925.
   4. Nikolai V. Talyzin, October 1985, former chairman of the
State Planning Committee and now first deputy premier and chairman
of the government's Social Development Bureau. Born Jan. 28, 1929.
   5. Dmitri T. Yazov, June 1987, defense minister holding rank of
army general, former commander of the Far East military district.
Born Nov. 8, 1923.
   6. Alexandra Biryukova, September 1988, had been Central
Committee secretary responsible for the consumer sector. New
responsibilities uncertain. Born Feb. 25, 1929.
   7. Anatoly I. Lukyanov, September 1988, had been chief of the
Central Committee's general staff. New responsibilities uncertain.
Born May 7, 1930.
   8. Alexander V. Vlasov, September 1988, Minister of the Interior
in charge of the nation's uniformed police. Born Jan. 20, 1932.
</TEXT>
