<1ST_LINE>u w PM-House-Wright 1stLd-Writethru a0441 09-30 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House-Wright, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Partisan Battles Flare in House</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with GOP calling for investigation of Wright.
Editing throughout to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican members of the House Intelligence
Committee said today they would ask the full House to vote to
investigate Speaker Jim Wright on charges that he improperly
disclosed a secret CIA operation in Nicaragua.
   The lawmakers said they had made that recommendation to House
Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., who had accepted it. They
said they were introducing a resolution calling for the Wright
investigation which could be voted on by the full House next week.
   Rep. Dick Cheney, R-Wyo., a member of the intelligence panel and
the No. 3 Republican leadership official, said the GOP had been
stymied by majority Democrats in seeking to start an investigation
through normal ethics and Intelligence Committee channels.
   ``Absolutely no action has been taken to date, and there appears
little prospect for action by the majority party,'' Cheney said at
a news conference.
   Joining Cheney in introducing the resolution were Reps. Henry
Hyde of Illinois, Bob Livingston of Louisiana, Bob McEwen of Ohio,
Dan Lungren of California and Bud Shuster of Pennsylvania.
   Cheney acknowledged that it would be difficult to pass the
resolution in the Democratic-controlled House, but said he believed
important institutional principles were at stake, including
cooperation with the executive branch on intelligence matters.
   The move promised to heighten partisan tensions over Wright's
problems with just a week left before Congress adjourns for the
campaign trail.
   ``The relationship between the parties is very strained,''
Cheney said, noting that verbal exchanges were reaching new highs
in bitterness.
   Cheney said Republicans, chafing for two years under what they
consider Wright's heavy-handed leadership style, had been
``energized'' by Wright's comments last week about a purported CIA
covert operation in Nicaragua, which they contend violated House
rules against disclosing secret information.
   The pressure over that issue was heightened when the
Intelligence Committee on Wednesday declined to turn over to the
ethics committee classified information relevant to a requested
investigation of Wright in the matter.
   Michel, who had requested the probe along with Cheney, asked GOP
members of the intelligence panel on Thursday to prepare a
confidential report for him recommending what should be done next.
   ``I've never seen this thing get out of control like it is
now,'' said Rep. Tony Coelho, the Democrats' No. 3 leadership
official in the chamber. Coelho accused GOP leaders of trying to
``tear down the institution'' and of caving in to right-wing
elements of their party who seek to embarrass Wright.
   Coelho, D-Calif., said the intelligence meeting was forced by
Republicans, who knew the panel would have to decline to release
the information.
   ``What you have now is an effort that's very political, very
aggressive and loaded with grenades,'' he said, attributing the
whole controversy to Republican frustration over being the minority
party in the House since 1956.
   ``The Republicans' problem in the House is that we don't take
them seriously, Republicans in the Senate don't take them seriously
and the White House doesn't take them seriously,'' Coelho added.
   ``I wonder what Tony's smoking?'' Cheney said when apprised of
the comments. ``The real problem is the speaker, and the way he
operates. ... He's trashed the CIA, damaged U.S. foreign policy in
Nicaragua. ... All of Tony Coelho's blue smoke and mirrors won't
change that.''
   Wright, D-Texas, said the effort to launch a probe into his
comments was a political move and again denied revealing classified
secrets when he spoke to reporters about what he termed the CIA's
attempts to instigate civil unrest in Nicaragua.
   ``It is really very sad that people will try to use the ethics
committee, or any other committee of the House, as a cat's paw to
try to carry out a partisan political vendetta against another
member,'' he said.
   But Republicans called the Democratic counteroffensive a dodge,
and said Wright simply was seeking to escape the consequences of
his mistake by stirring up a partisan smoke screen.
   And members in both parties saw Michel's participation in the
request for an investigation as a turning point in relations
between the parties in the chamber, because Michel has for years
taken a less confrontational stance in dealings with the majority.
   Some moderate Democrats were saying privately that while they
were proud of the legislative record of the 100th Congress under
Wright's leadership, they were uncomfortable with his highly
visible role in U.S. diplomacy toward Central America.
   Tensions between the two sides surfaced on the House floor
Thursday after one Democratic lawmaker, Rep. Pat Williams of
Montana, denounced GOP vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle for
``hypocrisy'' in campaign statements that didn't match his voting
record. Republican members bristled, and demanded that Williams be
ruled out of order.
   ``I think it's probably set the stage for a series of
fireworks,'' Williams said later. ``The members are at a boiling
point, not only because of the presidential campaign but also
because of the charges against the speaker.''
</TEXT>
