<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SatanicRumors     09-30 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Satanic Rumors,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cult Rumors Sweeping School; Some Parents Pull Kids Out of Class</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen-agers with overactive imaginations
are to blame for rumors that a satanic cult is searching for a
blond, blue-eyed child for human sacrifice, a police official said
Friday.
   As the rumors flowed, more than three dozen children were kept
from the elementary school in Sissonville, a town of 400 people 20
miles to the northwest.
   ``Yesterday we had 52 students out,'' Wallace Heights Elementary
School Principal Freddie Keen said Friday. ``Today we're down to
43, and six of them, their parents called to say they are sick.''
   The rumors have spread into adjacent Putnam County, where the
sheriff's department reported receiving 50 calls Thursday from
worried parents. One school secretary said she had received
numerous calls from parents who wanted to make sure teachers are
present when students are on the playground or boarding buses.
   Police say they've found no evidence to support the stories, but
some parents say they've heard rumors a satanic cult has been
mutilating dogs and searching for a blond, blue-eyed child.
   ``I've heard them. The parents have heard them,'' Keen said.
   Kanawha County Sheriff's Department Capt. W.T. Markham said
local children are to blame for the rumors.
   ``We think a bunch of kids 13 and 14 years old got hold of a
bunch of books about Satan worship and cults and they're reading
these things and starting rumors, and they're getting a lot of
mileage out of these rumors,'' Markham said.
   Markham said officers have found no evidence of a cult, but that
doesn't satisfy some parents.
   ``I told that to one parent, and she said, `Yes, but you don't
have a blond-haired, blue-eyed child, do you?'' Markham said.
   Kanawha County Schools Superintendent Richard Trumble said
security at school has been beefed up, but Keen said some parents
still are afraid.
   ``There's no physical evidence,'' Keen said. ``There's a lot of
fear. There's a lot of fear in the whole county. The rumors have
been going on for weeks.''
</TEXT>
