<DOCNO> AP880930-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     09-30 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Rebuffs Defense Bid to End Prosecution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Friday rebuffed an
attempt by Oliver L. North and two co-defendants to stop their
prosecution for diverting the proceeds of U.S.-Iran arms sales to
the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said it
would only consider arguments that the defendants' congressional
testimony was illegally used against them after convictions in the
case.
   ``Except for a very limited number of cases ... appeals in
criminal cases must await the termination of the proceedings by
final judgment,'' said Circuit Judges James L. Buckley, Douglas H.
Ginsburg and David Sentelle.
   ``If appellants' claims may effectively be reviewed on appeal
from a final judgment of conviction, there is no justification for
departing from the general prohibition against piecemeal review,''
the court said of the defense challenge that was joined by the
American Civil Liberties Union.
   North, a former National Security Council aide; former national
security adviser John M. Poindexter and arms dealer Albert Hakim
contended that because of widespread publicity, grand jurors and
witnesses were exposed to the congressional testimony the
defendants gave under limited immunity from prosecution.
   Prosecutors are barred from using the immunized testimony that a
witnesses gives Congress as evidence against that defendant in
court.
   While the court did not rule on the merits of the appeal, the
judges said the defendants' ``claim that the (congressional)
immunity affords them a right not to be prosecuted at all is
ill-founded.''
   The three defendants had appealed U.S. District Judge Gerhard A.
Gesell's preliminary determination that prosecutors and grand
jurors had not relied on the immunized congressional testimony as
evidence to return the indictment.
   Gesell's decision to hold only a limited pre-trial hearing on
the issue of grand jury ``taint'' was also a subject to the
challenge.
   The appeals court also dismissed a request that it order Gesell
to either dismiss the indictment or hold a more extensive pre-trial
hearing on the immunity issue.
   Gesell had ruled that the question could be dealt with in
post-trial proceedings if any evidence of taint emerged during the
trials.
   The judge has ordered separate trials for North, Poindexter,
Hakim and retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord, a business
partner of Hakim who testified on Capitol Hill without limited
immunity.
   The defendants are accused of conspiring to defraud the U.S.
government by diverting proceeds from the arms-for-hostages deals
with Iran to the Contras at a time when Congress banned American
military aid to the rebels.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh has elected to try North
first, but the case is not expected to go to trial until next year.
   Gesell has indefinitely postponed the case to give prosecutors
additional time to find and process a large number of classified
documents that North may be entitled to use in his defense.
   In a statement issued following Friday's decision, Walsh said:
``The Court of Appeals decision is most welcome and permits us to
concentrate on pursuing the cases awaiting trial.''
   At a pre-trial hearing last spring, Walsh documented elaborate
procedures to prevent members of his staff and grand jurors from
being exposed to the immunized congressional testimony of the
defendants.
   Walsh also filed evidence under seal in court to prove it was
not derived from information obtained by the House and Senate
Iran-Contra investigating committees.
   The appeals panel also rejected the defense contention that the
right not to be tried on ``tainted'' evidence must be invoked
before trial or it otherwise would not exist.
   The defendants ``have failed to demonstrate how the remedy
afforded by direct appeal will be `clearly inadequate' to correct
the perceived wrong,'' it said.
   ``Even when vindication of the defendants' rights requires
dismissal of the charge altogether, however, an interlocutory
appeal is not automatically justified,'' the court said of the
defense attempt to mount its legal challenge before the cases are
tried.
   The immunity issue also hinges on whether witnesses who
testified before the grand jury gave evidence in that proceeding
that was influenced what they learned from what North, Poindexter
or Hakim told Congress.
</TEXT>
