<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede DALLAS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Promotes Dukakis In Texas, North Carolina</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 6 grafs with Bentsen in North Carolina,
picking up in 3rd graf pvs, At the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen today dismissed Republican
George Bush's stated commitments to education and a balanced
federal budget, and also got in a jibe at Bush's running mate.
   ``George Bush likes to talk about balanced budgets,'' Bentsen
said. ``It's like Dan Quayle talking about his resume. There's not
much to say.''
   Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential nominee, said that
Michael Dukakis, his party's standardbearer, has balanced 10
consecutive Massachusetts budgets.
   ``That's the difference between promise and performance and
that's a difference we understand in the South,'' said Bentsen, a
senator from Texas.
   He also told the crowd of about 500 people that he and Dukakis
are committed to a strong national defense.
   The night before, in Dallas, Bentsen told fellow Texans that
Dukakis is more in tune with their concerns than Bush and declared
himself eager to debate his ``radical right'' counterpart on the
Republican ticket.
   At the fund-raiser, Bentsen joked about Bush's claim to be a
Texan. The vice president's legal residence is a Houston hotel
suite.
   ``I saw you check into the hotel and register,'' Bentsent told
Dukakis. ``In the minds of some, that makes you a Texan.''
   Jokes aside, Bentsen used strong partisan rhetoric in describing
the stakes of the November election in Texas and across the country
and of his debate next week with GOP vice presidential nominee
Quayle, who had campaigned in Texas the previous day.
   ``I don't have to tell you that the refusal of the Reagan-Bush
administration to develop themselves a national energy policy has
sentenced much of this state to a very deep and powerful
recession,'' the Texas senator told the $1.2 million fund-raiser.
   As for Quayle, Bentsen, who has spent much of this campaign trip
preparing for the debate, said he was ``looking forward to
discussing the issues with Dan Quayle because I think his radical
right agenda is out of the mainstream of America and I think
Americans think that.''
   ``He doesn't even know what century he lives in,'' Bentsen said
in a poke at a recent gaffe by Quayle, who said he had not lived in
this century. ``And believe me, if they get their way, we'll be
living in the 19th century and not the 20th century.''
   Dukakis, in his remarks, encouraged Bentsen to confront Quayle
on the issues and called the Indiana senator ``what's-his-name.''
   Bentsen attacked Bush and other Republicans for questioning the
patriotism of Dukakis _ whom he introduced as a ``patriot from
Massachusetts'' _ saying that the Pledge of Allegiance belongs to
all Americans and that the Democratic ticket had an extra pledge of
its own.
   ``We won't allow America to be kicked around by countries more
than happy to play us for the loser,'' Bentsen said. ``We won't let
this nation wonder what on earth is going on behind closed doors in
Washington. ... No crazy deals cooked up in the White House
basement. No falling asleep at the switch while second-level aides
run that show.''
   That comment appeared to be a direct attack of President Reagan,
something both Dukakis and Bentsen have for the most part avoided
throughout the campaign.
   Earlier, joining Dukakis to accept the endorsement of Texas'
largest police organization, Bentsen portrayed Dukakis as a proven
crimefighter who has cut crime and drug use in his state and a
leader who would provide action instead of Republican ``words and
rhetoric.''
   He also hailed the successful launch of the space shuttle
Discovery as a sign that the United States was ready to reclaim its
leadership in space and technology.
   ``Watch out Russia .. we're going to take that leadership
away,'' he said. Bentsen watched the launch on television in
Tennessee before flying to Texas on Thursday morning.
</TEXT>
