<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Reagan-Hostages     09-30 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Hostages,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Hostages</HEAD>
<HEAD>No Direct Talks With Iran: White House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today there is no truth to
a report published in Israel that the United States has negotiated
successfully with Iran to gain the freedom of eight Americans and
one Briton held hostage in Lebanon.
   ``We are not negotiating directly with Iran. We have not talked
to the kidnappers,'' Reagan said shortly after arriving here on a
political trip.
   ``I think maybe Iran is putting these stories out,'' he added.
   The report, in the month-old Israeli weekly The Nation, said
that in exchange for the releases, beginning in about a week,
Washington will provide economic aid, gradually release billions of
dollars in Iranian funds frozen in U.S. banks and resume diplomatic
relations with Tehran.
   The newspaper, quoting unnamed sources, said the United States
and Iran had been negotiating directly on the matter since Monday
in Geneva. The hostages are believed to be held by pro-Iranian
Shiite Moslems.
   Flying here from Washington, presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater told reporters on Air Force One:
   ``There have been no face-to-face negotiations. There have
always been third-party contacts, but there have been no talks that
we directed or we participated in. ...
   ``The problem is, I cannot account for other people who may have
been talking to Iran ... (but) in the sense of the word (that) we
asked somebody (to talk for the United States), the answer is no.''
   The spokesman said that ``there is no one authorized to make a
deal for hostages or do anything that is contrary to our policy.
... We're always ready to talk at authorized levels. We make no
deals.''
</TEXT>
