<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Explosion     09-30 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Explosion,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blast At Chemical Lab Kills Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MCMASTERVILLE, Quebec (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion in a chemical research
lab Thursday killed four scientists and seriously injured another,
company officials said.
   Six people were in the lab of CIL Inc. when the explosion
occurred shortly after 9 a.m. CIL manfuctures explosives and
produces chemicals used in the forestry, agriculture and plastics
industries.
   The scientists were doing experiments on emulsion explosives,
which are used in mining and construction, said Dr. Michael
Wenkoff, director of the CIL Explosives and Technical Center, part
of a large CIL explosives research and manufacturing complex about
20 miles east of Montreal.
   ``There was an accidental explosion without any fire or fumes,''
said Wenkoff.
   He said there was no hazard to surrounding buildings. The
explosion was confined to a small building, and there were no signs
of damage outside.
   ``These people were very familiar with the chemicals and their
dangers,'' said Yvan Toupin, director of operations for CIL, who
said the cause of the accident has not been determined.
   Margaret Simpson, who lives behind the building said she was
home all morning but didn't hear the explosion.
   ``But there have been umpteen explosions,'' she said.
   The last serious accident at the plant was on Oct. 1, 1975, when
eight people were killed in an explosion.
</TEXT>
