<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     09-30 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem, Christian Cabinets Meet; Six Wounded In Army-Druse
Skirmish</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian and Druse forces agreed to a
cease-fire Friday after a five-hour skirmish, and rival Moslem and
Christian cabinets sought to defuse tensions in separate meetings.
   Police said six people were wounded when pro-Syrian militiamen
of the Druse, a mystical offshoot of Islam, and soldiers loyal to
Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun battled with mortars and
machine guns.
   It was not known which side provoked the clash in the mountain
resort of Souk el-Gharb, seven miles southeast of the Lebanese
capital, police said.
   The cease-fire was arranged by a security committee that
included representatives of the army and the principal militias,
said a police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   An informal cease-fire halted fighting in the Christian-Moslem
civil war in 1986. But the threat of formal partition rose last
week after separate cabinets claimed power last week.
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, heads the Christian cabinet. He was
appointed prime minister by President Amin Gemayel on Sept. 22,
minutes before Gemayel's six-year term ended.
   Moslems rejected the appointment, insisting the legal cabinet is
that of Salim Hoss, acting prime minister under Gemayel. Hoss is a
Sunni Moslem.
   Under an unwritten covenant that dates to Lebanon's independence
from France in 1943, the president must be a Maronite, the prime
minister a Sunni and Parliament speaker a Shiite Moslem.
   On Friday, the Moslem cabinet decided to promote army and police
officers, a move that was adopted by Aoun's Christian cabinet in
its first meeting Tuesday.
   Aoun's three-man cabinet also met Friday. It decided to ensure
supplies of ``bread, flour, fuel and butane ... in east and west
Beirut as well as throughout Lebanon,'' Aoun told reporters after
the meeting.
   Hoss' cabinet also adopted a similar decision.
   Aoun's cabinet reminded government employees and other civil
servants to follow only ``the instructions issued by the
constitutional cabinet'' which was appointed by former President
Amin Gemayel Sept. 22, minutes before he ended his six-year term.
   The two cabinets said their decisions on promoting army and
police officers must be referred to Lebanon's 76-man Parliament for
ratification.
   The dual cabinets have separately noted that their main goal is
to speed up the election of a president to rule the war-torn nation.
   By Sept. 23, Parliament had failed three times in five weeks to
convene and elect a successor to Gemayel. House Speaker Hussein
Husseini, a Shiite Moslem, has indefinitely postponed the election
session.
   A boycott by Christian Parliament members prevented it from
attaining the 51-member quorum needed to vote for a new president.
   The boycott reflected opposition to the candidacy of
Syrian-backed Suleiman Franjieh and Mikhail Daher. The Christians
charged Franjieh and Daher would change Lebanon into a Syrian
satellite.
   Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon. It has 40,000 troops
in eastern and northern provinces as well as in west and south
Beirut.
</TEXT>
