<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Glance     09-30 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Glance,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Political System at a Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, is how political power is
apportioned in Soviet society:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE POLITBURO _ This 12-member group of top Communist Party
members is in fact the ruling body of the Soviet Union. Among its
members are Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the party's general secretary;
Prime Minister Nikolai I. Ryzhkov and Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze. The Politburo customarily holds weekly closed-door
sessions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CENTRAL COMMITTEE _ The party's policy-making body is in theory
its top organ between party congresses, held every five years. The
300-member Central Committee assembles local party leaders,
high-ranking Moscow government and party officials, military and
KGB brass and other national figures. The Central Committee elects
the party's general secretary, the post held by Gorbachev since
March 1985, and the members of the Politburo.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SUPREME SOVIET _ By law the country's top law-making body, the
1,500-member parliament in reality does little more than give legal
force to decisions of the party leadership. Gorbachev wants a third
chamber of 750 deputies added to the bicameral Supreme Soviet, and
a more active national legislature of about 400 representatives
elected from among the enlarged body.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE COMMUNIST PARTY _ It is the sole Soviet party since the 1917
Russian Revolution. Gorbachev now wants to get its 20 million
members out of daily government and economic management, but has
served notice that rival political parties will not be tolerated.
</TEXT>
