<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Germany-Libya 1stLd-Writethru a0663 09-30 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany Names Ambassador To Libya; First Since Berlin Bombing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Foreign Ministry citing
changes in Libya, comments about Gadhafi, U.S. claiming increased
Libyan terrorism. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany appointed an ambassador
to Libya for the first time since the 1986 bombing of a Berlin
disco that U.S. officials blamed on the north African nation, a
Foreign Ministry spokesman said Friday.
   ``We see in Libya positive changes, politically and economically
and in terms of foreign policy,'' said the spokesman, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   He cited as one example Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi's
decision to release prisoners from the fighting with neighboring
Chad, as well as unspecified ``internal reforms.''
   The April 5, 1986, attack on West Berlin's popular La Belle
disco killed two U.S. military personnel and a Turkish woman and
injured about 230 other people.
   Citing what it said was proof of Libyan involvement in the La
Belle attack, the United States bombed the Libyan cities of Tripoli
and Benghazi 10 days later in retaliation.
   That May, the last West German ambassador left Tripoli the end
of his three-year tour and was not replaced due to the controversy
over the La Belle bombing, the spokesman said.
   But since then, West Berlin authorities have said they have no
concrete indications that Libya was involved. Some West Berlin
officials have said they suspect Syria may have been behind the
disco attack.
   The Foreign Ministry spokesman said Juergen Hellner, who speaks
fluent Arabic, will be sent to Libya next month as the new
ambassador. A standard West German biographical reference book,
``Wer Ist Wer?'' said that Hellner served as the deputy chief of
West Germany's diplomatic mission in Syria in the early 1970s.
   The spokesman said there was ``no connection'' between the
appointment and the still inconclusive Berlin probe.
   ``We simply decided that we would have a better diplomatic
presence by being represented by an ambassador,'' the spokesman
said.
   Asked specifically whether Bonn officials believe Gadhafi has
backed off from a worldwide terrorism campaign, the spokesman said:
``If you take Gadhafi at his word, there has been a change. We hope
that has changed for the better, but we will have to wait and see.''
   But the top U.S. counter-terrorism official said in Washington
this week that Libya is supporting a renewed terrorist campaign led
by Palestine-born Abu Nidal.
   Ambassador-at-large L. Paul Bremer also told reporters that
Libya is using surrogates such as the Japanese Red Army in the
terror campaign. The United States has no diplomatic ties to Libya.
   West Germany will rejoin West European nations such as Spain,
France, Denmark, Greece and Italy that have ambassadors to Libya.
Italy is Libya's largest trading partner.
   Libya is West Germany's No. 2 oil supplier, behind Britain.
   Britain broke diplomatic relations with Gadhafi's government in
1984 after a London policewoman was shot to death during a protest
against the radical leader outside the Libyan Embassy in London.
   Since the departure of the previous ambassador, West Germany has
been represented in Libya by a charge d'affaires.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
