<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Landing Bjt   09-30 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Landing, Bjt,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tourists Can View Shuttle Land With Rattlesnakes, at Least One
Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A patch of the Mojave
Desert will be open for anyone who wants to watch Discovery land
Monday, but spectators will have to endure traffic jams, chemical
toilets _ and maybe even rattlesnakes.
   NASA expects 100,000 to 200,000 visitors at the viewing site on
the hard clay east shore of Rogers Dry Lake, where the space
shuttle is scheduled to touch down at 9:33 a.m. PDT, said Nancy
Lovato, a spokeswoman for the space agency.
   The record crowd for a landing was the estimated 500,000 people
who joined President Reagan in witnessing the July 4, 1982, landing
of Columbia on a paved runway at this military base 80 miles
northeast of Los Angeles.
   This time George Bush will attend, in his capacity as vice
president, not as the Republican presidential candidate, his aides
emphatically told National Aeronautics and Space Administration
spokesman Ralph Jackson.
   The viewing site opens 24 hours before the landing. Jackson
predicted heavy traffic along the desert highways, ``And remember,
all the Air Police fellows out there got radar.''
   Lovato said the worst traffic jams will occur before dawn. Haley
said all gates to Edwards Air Force Base will be closed to the
general public, and access to the east shore viewing site _ which
doesn't require a vehicle pass or entry through any of the gates _
will be halted one hour before the landing.
   ``No gasoline is available at the viewing site,'' a NASA fact
sheet advised. ``No shelter from the sun will be available. No
telephones will be available. No plumbing or electricity will be
available. No dumping facilities for RV toilets will be available.''
   However, dozens of portable, chemical toilets already have been
placed on the lakeshore viewing site. Very little water or food
will be available, so spectators are advised to bring their own.
   The fact sheet also warned: ``Rattlesnakes are present and must
be respected.''
   ``People can camp out there, and if they have a recreational
vehicle, they'd be well advised to do that,'' Lovato said.
   Bush will watch the landing from the roof of NASA's building
here or from a ramp by NASA's hangar, which Lovato said also has
been invaded by rattlers at times.
   As for the general public, ``Somebody who wanders out of where
they're supposed to be into the hills behind the viewing site could
encounter some rattlesnakes,'' Haley said.
   But he said he's not aware of any snakebite victims among
spectators at past shuttle landings.
   ``Usually with all the people and vehicles, there's so much
noise the snakes stay away,'' Lovato said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
