<DOCNO> AP880930-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1607EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GromykoProfile     09-30 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gromyko Profile,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Familiar `Mr. Nyet' Moves Offstage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Kremlin Shake-up, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei A. Gromyko, whose unsmiling countenance and
tough talk personified the Soviet Union for nearly three decades,
is making a graceful exit by Soviet standards.
   The 79-year-old president, who represented his government as
foreign minister through most of the post-Stalin era, was retired
Friday from his post on the ruling Communist Party Politburo,
ostensibly at his own request. He is expected to surrender the
largely ceremonial presidency at a Saturday meeting of the Supreme
Soviet, or parliament.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev praised the outgoing
president for his ``great work and faithful service'' to the
Communist Party and the Soviet nation, indicating Gromyko is
leaving in good standing.
   As a further indication he remained in good stead, Gromyko's
comment that he was sad to be leaving but that ``age is a stubborn
thing'' was read on the national evening news, along with
Gorbachev's praise.
   Nicknamed ``Old Stoneface'' by the Western diplomats who faced
him through years of negotiations and East-West tensions, Gromyko
remained a symbol of continuity after Gorbachev moved him aside
three years ago to install Eduard A. Shevardnadze, a newcomer to
foreign policy, as the head of the Foreign Ministry.
   Since then, he has appeared at official functions, greeted
foreign visitors and performed various ceremonial tasks.
   In his longtime role as foreign policy chief, he was respected
by those who faced him across the bargaining table for his ability
to precisely enunciate Soviet policy and his voluminous knowledge
of historical detail.
   He always stuck to the official line and was known as a stubborn
negotiator who would rather walk away from negoatiations than
compromise on an issue critical to his government.
   After joining the Foreign Ministry and being posted to
Washington at the outbreak of World War II, Gromyko became
ambassador to the United States. In 1946, he was named his
country's first permanent U.N. representative.
   During the world body's formative years, he earned the nickname
``Mr. Nyet'' for the 26 vetoes he cast in the Security Council and
his frequent walkouts.
   Nikita Khrushchev, who elevated him to foreign minister, told
the United Nations that Gromyko was so loyal he would drop his
pants and sit on a block of ice if Khrushchev told him to. Gromyko
sat impassively as his leader spoke, as he did again several years
later when Khrushchev startled the General Assembly by removing his
shoe and banging it on his desk.
   Gromyko was a player in every superpower confrontation for more
than a quarter-century but rarely shared his private insights. His
memoirs, published after he left the Foreign Ministry, were most
notable for their lack of spicy detail.
   Although he was generally regarded as a party hardliner, Gromyko
reportedly played a pivotal role in the selection of the reformer
Gorbachev to take over the Soviet leadership in March 1985.
   Although Gorbachev removed him from the foreign minister's post
he had held for 26 years, the party chief kept him on in a visible
role as chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the
equivalent of the presidency.
   Gromyko's advancing age made his replacement inevitable, but
Gorbachev practically set a timetable for his retirement at the
party's national conference in June when he proposed a new
governmental structure with a strong president elected by an
expanded Congress of Peoples' Deputies.
   Gorbachev is expected to seek that post, probably in the spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880930-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan-WrigleyField     09-30 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Wrigley Field,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Visits Wrigley Field, Does Play-by-Play</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, recalling his early days as a
radio announcer, visited Wrigley Field on Friday, calling the
play-by-play for a television broadcast of a Chicago Cubs baseball
game.
   Reagan, who had been scheduled to speak to a group of ethnic
leaders and attend a GOP fund-raiser during Friday's visit, made an
unscheduled stop at the venerable ballpark for a National League
game between the Cubs and Pittsburgh Pirates.
   In his early days as a radio broadcaster in Davenport and Des
Moines, Iowa, Reagan used to re-create Cubs games on the air using
wire-service play-by-play.
   ``You know, in a few months I'm going to be out of work and I
thought I might as well audition,'' Reagan said after he was
introduced by Cubs announcer Harry Caray.
   Reagan called part of the first inning and the top half of the
second.
   Here's how he called the scoring play when the Cubs took a 1-0
lead in the bottom of the first:
   ``And there are still men on first and third. And there goes a
ball over second base and it's a hit out into center field.
   ``One run in. Men on first and third.''
   Reagan chatted with Caray and fellow announcer Steve Stone,
telling them his present job is more difficult than making up Cubs
play-by-play 50 years ago.
   ``Since I did the Cubs games by telegraphic report, I don't
think it was as hard as the present job, because by the time I got
the slip of paper it had already happened,'' he said.
   Before entering the broadcast booth, Reagan donned a red, white
and blue Cubs warm-up jacket and threw out the ceremonial first
pitch.
   From his vantage point, Caray called it ``high and inside.''
</TEXT>
