<DOCNO> AP880930-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Boosters 1stLd-Writethru a0731 09-30 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Boosters, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,790</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: To UPDATE with Marshall official's comment, SUB lead and 4th
graf prv: ``Our people...;'' with 1 graf, pick up 5th graf:
``A-double-plus.''
^Discovery's Boosters Returned For Examination</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CSB2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovery's solid fuel boosters,
looking ``absolutely perfect'' except for slight discoloration,
were pulled ashore Friday for scrutiny by anxious experts who
revamped the rockets after the Challenger disaster.
   As curious gray-and-white seagulls squawked and glided overhead,
two recovery ships brought the empty casings into Port Canaveral's
choppy waters. Dozens of camera-armed tourists and some NASA
officials looked on.
   Other than some blackening at their bottoms and discoloration
attributed to the flames of liftoff, the 149-foot-long,
200,000-pound reusable boosters showed no outward signs of problems.
   ``It looked absolutely perfect,'' said John Thomas, who headed
oversight of the booster redesign for the Marshall Space Flight
Center in Huntsville, Ala., the NASA center responsible for shuttle
propulsion.
   ``A-double-plus,'' was the estimate from Rocky Raab, spokesman
for Morton Thiokol Inc. of Brigham City, Utah, which build the
boosters.
   Rabb said divers who got the first look said they seemed ``in
perfect condition,'' adding that they ``would see evidence if the
joints were leaking ... there was none of that.''
   He said Morton Thiokol's contract specifications called for a
plus-or-minus 3 percent range in the pressure (pounds per square
inch) used by the boosters in blastoff, and the data returned
Thursday showed a deviation of only .09 percent.
   Divers waiting with special attachment devices in recovery ships
150 miles east of the Kennedy Space Center got to the boosters
quickly after they dropped off the shuttle two minutes, four
seconds after liftoff, their 81-feet-per-second descent slowed by
parachutes Thursday. Both were at Port Canaveral before noon,
several hours earlier than expected.
   As soon as the first booster was brought to port by the recovery
ship Freedom Star , an orange-suited safety inspector went out to
meet it in a lifeboat and crawled inside to begin taking a close
look and to check for leaks of volatile hydrazine.
   The boosters were then headed to a hangar at the Cape Canaveral
Air Force Station where technicians will use high-powered water
sprays to ensure safety and to clean them. Within two weeks, they
will taken apart under the watchful eyes of NASA officials and
technical experts of Morton Thiokol.
   Within two months they should be back at the Utah plant for
further examination and, barr notoriety after the Challenger
disaster, in which the boosters were blamed for causing the
explosion, piqued interest, along with television images Thursday
of flames spewing up the boosters' sides.
   ``It's pretty impressive. I'm pretty well informed on these; Ich and
people
remember what happened to Challenger, people looked at that and
they forgot that it's normal,'' said Raab.
   It was a failed joint that led to the Jan. 28, 1986, Challenger
destruction, killing seven astronauts. A presidential commission
that investigated the accident found that rubberized O-rings did
not seal, allowing flame to escape.
   To return the grounded shuttle fleet to space as soon as
possible, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration chose
to redesign the Challenger-style boosters, a process that took 32
months instead of the four to five years required to develop an
entirely new design.
   NASA made 145 changes and then subjected the boosters to the
most rigorous testing program ever conducted for solid-fueled
rockets.
   The boosters are the largest solid-fueled rockets ever built.
   Loaded with 1.1 million pounds of propellant, each booster
weighs 1.3 million pounds and produces 3.3 million pounds of
thrust. The two boosters used in each shuttle launch provide 80
percent of the power need to reach orbit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
