<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Routine Bjt   09-30 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Routine, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sound And Fury Over, The Real Work Begins</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fire, smoke and roar of
thundering rockets captures the attention of the nation, but it's
after the shuttle settles quietly into orbit that the real business
of space travel begins.
   Getting to space and returning may be the most fun, but being
there is the reason for the whole adventure. And the part that is
least noted by most Americans.
   NASA officials expressed elation and relief as Discovery slipped
smoothly into orbit. The spectacular launch proved to the world
that America's space agency had recovered from the flawed boosters
that destroyed Challenger 2{ years ago, killed seven crew members
and grounded the whole shuttle fleet.
   The moment of applause, of intense spotlighted attention, of
excitement and public triumph, passed within hours. Now it was time
to take up again the real purpose of flying in space.
   For the astronauts, this meant settling into a routine
controlled rigidly by a script that NASA calls the ``crew activity
plan.''
   The plan is designed to squeeze something useful out every of
precious astronaut minute in orbit. Waking, sleeping, eating and
working, the astronaut in space is directed by the ``CAP.''
   To make even a slight change in procedures, the astronauts are
supposed to get permission from engineers on the ground. ``Mission
Control Center'' is an accurate description of that command post in
Houston.
   Most of the work of astronauts in space concentrates on the
grinding routine and small details of scientists and engineers
exploring a new frontier and trying to build a body of
understanding. Progress is inch by inch and is seldom the stuff for
headlines or for the main story on the evening television news.
   Harassed astronauts may spend hours working quietly to conclude
a tedious task and then report the results in a single phrase:
``Houston, step five completed.'' Not exactly words that grab
national attention.
   Yet, it is from such work that the ultimate benefits from space
will be achieved.
   Aboard Discovery, the astronauts are working hour after hour
conducting experiments in medicine, materials processing, weather
observations and communications. They seldom take time to chat with
Mission Control and when they do, they speak in the spare shorthand
of technical minds hard at work.
   It's unlikely the four-day mission will provide a major
breakthrough that overnight will change the lives of people on
Earth. But each test will add another bit of new knowledge, perhaps
a single page in a growing library of understanding.
   Voyages to new frontiers are noted for their beginning and
ending. The hard work in between is seldom recalled. Who remembers
what Columbus did in the middle of the Atlantic on some September
day in 1492? It's his departure for the unknown and his arrival in
a new world that are honored.
   So, too, for Discovery. Its launch harvested headlines because
it marked America's return to space. And the shuttle landing on
Monday will again capture attention because daring men have
returned safely to Earth. But it is the work in between, the long,
quiet hours in space, that may eventually be the most important.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
