<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0743,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Picks Up More Police Endorsements</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Johnson to Jacobson in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush tweaked rival
Michael Dukakis again Friday by traveling to the governor's home
state to claim the endorsements of two Massachusetts law
enforcement organizations.
   During a day in which he also courted voters in New Jersey and
Connecticut with a tough-on-crime pitch, Bush made a foray into
Massachusetts to accept the backing of the International
Brotherhood of Police Officers, Local 264, and the Springfield
Police Supervisors Association.
   The president of the first group, Robert Jacobson, told a small
gathering outside Springfield police headquarters that ``Michael
Dukakis is soft on crime and George Bush is tough on crime.''
   Bush called the state's prison furlough program under Dukakis
``a national disgrace'' and said he appreciated the endorsement
because ``you know the truth not just about me but about my
opponent as well.''
   ``I am running as myself, and my opponent is running from
himself,'' he said.
   The Bush campaign did not announce the Springfield stop until
about three hours ahead of time to avoid a counter-attack by
Dukakis, press secretary Sheila Tate acknowledged.
   When Bush was recently endorsed by the Boston Police Patrolmen's
Association, Dukakis quickly put together his own big law
enforcement show of support the same day.
   Also on Friday, Bush campaigned in New Jersey and went into
heavily Democratic Paterson County to pick up the endorsement of
five locals of the Police Benevolent Association.
   Bush campaign officials said their analysis agrees with local
polls that show the race even in New Jersey, which has 16 electoral
votes, and close in Connecticut with eight electoral votes.
   The campaign is making a concerted push for the middle-class
Democrats who crossed party lines to vote for President Reagan.
That appeal was part of Friday's law-and-order and anti-drug
message.
   In New Jersey, Bush and Gov. Thomas Kean also met in the morning
with a group of black ministers who helped Kean in his last
gubernatorial race.
   Bush spoke to a rally in Paterson, where he said he would
appoint tough judges and support the death penalty for drug
kingpins and murderers of police officers.
   The public address system for Bush's outdoor speech was turned
up as a band of about 30 demonstrators, many of them young people,
chanted loudly from across the street, ``Where was George?''
   The motorcade buses were moved into the street blocking the
protesters' view of the rally. Police officers also stood in the
streets in front of them.
   Passaic County Sheriff Edwin Englehardt, in his introductory
remarks, said, ``There's half a dozen kids across the street. They
represent the ACLU, Mr. Vice President, but don't worry about that.
The vast majority of people are law-abiding and they're for you.''
   Bush frequently criticizes the American Civil Liberties Union
and Dukakis' membership in it.
   The vice president ridiculed Dukakis' environmental campaign
trip to New Jersey on Thursday and took a familiar swipe at the
water pollution in Boston Harbor under Dukakis' governorship.
   ``My opponent had the nerve yesterday to come in here and talk
about oceans you can't swim in. You tried to drink the water in
Boston Harbor recently? Don't do it,'' Bush said.
   Then, poking fun at his own misstatement of the date of the
Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, Bush quipped, ``I may have a
little trouble remembering Pearl Harbor, but I don't have any
trouble remembering Boston Harbor.''
   Bush also spoke at Ridgefield Memorial High School in
Ridgefield, N.J., where he told students to shun drugs and
encourage their parents not to use drugs. He warned against
``enabling behavior'' in which students keep quiet while their
friends abuse drugs.
   ``Make it uncool to do drugs,'' he said.
   Bush later headed to Hartford, Conn., to meet with Roman
Catholic Archbishop John Whealon and to address a rally at St.
Joseph College.
</TEXT>
