<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1704EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SchoolShooting     09-30 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Shooting,0540</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Funeral Held For First Of Two Killed</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``perfect child'' was buried Friday
when friends and family gathered to mourn one of two 8-year-old
girls who died after a gunman opened fire in their school, wounding
nine other people.
   Shequila Bradley died in the school after a man identified as
James William Wilson, 19, of Greenwood, walked in Monday and began
shooting.
   Tequila Jones died Thursday; her funeral was set for Sunday.
   ``Shequila was the kind of child that always wanted to please
people. If there had been the perfect child, she would have been
it,'' Eleanor Rice, principal of Oakland Elementary School, said at
Friday's funeral.
   Wilson has been charged with two counts of murder and is
undergoing psychiatric testing at the State Hospital in Columbia.
   The Greenville News reported Friday that a state mental health
center had rejected two attempts since 1986 by Wilson's relatives
to have him involuntarily committed for psychiatric care.
   ``The only comfort I have at this point is that I know she's
with God _ he only takes the best,'' Mrs. Rice told a
standing-room-only audience at the New Jerusalem Deliverance Church.
   The girl's mother, Lynn Bradley, had to be carried into the
funeral.
   ``She was crazy about her kids, Shequila was her heart,'' said a
neighbor, Lena Moore. ``If you lost your baby _ that's a lot to
think about.''
   Among the flowers arranged around Shequila's coffin was a
bicycle of flowers, made by some of Shequila's friends.
   ``Oakland will never be the same, but we'll always remember her
with that special smile,'' the principal told relatives, school
officials and faculty, classmates, and friends.
   Relatives have described Wilson as a hyperactive recluse who has
been in and out of a hospital psychiatric unit during the past
eight months.
   Retired Probate Judge Rosemary M. Trakas told the Greenville
newspaper that Wilson's family filed affidavits for involuntary
commitment and Wilson was evaluated by a state mental health center.
   She told the newspaper that, after the evaluation, Beckman
Mental Health officials declined to admit Wilson into the state
mental hospital system.
   The Department of Mental Health ``can't confirm or deny that a
person has been a patient or has received treatment from the
department,'' spokeswoman Susan Craft said Friday. ``That's the
law. It's a confidentiality statute.''
   Neighbors of the Bradley family say the neighborhood has been
devastated.
   ``It's torn up this neighborhood,'' said Mrs. Moore. ``I felt
like I lost one of my own children, I'm still hurting.''
   ``The whole neighborhood just hates that this happened to a
little child for something stupid,'' said Mrs. Moore.
   ``Anyone who just sits around and thinks about doing this, they
shouldn't just let him get off 'cause he's crazy,'' she said.
   Eight-year-old Jana Moore said she knew Shequila well.
   ``She used to spend the night over my house, and she used to go
over my grandmother's house,'' Jana said. ``I was in the class next
door when he shot Shequila. We heard noise like someone getting
beat with a whip, but it was that man shooting.''
</TEXT>
