<2ND_LINE>AM-Commuter-Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0766,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA: South Pacific Island Airways Certificate Not Surrendered</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after 6th graf pvs, ``But Farrar,'' to
UPDATE with comments from Grand Canyon Airlines official</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said
Friday that a further check of its records indicated that South
Pacific Island Airways has not _ as the agency said previously _
surrendered its commuter airline operating certificate.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said South Pacific Island's status was
rechecked after complaints from the airline about its inclusion
Thursday in a list of seven air carriers that the FAA said had
surrendered their certificates before scheduled safety inspections.
   South Pacific Island continues to operate commuter service in
the America Samoa islands, although it did turn in a certificate as
a charter airline after deciding not to continue operating such
flights, Farrar said.
   Meanwhile, a spokesman for the parent company of Texas National
Airlines of San Antonio disputed the FAA statement that it had
surrendered its commuter license.
   Brian Loflin, corporate communications director for Fairchild
Aircraft Corp. of San Antonio, Texas, said Texas National, a
subsidiary of Fairchild, got out of the commuter business in August
but did not surrender its certificate and continues flying as a
charter service.
   But Farrar said FAA records show the airline had surrendered the
certificate that had allowed it to provide scheduled commuter
service, although he said Texas National continues to provide
on-demand air taxi service.
   Another airline also disputed FAA assertion that it surrendered
its commuter certificate.
   Ron Warren, general manager of Grand Canyon Airlines, said the
airline no longer operates commuter services but continues to fly
sightseeing charters over the Grand Canyon.
   Warren said the certificate it uses for the sightseeing tours is
the same as its commuter certificate. But Farrar said while the
airline's sightseeing flights may not be affected, its license to
operate scheduled commuter service was surrendered.
   The airlines were among more than 35 commuter airlines that had
been targeted for special safety inspections under a broader FAA
probe of the commuter airline industry's compliance with federal
safety regulations.
</TEXT>
