<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1725EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Peacekeepers Bjt   09-30 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peacekeepers, Bjt,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNIFIL: A Mission Impossible?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAJDAL ZOUN, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours after the Nobel Peace Prize
was awarded to U.N. peacekeepers, six rounds of machine-gun fire
blasted into the hill behind a U.N. observation post near this
south Lebanese village.
   ``It's just part of our job,'' said Lt. Arjun Sapkota, 29, of
Nepal, who said being shot at is not an unusual experience here.
   The post's 5,800 soldiers of the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon,
or UNIFIL, undoubtedly have one of the most difficult missions of
the seven United Nations forces sharing the prize _ watching 240
square miles of southern Lebanon.
   UNIFIL was deployed in 1978 to supervise the withdrawal of an
Israeli invading force. But the Israelis haven't fully withdrawn
and UNIFIL is sandwiched between them and a myriad of militias that
have sprouted in Lebanon.
   ``It has seemed a mission impossible at times,'' said Lt. Col.
Gerry McMahon, of Ireland, UNIFIL's senior operations officer and a
veteran of U.N. peace missions in Zaire, Cyprus, Syria and Lebanon.
   Still, he said, UNIFIL has made a difference in a country
factionalized by 13 years of civil war and at odds with its Israeli
neighbor.
   ``If UNIFIL didn't exist here, this place would be a
battlefield,'' McMahon said. ``We have been a stabilizing influence
in southern Lebanon.''
   UNIFIL troops, with headquarters in the southern town of
Naquora, can be distinguished by their pale blue helmets and berets
and the blue-and-white banner that flies above their observation
posts and roadside checkpoints. Nepal, Fiji, Ireland, Ghana,
Finland, Norway, Sweden, France and Italy contribute to the force.
   UNIFIL has paid dearly. About 156 men have died in service, and
more than 230 have been wounded. Two are missing. American Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins, leader of a truce observer group attached to
UNIFIL, was kidnapped Feb. 17 by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
militiamen.
   An Irish soldier, Pvt. Brian Joyce, has been missing for seven
years; he has not been seen since he disappeared from a desolate
outpost.
   There is little to suggest the danger will abate soon.
   ``The fact is that we are trying to do our job while what
amounts to a war is going on around us,'' McMahon said. ``It's
inevitable we get caught in the middle.''
   As envisioned by the U.N. Security Council in 1978, the U.N.
force was given a mandate to supervise Israel's withdrawal and help
the Lebanese army reestablish authority in the region.
   Instead, Israel continues to hold a strip of land along the
border as a security zone and augmented its forces with an
Israeli-equipped and trained militia known as the South Lebanon
Army, a Christian-dominated group.
   Palestinian guerrillas, largely driven out of southern Lebanon
by a second Israeli invasion in 1982, have been replaced by
increasingly militant Shiite militias.
   The Iran-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, is among militias
hostile to all foreign presence and which continue to try and
penetrate UNIFIL territory to attack Israel.
   The U.N. soldiers have ended up being victimized by both sides.
   In 1985, the South Lebanon Army abducted 21 Finnish soldiers and
held them for more than a week after alleging they had helped seven
of its militiamen defect to Moslem groups.
   In 1986, several French soldiers were killed in a series of
attacks blamed on Iranian-backed Shiite fighters angered over the
sale of French weapons to Iran's Persian Gulf war foe, Iraq.
   Eighteen months ago, a car bomb exploded beside a Fijian
checkpoint, killing three soldiers.
   Since the start of this year, more than 864 incidents have been
reported in which bullets or artillery fell on or near U.N.
positions.
   But UNIFIL has succeeded, to some extent, in returning normalcy
to the more than 500,000 people who live in the territory under its
supervision.
   Militiamen are not allowed to enter the region with weapons, and
UNIFIL sponsors medical and food relief programs to help the
largely Shiite population.
   It does not always succeed in its job as referee.
   On Friday, for example, members of the Shiite militia Amal set
up a ``checkpoint'' on a tiny village road near Majdal Zoun,
apparently to try to halt any suspected members of the rival
Hezbollah. Tension between the two militias has been running high
since three Amal leaders were slain last week, apparently by
Hezbollah fighters.
   Meanwhile, Israel complains that groups intent on attacking the
Jewish state, including Palestinian guerrillas, have made it
through UNIFIL territory undetected.
   ``We do try to watch everything,'' said Nepalese Corp. Arjun
Dahal, as he peered trough field glasses at the surrounding hills.
``I watch positions for any movement or firing that takes place and
I report it immediately so we can get it stopped.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
