<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen     09-30 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Focuses On Education; Says Quayle Resume Empty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen ridiculed George Bush's
education promises, saying the vice president's ``record on
education is as empty as Dan Quayle's resume.''
   The Democratic vice presidential nominee addressed an early
afternoon rally in Charlotte before heading to Washington to accept
the National Education Association endorsement of Bentsen and
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis. The Texas senator was taking
the weekend off to preprare for his debate next week with Quayle.
   At the rally, Bentsen thanked North Carolina for hosting the
debate between Dukakis and Bush and said the showdown proved ``that
Mike Dukakis is the one who is in mainstream America.
   ``Every time that Mike Dukakis starting talking about crucial
issues that face America _ about drugs and housing and health care
and education and Social Security _ it seemed that George Bush had
nothing to say for himself,'' Bentsen said.
   Bentsen promoted the Democratic ticket's chances in the South
and specifically mentioned Texas and North Carolina _ two major
Dukakis-Bentsen targets.
   His text also included Arkansas, another state where the
Democrats are counting on a win, but he did not mention either
Mississippi or Alabama, states that several Dukakis aides have
conceded privately appear out of reach and among states that will
be de-emphasized in the final weeks of the campaign.
   At one point in his speech Bentsen mistakenly referred to being
in South Carolina, another state where Dukakis aides concede
privately that their chances are slim, but quickly corrected
himself. ``Let's get the message to them, too,'' he said to laughs
from the crowd.
   Bentsen said Dukakis had a key Southern value _ fiscal
conservatism _ and said it stood in stark contrast to the
Reagan-Bush record of deficit spending.
   ``George Bush likes to talk about balanced budgets,'' Bentsen
said. ``It's like Dan Quayle talking about his resume. There's
nothing to say.''
   He adopted a similar line for his later speech to the NEA
convention in Washington.
   ``George Bush woke up one morning and decided he wanted to be
the education president, but there is no evidence that he has ever
lifted a hand to help education in America, I'll tell you,''
Bentsen said in the text of that address. ``His record on education
is as empty as Dan Quayle's resume.''
   The senator, in the speech to the labor group, said the Reagan
administration as undermined a number of education programs,
including funding for college loans, remedial education and teacher
improvement.
   Bentsen said Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, had taken his
state from 40th to 10th in terms of per-student spending while also
supporting programs to improve teacher quality. He also touted
Dukakis' proposal to allow students to repay college loans through
long-term payroll deductions.
   At the North Carolina rally, which was attended by about 500
people, Bentsen promised a strong national defense and an
administration ``ready to pay the price to defend freedom.''
   As for the debate, Bentsen told reporters aboard his plane he
would spend most of the weekend preparing and practicing. Advisers
who helped Dukakis prepare for his debate are part of the Bentsen
effort.
</TEXT>
