<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NewJerseySenate 2ndLd-Writethru a0691 09-30 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Jersey Senate, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0691,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negative New Jersey Senate Race Called `Barroom Brawl'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 7th graf to CORRECT Dawkins' age to 50 sted 43, bgng
``Dawkins...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $15 million race between New Jersey Sen.
Frank Lautenberg and Republican Peter Dawkins has reached such a
level of nastiness that the challenger describes the contest as a
``barroom brawl.''
   In the past few weeks, Dawkins has put television commercials on
the air that brand Lautenberg as an extreme liberal in the
tradition of actress Jane Fonda and former Sen. George McGovern.
   Lautenberg has fired back with his own ads accusing Dawkins, a
Michigan native, of being a carpetbagger.
   ``This is going to be a tough, rock 'em-sock 'em 15 rounds. No
hold barred,'' Dawkins says. ``This is a barroom brawl.''
   The two men in the race come from widely differing backgrounds
and styles.
   Lautenberg, 64, made his fortune in the computer business and
won his first term in the Senate in 1982, coming from behind in the
race against Millicent Fenwick.
   Dawkins, 50, is a retired Army brigadier general, Rhodes
Scholar, with Hollywood good looks and a parade-ground presence.
   The two sides say they'll spend between $7 million and $8
million each, mainly buying expensive New York and Philadelphia
television time.
   While pre-Labor Day campaigning focused on issues, both
candidates have detoured in the final stretch of the campaign.
   Lautenberg has aired TV spots that accuse Dawkins of using New
Jersey as a ``political pit stop,'' and of exaggerating his
already-impressive resume. ``C'mon Pete, be real,'' is a Lautenberg
campaign slogan.
   Lautenberg, who co-founded and ran the worldwide Automatic Data
Processing Corp., has stood in the political shadow of fellow Sen.
Bill Bradley, D-N.J., who is touted every four years as
presidential stock.
   And because New Jersey, with no statewide newspaper or
television channel, is blanketed by the giant media markets of New
York and Philadelphia, Lautenberg has been frustrated in drawing
news media attention to himself. New York Mayor Edward Koch is a
more familar face to many New Jersey viewers than their junior
senator.
   Lautenberg insists he has done a good job for New Jersey, but
acknowledges not enough constituents connect his name with his
record.
   But, Lautenberg says, ``When they hear that I wrote the law to
put people who dump plastics in the ocean in jail, they love it.''
   Dawkins, despite arriving in the state just last year, has
gained the loyalty of most Republicans. However, he's been bruised
by some unflattering press and an insensitive gaffe in April.
   After he settled in the posh suburb of Rumson, N.J., Dawkins
confessed to reporters he'd rather be in Washington. ``I'd blow my
brains out if I had to live in a small town,'' he said.
   Once stiff, almost arrogant, Dawkins has begun to loosen up. He
is greeted as a star and delivers a practiced campaign speech that
blends pride in New Jersey with Lautenberg-bashing.
   Top New Jersey Republicans courted Dawkins away from Wall
Street, where he prospered after leaving the Army in 1983.
   Born in Michigan, and a childhood victim of polio, Dawkins was
an academic and athletic star at West Point, winning the 1959
Heisman Trophy. He studied at Oxford as a Rhodes Scholar, and
earned a Ph.D. at Princeton. In a 24-year Army career, Dawkins was
a Vietnam hero and, at 43, an unusually young brigadier general.
   Yet, Lautenberg and his aides have repeatedly accused Dawkins of
gilding the lily.
   The challenger's campaign was caught adverstising Dawkins as
wounded in Vietnam, which he was not. Early campaign literature
said Dawkins served two tours in the Asian conflict. He served one
full tour, and returned for a few months in a non-combat role.
   Dawkins corrected the exaggerations himself.
   Like Dawkins, Lautenberg has an impressive background.
   Raised in poverty, he served in the Army in World War II and
went to college on the G.I. bill. He co-founded the ADP Corp. and,
in 30 years, amassed a fortune estimated near $40 million.
</TEXT>
