<DOCNO> AP880930-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan-Politics     09-30 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Politics,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Seeks Midwest Support for Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 13-14 for release at 8 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, trying to score political
points for George Bush in the Midwest, said Friday their
administration has worked to recover ``bedrock values'' after
taking the White House from the Democrats.
   ``There really are only two things the liberals don't understand
_ the things that change and the things that don't,'' Reagan told
some 1,500 people gathered for lunch at Wozniak's Casino, a Polish
social club.
   Noting that he once was a Democrat, the president told the crowd
that the present leadership of the party is out of step with the
rank-and-file.
   ``The liberals may try to mouth some of our words, but when they
talk about `values' and `family' they mean something very
different,'' he said.
   Reagan's trip to Chicago was aimed at helping Bush with
conservative-minded Democrats and independent voters in ethnic
communities _ many of whose votes Reagan and Bush won while
carrying Illinois in 1980 and 1984.
   The president said that the Republican Party represented the
best hopes of people seeking liberation of Eastern European nations.
   He called the Munich Pact in 1938 ``the naive appeasement that
brought us the great nightmare of this century _ the Second World
War.''
   ``The sad lesson is that to be weak is to invite war,'' he said,
``and George Bush and I will not rest until freedom is restored to
all the peoples of Eastern Europe.''
   Without mentioning the name of Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis, Reagan suggested that Bush had fared better than
the Massachusetts governor in last Sunday's nationally televised
debate.
   Reagan, taking a new slap at Dukakis' membership in the American
Civil Liberties Union, said, ``You know, after the debate, I had to
say, `Isn't that just like an ACLU member. He didn't have a prayer
when he needed one.''
   ``Over the last eight years, America has begun a great
enterprise of resurrection,'' he said. ``We have worked to recover
the bedrock values that you and most Americans never departed
from.''
   ``We have rebuilt our defenses, our country is at peace, our
economy is strong and our future is bright.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Following embargoed for release at 8 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In remarks prepared for delivery at a $250-per-plate fund-raiser
later, Reagan called Bush ``one of the finest men I have ever
known.''
   ``We've all seen what a brilliant job he's done in the past _
and I can promise you he's going to do an even better job in the
future.''
   Reagan criticized former President Carter's administration,
which preceded his own, and said, ``Today we have peace and
prosperity, and the liberals are trying to pretend those economic
and foreign policy nightmares never happened.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End embargoed material</HEAD>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   He also attended a private reception for 80 couples who donated
at least $10,000 a couple to GOP coffers.
   He departed from his announced schedule to throw out the first
ball at the Chicago Cubs-Pittsburgh Pirates baseball game at
Wrigley Field. Reagan once did radio broadcast re-creations of Cubs
games on stations in Davenport and Des Moines, Iowa.
</TEXT>
