<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-WrongNumber     09-30 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Wrong Number,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coloma NAPA Auto Supply Owner Bombarded With NASA Phone Calls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Americans rejoice in the safe launch
of space shuttle Discovery, Tim Whiting is getting tired of
answering his telephone.
   Whiting, owner of NAPA Auto Supply in Coloma, has a toll free
number, 1-800-999-NAPA, which is being confused with a 900 number
for shuttle news.
   The number to call to hear shuttle-to-ground conversation and
periodic updates on the mission is 1-900-909-NASA.
   Apparently some radio stations were incorrectly promoting
1-900-999-NASA as the space hotline number. That is close to
Whiting's number, since both NAPA and NASA translate on a telephone
into the numerals 6272.
   Whiting said he began receiving the strange phone calls even
before the Thursday morning launch and about 30 had come in by the
time he closed his store.
   Whiting called his MCI to see if his 800 number could be
disconnected for the day. He was told a change in the number would
take two weeks.
   In the meantime, he will have to pay for the incorrect,
toll-free calls.
</TEXT>
