<DOCNO> AP880930-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ACLU-Ads     09-30 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ACLU-Ads,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ACLU Advertises To Defend Its Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union, attacked
by Vice President George Bush as the incarnation of ideas that
voters loathe, will embark on a $250,000 effort to tell Americans
its only cause is the Bill of Rights.
   Dan Goldberg, chairman of the ACLU Foundation of Southern
California, announced the campaign Thursday at a news conference
and played two commercial taped for the organization by actor Burt
Lancaster, who tells viewers: ``I have a confession to make. I'm a
card-carrying member of the ACLU.''
   The reference to being a ``card-carrying member'' is the same
one Bush has used to describe Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis up
to and including Sunday's nationally televised debate. Bush claimed
Dukakis' ACLU membership showed how out of touch he was with
Americans.
   Dukakis did not defend the organization during the debate, and
the day afterward his campaign issued a list of ACLU positions with
which he disagrees.
   Other commercials for the 68-year-old ACLU will be made next
week by Jill Eikenberry and Michael Tucker, the husband-and-wife
actors who portray married lawyers on the ``L.A. Law'' television
series.
   Goldberg, a talent manager whose previous battles have included
thwarting the movement to rate records according to their lyric
content, said people associate the ACLU with the often-unpopular
causes and groups it defends.
   He said the campaign is designed to show Americans that ``our
one client is the Bill of Rights.'' He said the defense of
Constitutional principles such as separation of church and state,
the rights of groups to speak and march and the rights of accused
people leads the ACLU to represent such groups as the Ku Klux Klan
and the Communist Party.
   The television commercials are expected to quickly use up the
initial $30,000 budget for time purchases in Southern California,
with 18 spots to be seen locally on Cable News Network and three on
``The CBS Morning News.''
   The ACLU Southern California Foundation, the organization's
largest, also has launched a letter campaign to its 25,000 members
seeking $250,000 for additional advertising money.
   The ads will be made available to the ACLU's 50 other
foundations.
   Goldberg said the idea for an advertising campaign actually
began after the Republican National Convention in August when Pat
Robertson attacked the ACLU during an address.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
