<DOCNO> AP880930-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-YellowstoneFires     09-30 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone Fires,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steps Seen Likely to Prevent Future Buildup of Dead Trees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An interagency review committee probably will
recommend steps in Yellowstone National Park to prevent the
century-long buildup of dead trees that made this summer's fires so
destructive, Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel said Thursday.
   And the chief ranger of the National Park Service said
controlled burning hasn't been done before in Yellowstone because
the predominant species there, lodgepole pine, is almost impossible
to burn under control.
   Hodel told two Senate subcommittees that he and Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng on Monday named members of a panel of
experts to make recommendations for changes in firefighting
policies by Dec. 15. The panel was instructed to consult other
experts in universities, state governments and other places outside
the federal establishment.
   Lyng's department controls the Forest Service, the agency with
the dominant role in fighting most fires on government land.
Hodel's department is in charge of the National Park Service, which
runs Yellowstone.
   ``I would expect them to come back with a recommended means of
trying to reduce the fuel. I don't think anybody can tell me what
that will be,'' Hodel told the agriculture, nutrition and forest
subcommittee of the Agriculture Committee and the public lands and
parks subcommittee of the Energy and Natural Resources Committee.
   The hearing was called to ventilate complaints of Western
senators that the ``let it burn'' policy of the Park Service in
effect since 1972 had led to a disaster for the park.
   Although other parks have employed controlled burns to
regenerate the land, they had never been used in Yellowstone
despite the buildup of dead trees from almost a century of trying
to put out every fire.
   Walt Dabney, the chief ranger, said, ``The only time that
material (lodgepole pine) will burn successfully is when it's very,
very dry'' and there are winds to move the fire along.
   ``To light a fire when it's dry and windy, you're in the same
situation we were in this year. It's very hard to control,'' he
testified.
   Dale Robertson, chief of the Forest Service, said his agency
would plant new trees where needed, but William Penn Mott, director
of the Park Service, said Yellowstone plantings would be limited to
native grasses and wildflowers along the roads and along trout
streams if necessary to hold back erosion from bare ground.
   Lodgepole pine needs fire to burst cones and throw seeds on the
ground. Seed counts, Mott said, show 50,000 per acre _ more than
one per square foot _ where the hottest fires burned and up to a
million per acre elsewhere.
   ``We don't need seeds,'' Mott said.
   In mid-July, the park service decided to fight all the fires in
Yellowstone _ some of which had entered from Forest Service land
outside the park. Hodel confirmed the decision during a visit there
July 22.
   Some senators expressed skepticism that the Park Service really
was trying to put out the fires, and Sen. John Melcher, D-Mont.,
chairing the hearing, asked, ``Was what Secretary Hodel wanted
done, done?''
   Hodel said his conversations with firefighters on another visit
in September led him to conclude his wishes were not being
sabotaged. Many of the people he talked with were not from the Park
Service but experts from other agencies, and ``They were making the
best decisions they could make.''
   Senators also expressed skepticism that the Park Service could
assess the spring as normal or wetter than normal when nearby
counties were crying for drought relief, but Hodel said such data
``may well have lulled us into a false sense of security.'' He said
he was awaiting the compilation of a detailed chronology to see
``when the extra dry conditions in Yellowstone became visible.''
   Senators also expressed dismay that publicity about the fires
would keep tourists away next year, and Hodel said the park was
``very much worth viewing. ... Fully one-half of the park has not
been touched and fully one-half of the area that has been touched
very shortly will appear not to have been.''
   Although the area suffered economically, said Sen. Malcolm
Wallop, R-Wyo., ``Probably more important, we suffered
emotionally.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
