<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Children     09-30 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Children,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Push for One Bill on Child Care, Pornography, Parental
Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats laid down an election-season
challenge to the GOP on Thursday by moving to combine a $2.5
billion child care initiative with a hybrid anti-pornography and
parental leave bill.
   ``Everybody claims they want to do something'' for families,
said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., sponsor of two of the three
measures. ``Here's the chance.''
   Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., made the move after his
Republican counterpart, Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, said he
could offer no deal to limit amendments or schedule a vote on the
pornography-leave bill.
   The leave component, sponsored by Dodd, requires businesses with
more than 50 employees to give workers at least 10 weeks of leave
to cope with a newborn, newly adopted or seriously ill child or a
worker's own serious illness.
   Some of the most adamant opponents of the leave bill worked
vigorously this week to add to it a measure strengthening laws and
penalties against child pornography and obscenity. That part was
sponsored by Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
   The child care section would be modeled on the Act for Better
Child Care Services, a Democratic initiative centered on subsidies
to help families pay for day care. Dodd was the sponsor.
   Dodd said he and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, a leading
conservative player in the child care arena, had agreed on a
compromise authorizing the same amount of money. Federal staff,
health and safety standards still would be required of centers and
homes receiving federal money, but governors could seek temporary
variances for counties or other parts of their states having
trouble with compliance.
   A separate tax provision would be proposed either on the floor
or as part of a tax technical corrections bill, Dodd said. He said
it would involve the earned income tax credit, but declined to give
details.
   Dodd labeled the children's package the ``Thurmond-Hatch-Dodd''
proposal.
   ``While this is a little cumbersome, I admit, and we're running
out of time, I admit, I don't think we're that far apart,'' Dodd
said.
   Dole, in his floor exchange with Byrd, labeled the trio of bills
``a total political agenda'' and said senators should be spending
their time on tax corrections and an anti-drug bill _ ``issues that
affect the public interest, not the political interest.''
   Dole said the Republicans might offer a motion to kill or
indefinitely postpone a vote on Byrd's proposal, which involves
sending the leave-pornography bill back to committee to be fused
with Dodd-Hatch child care compromise and swiftly returned to the
floor.
   If that happens, Dodd said, ``they bear the responsibility of
this package of legislation dying in this Congress.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
