<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StolenLetters     09-30 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stolen Letters,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scholer Convicted On Possession Of Gun, Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An eccentric scholar serving a three-year
sentence for trying to sell valuable letters from government
libraries was convicted Thursday of possessing a gun and drugs
found in safety deposit boxes.
   A U.S. District Court jury convicted Charles Merrill Mount on a
felony charge of illegally possessing a .32-caliber pistol and two
misdemeanor counts of possessing more than 1,000 barbiturates.
   Mount, already serving a three-year sentence for trying to sell
valuable letters to a Boston bookstore, could receive up to five
years imprisonment for the weapons conviction and one-year terms
for each of the two drug possession counts.
   Jurors, who deliberated nearly four hours following the two-day
trial, declined to convict Mount of the more serious charges of
felony possession with intent to distribute prescription drugs.
   Mount, the son of a Brooklyn physician who affects a British
accent and carries a cane in the style of an Edwardian gentleman,
contended that he kept the pills to prove that his late father was
a drug addict.
   He testified that pills were to be used as evidence in court to
contest the will in which his father, Dr. Abraham Suchow, had
disinherited him.
   Mount had been convicted in 1982 of making threatening telephone
calls to his mother during the bitter court fight over his father's
will.
   Mount, who was born Seymour Suchow, also was convicted in 1984
of filing a false passport application.
   On May 24, Mount was sentenced in Boston to three years
imprisonment for transporting stolen documents, including letters
by Abraham Lincoln and Winston Churchill, that belonged to the
Library of Congress and the National Archives.
   Mount, 60, was arrested Aug. 13, 1987, while trying to sell
letters and papars signed by Lincoln and several Civil War generals
to Goodspeed's Bookshop in Boston.
   He is awaiting trial in Washington on 17 additional counts of
receipt of stolen property stemming from the hundreds of Civil War
documents the FBI said were found in two safety deposit boxes Mount
kept under assumed names.
   It was in those boxes, searched following Mount's arrest in
Boston, that agents found the barbiturates and the pistol.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. did not schedule a
sentencing date for Mount on the gun and drug convictions.
   Robinson also refused a request by defense attorney David H.
Williams to order the government to turn over a painting that Mount
had deeded to the law firm to help pay legal expenses.
   Assistant District Attorney Scott L. Fredericksen said the
painting and other items seized last year from Mount's Capitol Hill
apartment were being examined by the FBI as part of its continuing
investigation.
   Fredericksen told the judge there was evidence that Mount, an
accomplished portrait painter and art historian, had painted the
picture himself, forged Claude Monet's signature and tried to sell
it as an original of the famous French artist.
   An art expert had identified the Monet signature as a forgery,
Fredericksen said.
   Mount, a former Guggenheim fellow, is the author of biographies
of American painters John Singer Sargent, Gilbert Stuart and Monet.
   According to the FBI, Mount frequented the manuscript collection
at the Library of Congress and the Archives, where he gained access
to valuable documents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
