<1ST_LINE>r w AM-USAttorney-Lawsuit     09-30 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US Attorney-Lawsuit,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Sues For Former U.S. Attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Thursday sued a former U.S.
attorney in Cleveland for failing to report loans on a financial
disclosure form while he was a federal prosecutor.
   The Justice Department complaint in U.S. District Court in
Cleveland seeks $20,000 in civil penalties from J. William Petro
for alleged violations of the financial disclosure provisions of
the Ethics in Government Act of 1978.
   Petro was fired as a federal prosecutor in 1984 amid a Justice
Department probe of his activities and eventually was convicted of
disclosing the contents of a sealed indictment.
   The suit says Petro submitted a disclosure form in October 1981
reporting no liabilities to creditors when a man named Carl
Glickman had supplied Petro with a $15,000 loan the previous month.
   The complaint says an individual identified only as Lozick
loaned Petro $120,000 in 1982, but that the U.S. attorney didn't
report either that obligation or the Glickman loan on his
disclosure form for that year.
   In addition, the government says Petro failed to report the
Glickman or Lozick obligations or an additional $15,000 in loans
from Lozick for 1983; nor did he report the Glickman loan on an
amended form for 1983.
   President Reagan on Oct. 3, 1984, ordered that Petro be
dismissed immediately as U.S. attorney in Cleveland at a time when
the Justice Department was investigating Petro in connection with
the possible leaking of information concerning a criminal
investigation.
   A federal court jury on March 7, 1985, in Baton Rouge, La.,
convicted Petro of criminal contempt for disclosing the contents of
a sealed indictment.
   Cleveland businessman Howard Schulman had a conversation with
Petro about the indictment and then Schulman told details to one of
the defendants, a close friend, Stanley Moss.
   Moss and several others were charged in the indictment with
fraud involving the alleged sale of counterfeit merchandise.
   Petro, then 44, testified he didn't know the indictment was
sealed when he revealed its contents.
   A man who answered the telephone at the Cleveland address listed
in the complaint denied that he was the Petro named in the suit and
said no such person lived at that address.
   In an unrelated matter, the government also announced it is
suing an Alaska man under the Ethics in Government Act for
allegedly neglecting until this year to file a federal financial
disclosure form in connection with his candidacy in 1986 for the
U.S. Senate.
   The government has brought a total of four civil suits under the
ethics act. The other two were against Constance Hansen, the wife
of former U.S. Rep. George Hansen, and Steve Tarver, a Republican
candidate from Wyoming running for the U.S. Senate. Both Mrs.
Hansen and Tarver paid civil penalties in connection with financial
disclosure requirements. Mrs. Hansen was a government employee as
well as a congressional candidate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
