<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Cuba-SexChange     09-30 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Sex Change,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Sex Change Operation in Cuba Performed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban woman is ``working normally and has
stabilized emotionally'' after undergoing the Communist-ruled
nation's first sex change operation, the Cuban news agency Prensa
Latina reported Friday.
   ``For the first time an individual considered to be a man has
changed his sex and become a woman,'' Prensa Latina said in a
dispatch monitored in Mexico City.
   It said the afternoon daily newspaper Rebel Youth disclosed the
operation on Friday but did not identify the woman or say when the
surgery took place. The operation was performed by a team of
surgeons led by Julio Cesar Morales Concepcion at a hospital in the
capital, Havana.
   ``The patient, since her infancy, presented serious
psychological disturbances that weren't conveniently interpreted,''
Rebel Youth quoted Morales Concepcion as saying.
   ``Out of ignorance, neither her relatives nor society was aware
of this pathological and scientific phenomenon so they could not
direct someone who wanted to change her sex,'' Morales Concepcion
said.
   The patient contacted a national sex education group, which
referred her to the surgery team. It performed the operation ``with
a technique that has been well-established in Denmark, Sweden,
Spain and the United States,'' the report said.
   Rebel Youth quoted Morales Concepcion as saying the case ``is
not a matter of a homosexual but a truly humanitarian case.''
   Critics have accused the government of President Fidel Castro of
persecuting homosexuals in Cuba and of sending homosexuals to work
camps in the 1960s and 1970s. Castro took power in 1959 in a
revolution that ousted dictator Fulgencio Batista.
   The woman ``can be found working normally and has stabilized
emotionally in absolute form,'' Rebel Youth said.
</TEXT>
