<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GreenTrial     09-30 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Green Trial,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nurse Not Criminally Responsible in Deaths of Her Babies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pediatric nurse Ann Green, who said she killed
two of her babies and tried to kill a third because she was
depressed after childbirth, was found innocent of murder and
attempted murder Friday because of insanity.
   Mrs. Green, 43, slumped forward at the defense table and her
lawyer, Michael Dowd, hugged her as jury foreman Andrew Kessler
pronounced the verdict. Her 54-year-old husband, Larry, wept.
   State Supreme Court Justice Stephen Crane let Mrs. Green remain
free in $125,000 bail and directed her to undergo psychiatric
evaluation within 30 days. He scheduled a hearing on the
psychiatric report for Oct. 28.
   ``I know I need help,'' Mrs. Green said after the verdict, ``and
I'll continue to seek it. I'll just take it one day at a time.''
   Crane, after hearing the psychiatric report, may commit Mrs.
Green for treatment, or if she is not considered dangerous, release
her from custody.
   Larry Green, a former building superintendent who says he is
dying of cancer, said he and his wife had come through ``three
years of hell.'' But because the jury was ``intelligent'' and
``merciful,'' he said, ``we have just been delivered from a
terrible ordeal.''
   Mrs. Green admitted she smothered two of her babies in 1980 and
1982 by putting pillows over their faces. She said she tried to
kill a third the same way in 1985 but a neighbor, also a pediatric
nurse, resuscitated the infant. That child, a boy, lives with
relatives.
   Mrs. Green testified that when she smothered the infants, it
always seemed that someone else was doing it. ``I was not fully
aware of what happened to my babies or why,'' she said.
   The jury got the case around 4 p.m. Thursday after hearing the
prosecution say Mrs. Green, contrary to defense claims, was
criminally responsible for her children's deaths. Kessler, a
34-year-old researcher and Russian language expert explained the
jury's verdict.
   ``The overriding feeling,'' he said, ``was that the
prosecution's experts were not extremely credible and did not seem
to have a thorough familiarity with Mrs. Green's history so as to
win our trust.''
   Assistant District Attorney Marybeth Richroath charged that Mrs.
Green smothered her infants when they were just days old because
they annoyed her with their crying.
   The prosecutor said the defendant was fully aware of what she
was doing and had taken steps to conceal her actions.
   Mrs. Richroath said Mrs. Green lied to her husband and doctors
about what happened to the babies, and said she sought psychiatric
help only after a physician said he suspected foul play in the near
death of her third child.
</TEXT>
