<DOCNO> AP880930-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PeaceConvoy     09-30 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peace Convoy,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: President Can't Block Humanitarian Aid to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAREDO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president has no authority to prohibit
humanitarian aid to foreign countries, a federal judge said in a
ruling supporting a group that bucked the government and took
vehicles to Nicaragua.
   The Veterans Peace Convoy filed suit while it fought with the
government over plans to take vehicles filled with donated goods to
Nicaragua.
   The group eventually was able to take 30 of the group's 38
vehicles across the border at Laredo in July. Most of the vehicles
are in Nicaragua.
   U.S. District Judge George P. Kazen's ruling, issued Friday,
limits the scope of the International Emergency Economic Powers
Act, the basis for the Reagan administration's economic embargo of
Nicaragua.
   The act contains an exemption for humanitarian aid. The Reagan
administration had been interpreting it on a case-by-case basis,
the court said, and refusing to allow export of certain items
including cars and trucks.
   Kazen's ruling said because of the exemption in the Economic
Powers Act, the president has no authority to regulate or prohibit
U.S. citizens' donations to foreign countries ``which the donor
intends to be used to relieve human suffering.''
   Specifically, the Foreign Assets Control Office, part of the
Treasury Department, cannot require donors to get licenses before
exporting such aid, Kazen said. The act was cited when the office
temporarily barred the veterans' donation of vehicles to Nicaraguan
schools, hospitals and churches.
   Plaintiffs in the case said the ruling clears the way for
further aid to Nicaragua.
   ``We consider it an important victory. We actually got a much
broader ruling than we had expected,'' said Tom Hansen, former
coordinator of Veterans for Peace.
   Hansen last week joined Pastors for Peace, a Detroit-based group
which hopes to send a similar convoy to Nicaragua in 1989. Donating
to Nicaraguan groups will be much easier now that U.S. citizens
don't have to worry about getting licenses, he said in a telephone
interview.
   A Treasury Department spokesman, who spoke on condition he not
be named, said, ``We have not seen the decision yet. It will be
reviewed by the Treasury and Justice departments.'' He declined
further comment.
   The Veterans Peace Convoy collected donations in 100 cities in
42 states last spring before converging in Laredo. Ten hours before
the veterans' planned crossing into Mexico, U.S. Customs notified
them they couldn't go, Hansen said. Four of the vehicles were
confiscated.
   When the case came to trial the government argued there was no
reason to hear it, because the vehicles had been allowed to cross
and the impounded ones had been returned to the owners.
   Kazen said the plaintiffs' vehicles could be subject to seizure
in the future. He also noted the plaintiffs are under continuing
threat of criminal and civil prosecution.
   Justice Department spokesman Brad Marman had no immediate
response Friday when asked what government policy would be in light
of the decision, other than to say the department always abides by
court decisions. He said Justice officials had not seen the ruling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
