<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Papandreou, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0832,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Prime Minister Undergoes Open-Heart Surgery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 `Shortly after...Thomson said' with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with Papandreou's condition listed as satisfactory. Name of
donor not released. Pickup 7th graf pvs `In Athens...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAREFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek Prime Minister Andreas
Papandreou underwent open-heart surgery Friday, and a Greek Embassy
spokesman said ``Everything is fine.''
   Dr. Nicholas Papadakis, the Greek Embassy press attache, added:
``The operation was successful.''
   Greek officials at the hospital said a team headed by Magdi
Yacoub, Britain's top heart surgeon, performed the six-hour
operation on the 69-year-old Socialist prime minister at Harefield
Hospital north of London.
   The prime minister's four children and his girlfriend, airline
stewardess Dimitra Liani, 34, were at the hospital throughout the
surgery.
   Papandreou's condition was listed as satisfactory, Vasilis
Kapetanyannis, a Greek Embassy press officer at the hospital, said
late Friday night.
   Shortly after the operation, hospital general manager David
Thomson told reporters that Papandreou ``underwent an operation for
replacement of his aortic valve using a human valve. This was
combined with insertion of three bypass grafts and the clearing of
the diseased coronary artery, to improve the heart function.''
   ``The team of doctors who performed the operation is pleased
with his progress so far,'' Thomson said.
   In keeping with medical practice in Britain, the name of the
donor of the heart valve was not revealed.
   In Athens, state-run television interrupted evening programs
with a special news bulletin to say surgery was a success and that
the prime minister's doctors ``are absolutely satisfied.''
   Papandreou, head of the governing Panhellenic Socialist Movement
and president of the 12-nation European Economic Community, flew to
London Aug. 25 after his heart condition suddenly worsened. Greece
does not have a hospital where a complex open-heart operation like
his could be performed.
   He underwent pre-surgical treatment at Harefield for a narrowing
of the aorta, the main blood vessel carrying blood from the heart.
   Greek officials said the main operation was delayed a month to
clear a liver disorder linked to the heart problem.
   Waiting in a hospital corridor away from the news media were his
four adult children, several government ministers and Ms. Liani,
whose public appearances walking hand-in-hand with Papandreou have
become a hot issue in the Greek press.
   After Papandreou arrived in Britain, the Greek government
announced he would divorce Margaret Papandreou, his American-born
wife of 37 years, prompting speculation that he planned to marry
Ms. Liani.
   Mrs. Papandreou is not in London, according to the embassy.
   Papandreou's relationship with Ms. Liani, a stewardess for
Olympic Airways, the national airline, became public a year ago
when they were seen together on an Aegean island.
   Papandreou came to power in 1981 at the head of his Panhellenic
Socialist Movement and won a second four-year term at national
elections held in 1985.
   He is the dominant personality in Greek politics and reserves
most decision-making for himself. His four-week absence from Athens
has markedly slowed government activity according to socialist
officials.
   Opposition conservatives from the New Democracy party complain
Papandreou's refusal to appoint a stand-in while he's away is
unconstitutional and has left a power vacuum.
   His deputies are Defense Minister Yiannis Haralambopoulos, who
handles ceremonial occasions, and Justice Minister Menios
Koutsogiorgos, who supervises day-to-day running of the government.
Both have deputy premier status.
   But during his hospitalization, Papandreou has stayed in close
touch with his Cabinet by telephone and telefax and senior Cabinet
ministers have flown to London to get instructions.
</TEXT>
