<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SeattleEndorsement     09-30 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seattle Endorsement,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seattle Times Breaks Republican Tradition To Endorse Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seattle Times is breaking a virtually
rock-solid tradition of supporting Republican presidential
candidates and endorsing Democrat Michael Dukakis this year.
   The endorsement, announced Friday, said that with five weeks
left before the election Nov. 8, the Massachusetts governor had
shown ``a broader, deeper understanding of the economies of the
states and nation.''
   The editorial endorsing Dukakis will appear in the newspaper's
Sunday editions.
   ``Gov. Michael Dukakis is conspicuously the best choice to lead
America as its president through the coming four years,'' the
editorial said.
   Vice President George Bush must share responsibility with
President Reagan for ``the potentially catastrophic federal deficit
... (and) the widening financial gap between the well-off who've
gained handsomely and the tens of millions of middle-class and poor
Americans who are today relatively worse off,'' the editorial said.
   Dukakis also was chosen on the basis of his support for
education, civil rights, defense, clean government and choice of a
running mate.
   ``Bush wraps himself in the flag, exploits emotions surrounding
the issue of abortion, casts doubt on the patriotism of his
opponent and attacks the American Civil Liberties Union,'' the
editorial said.
   ``These tactics suggest that Bush is a small man, fearfully
marching backward toward the 1940s, rather than being a leader who
can inspire America and its citizens to higher thoughts and deeds.''
   The endorsement announcement said a search of internal Times
files going back to 1920 showed that the only time the larger of
the city's two daily papers failed to support a Republican for
president was in 1964, when neither Republican Barry Goldwater nor
Democratic President Lyndon B. Johnson was endorsed.
</TEXT>
