<1ST_LINE>u w AM-D.C.Budget     09-30 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-D.C. Budget,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Attaches Anti-Abortion Amendment to D.C. Appropriations Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Friday attached a strong
anti-abortion amendment and a measure allowing Georgetown
University to deny certain rights to gay groups to the District of
Columbia appropriations bill, prompting a threat by city officials
to shut down their government.
   In approving the city's $3.2 billion fiscal year 1989 budget,
the House added an amendment that would freeze the $530 million
federal payment for the District's budget and prevent the city from
spending its own money if Medicaid-funded abortions are performed
on women whose lives are not threatened.
   The House bill, still to be considered by the Senate, also would
allow Georgetown University to go back on its agreement to allow
gay student associations to meet on campus and apply for student
government funds.
   The Roman Catholic school had reached an agreement with the gay
groups in March after the District of Columbia Superior Court and
Court of Appeals upheld a finding by the city's human rights office
that Georgetown was discriminating against gay groups. Georgetown
officials have said that they will not go back on their agreement
with the student groups, regardless of what Congress decides.
   Del. Walter Fauntroy, D-D.C., angered by the intrusion into
local affairs, said he would encourage city officials to disobey
the abortion-funding prohibition to trigger a congressionally
mandated shutdown of city government. Such a move would leave
Congress with the responsibility of governing the nation's capital.
   ``You will forgive me, having respected you for 18 years, if I
suggest to my mayor and people that work for this (city) government
that maybe it's time to end this facade,'' a tearful Fauntroy told
his House colleagues in a meeting where the final touches were put
on the budget. ``If Congress wants to decide every little detail,
maybe it's time to do that.''
   David Clarke, chairman of the District of Columbia Council,
concurred with Fauntroy, saying, ``I believe it is time for the
people of the District of Columbia to take to the streets to defend
their constitutional rights.''
   The abortion measure, offered by Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif.,
toughens current legislation, which allows the city to use locally
generated funds for abortions, and restricts federal funds for use
by rape and incest victims, women suffering through ectopic
pregnancies, or when the mother's life is threatened.
</TEXT>
