<1ST_LINE>u i AM-HumanRights-Cuba     09-30 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Human Rights-Cuba,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Group Received 1,500 Requests for Meetings With Cubans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,500 Cubans requested meetings with a U.N.
human rights delegation that returned from Cuba this week, many of
them complaining that they were barred from leaving the country, an
official said Friday.
   The delegation, which stayed in Cuba for 10 days, was the first
of its kind to visit the Caribbean island nation since President
Fidel Castro came to power in 1959.
   The six-member team only had time to meet with 86 of the 1,500
Cubans who requested meetings, delegation chairman Alioune Sene of
Senegal told a news conference.
   He said the 86 represented a cross-section of the different
allegations of human rights abuses that the group received.
   The allegations included ``bad treatment,'' temporary
disappearances, illegal and arbitrary detention and lack of
religious freedom, Sene said.
   He said ``a good part'' of the total 1,500 written requests were
from people who said they were barred from emigrating. Many wanted
to join family members living in other countries, but some said
they would go ``anywhere,'' Sene said.
   He declined to comment on any specific cases.
   In addition to Sene, the delegation consisted of members of the
U.N. Human Rights Commission from Bulgaria, Colombia, Ireland,
Nigeria and the Philippines.
   The group visited Cuba Sept. 16-26 on a mandate from the
commission, which last March accepted an invitation from Castro to
visit the island and investigate the human rights situation.
   The invitation followed a two-year effort by the United States
to have Cuba put on the commission's agenda.
   The United States and international organizations including
Amnesty International have cited reports of human rights violations
in Cuba, including torture and mistreatment of political prisoners.
Cuba has denied the allegations.
   The delegation will present its report to next year's
commission, which opens in February, Sene said. He declined to go
into the group's conclusions.
   In answer to a question, Sene said some Cuban prisoners who met
with the group said they had been threatened because of their wish
to meet with the human rights delegates.
   But Sene said the Cuban government had assued the delegation
that all citizens could meet freely with the panel without fearing
reprisals after the group left Cuba.
   Sene said his group visited three prisons and a psychiatric
hospital.
   The group also met with Castro and other Cuban officials, as
well as private citizens, church officials and non-governmental
organizations, including the Cuban Human Rights Commission.
</TEXT>
