<HEAD>Dukakis Ad Calls Bush Packaged Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympics fans who were watching television
Friday night were exposed to the newest Michael Dukakis ad, which
suggested that Republican rival George Bush was wrapping himself in
the American flag because he lacked a real issue with which to
attract voters.
   The 30-second ad on NBC consisted of a group of actors posing as
George Bush's aides trying to plot out a campaign strategy.
Entitled ``The Packaging of George Bush,'' the ad begins with one
of the aides mentioning Democrat Dukakis' health insurance plan for
the 37 million Americans who lack coverage.
   ``It's going to go over real well with the middle class,''
another voice says. ``We've got enough problems with the middle
class.''
   When one aide asks ``So, what does Bush do?'' another answers,
``Wraps himself up in the American flag.'' ``That again?'' another
asks. ``Get out the flag, boys'' another says.
   The ad concludes with the slogan: ``They'd like to sell you the
package. Wouldn't you rather choose a president?''
   The Dukakis headquarters in Boston refused earlier Friday to
supply a script and information on the ad.
