<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-Pinochet     09-30 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Pinochet,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Winds Down Plebiscite Campaign With Attack On Critics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALPARAISO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military President Augusto Pinochet,
winding down his campaign for eight more years of rule, on Thursday
called his political foes liars ``infected'' by contact with
communists.
   In a speech before thousands of supporters in the central port
city of Valparaiso, 75 miles west of the capital Santiago, Pinochet
called on citizens to vote ``yes'' in the Oct. 5 plebiscite on his
presidency.
   If he wins, he said, ``in this next period I will dedicate
myself wholly to my people, for my people and with my people.''
   Speaking of his political opponents, he declared: ``I'm
profoundly worried by some gentlemen who call themselves democrats
and nonetheless embrace and shake hands with Marxist communists.
What kind of mix is that?''
   ``No one understands them because they lie, lie, lie, because
they are infected by communists,'' he said.
   In speeches and mass media propaganda, Pinochet and supporters
have repeatedly tried to link the moderate opposition with the
extreme left.
   A coalition of 16 parties, ranging from the center-right to the
Socialist left, is campaigning for his defeat in the plebiscite,
but has excluded the pro-Moscow Communist Party and other Marxist
groups from its ranks.
   Pinochet accused the opposition of ``offering limitless statism,
demagogism that feeds illusions, poverty for thousands of
Chileans.''
   At the polls the nation's 7.4 million registered voters will be
able to ``yes'' or ``no'' on a proposal by the country's military
commanders that Pinochet remain in power until 1997.
   If a majority votes ``yes,'' Pinochet begins a new eight-year
term next March. If most voters choose ``no,'' an open election
will be called next year and Pinochet will be succeeded by the
winner in March 1990.
   Regardless of the outcome, elections are planned in a year for a
Congress, disbanded after Pinochet seized power in a bloody 1973
coup that toppled the elected government of an avowed Marxist,
President Salvador Allende, during a period of social and economic
upheaval.
   By law, political campaigning must end on Sunday, a full 48
hours before the day of the vote. The opposition coalition plans a
massive final rally Saturday in Santiago and a pro-Pinochet
demonstration is slated for Sunday in the capital.
</TEXT>
