<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Owens-Ethics     09-30 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Owens-Ethics,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethics Committee Decides There's No Time To Investigate Owens This
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee has decided there's
no time this year to investigate allegations that Rep. Wayne Owens,
D-Utah, allowed a utility company lobbyist to perform congressional
duties in violation of House rules.
   Ethics panel Chairman Julian C. Dixon, D-Calif., and ranking
Republican John T. Myers of Indiana, announced the decision in a
letter Wednesday to H. Craig Moody, the Utah Republican chairman
who complained about Owens. The letter was released by Owens on
Thursday.
   Owens said he welcomed the committee action, but expressed
``regret they could not deal with the merits of the frivolous
issue'' raised by the GOP chairman.
   Moody complained to the committee Aug. 10 that Owens allowed
Kenley Brunsdale, a Utah Power & Light Co. lobbyist, to perform
congressional staff duties in preparing a financing bill for the
Central Utah water development project.
   The complaint contended the work was illegal because Brunsdale
was receiving a salary from the utility. Moody said Brunsdale's
work on the bill amounted to an in-kind contribution from an
outside entity, which is prohibited under House rules.
   The complaint was mailed hours after the Interior Committee
approved the bill, which boosted the water project's money for the
1989-90 fiscal year by $45.2 million, well under the $750 million
Owens originally sought.
   Dixon and Myers wrote Moody that his filing did not meet the
requirements for complaints made by non-members of the House
against House members.
   Noting the committee could undertake the investigation on its
own, the chairman and ranking member said there is not sufficient
time to consider the matter in the waning days of the 100th
Congress.
   ``However, the committee may entertain taking up the matter in
the next Congress when there will be time to fully investigate and
explore the issues,'' said the two members of what is formally the
Committee on Standards of Official Conduct.
   Owens called Moody's complaint ``the thinnest attempted smear in
the history of Utah politics.'' He termed it ``a mean-spirited act
of political desperation....''
</TEXT>
