<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea-US     09-30 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea-US,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Will Not File Charges Against U.S. Swimmers For Prank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No charges will be filed against two
U.S. Olympic swimmers for the theft of a marble lion's head from a
hotel bar and they can return home now that they apologized for the
prank, a prosecutor said Friday.
   ``The case is now closed and they can leave the country,''
senior prosecutor Yoo Sung-soo said.
   Yoo said he notified the U.S. Embassy that gold-medal winners
Troy Dalbey and Doug Gjertsen and a third American, Ernest Mangum,
can leave Saturday.
   The prosecutor said he decided not to charge the three Americans
because they wrote statements repenting for the action and
apologized to the South Korean people.
   Police said Dalbey and Mangum admitted removing the $830 carving
from a Seoul hotel Saturday, but that an investigation showed
Gjertsen was not involved. Authorities said Dalbey and Mangum, who
identified himself as a friend of the two swimmers, were drunk when
they pulled off the stunt.
   It was not immediately clear why Gjertsen apologized if he was
not involved.
   The case attracted nationwide attention. Hundreds of Koreans
called newspapers and police to demand the swimmers be punished and
prevented from leaving the country.
   The two swimmers said in a statement Tuesday that they were
being exuberant and the incident was a prank to celebrate their
gold medal victories in two Olympic events the previous day. The
two apologized and said they hoped the incident would not damage
U.S.-South Korean relations.
   The two swimmers will keep their medals, but U.S. Olympic
officials kicked them off the team and said they were to be sent
home as soon as they were cleared with police.
   The incident received wide publicity because it took place at a
time of growing anti-U.S. sentiment among South Koreans during the
Olympics. Incidents involving U.S. athletes and news media touched
off a wave of anti-Americanism.
   Many South Koreans are displeased by the disorderly conduct of
U.S. athletes during the opening ceremony of the Olympic Games. NBC
television also came under fire for its allegedly ``biased''
coverage of a boxing bout, during which South Korean sports
officials attacked a referee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880930-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EastSt.LouisWoes     09-30 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-East St. Louis Woes,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Testifies He Has ``Gone Overboard'' In Trying To Meet
Request</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge dropped civil and contempt
charges Thursday against the impoverished city of East St. Louis
and its mayor despite their inability to produce records explaining
$80,000 in payments.
   Mayor Carl E. Officer said he had ``gone overboard'' to try to
explain why he received the money in addition to his annual $30,000
salary between 1984 and last year.
   Circuit Judge Robert Craig agreed East St. Louis had made
good-faith efforts although many financial records were missing.
St. Clair County State's Attorney John Baricevic, who requested at
a hearing that charges be dropped, would not comment afterward
about his motivation.
   Officer's lawyer, Eric Vickers of St. Louis, said Baricevic
``knows he didn't have a case against him.'' Vickers opposed
dismissal of the lawsuit, saying the mayor had been embarrassed
publicly by the charges and deserved to be exonerated by a trial.
   The mayor and his aides said many of the city's financial
records were lost in a move about three years ago and in an arson
fire in April.
   The lawsuit over the $80,000 was only one of many woes facing
East St. Louis.
   In the past year, the city's bank accounts were frozen three
times, the latest on Wednesday by the federal government, which is
seeking repayment of an Environmental Protection Agency sewer grant
allegedly misused.
   Another freeze expected to be lifted soon resulted from
firefighters going to court to force payment of more than $82,000
owed them for five years of clothing allowances.
   The city of 55,000 people across the Mississippi River from St.
Louis had repeatedly failed to meet its payroll, requiring an
infusion of state money in June. But the city has avoided seeking
bankruptcy protection, because that would allow a court-appointed
trustee to make decisions now in the hands of elected officials.
   Officer, meanwhile, faces a federal inquiry into his campaign
finances, focusing on whether he failed to report the transfer of
$19,000 in 1986 from Pete Fields, an unsuccessful congressional
candidate.
   The mayor has denied breaking any laws and said he had no qualms
about the investigation. But he told city council members Wednesday
night that the EPA judgment, combined with a projected city deficit
of nearly $500,000 for the rest of the year, will lead to more
layoffs.
   ``We're going to have to cut and cut deep,'' he said.
   In April, state prosecutors went to court to force the city to
pick up garbage after cutbacks suspended regular pickups for six
months.
   One of the biggest financial setbacks for East St. Louis this
year was a $4 million judgment won by a jail inmate who suffered
brain damage when he was beaten by another prisoner. Officials said
they didn't have the money to pay the award, but the inmate's
attorney garnished the city operating funds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
