<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SymphonyDirector     09-30 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Symphony Director,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit Symphony Names First Woman Chief Executive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deborah Borda has been named executive director
of the Detroit Symphony Orchestra, symphony executives announced
Thursday.
   Borda, president and managing director of the St. Paul (Minn.)
Chamber Orchestra, becomes the first female chief executive among
the nation's largest symphony organizations, the DSO said.
   Before joining the St. Paul orchestra in 1986, Borda, 39, spent
eight years with the San Francisco Symphony, serving as general
manager and artistic administrator.
   A violinist who studied at the Royal College of Music in London,
Borda will head Detroit Symphony Orchestra Hall Inc., the new
organization formed by the merger of the Detroit Symphony Orchestra
and Save Orchestra Hall Inc.
   The selection of Borda completed a search that began last summer
after Oleg Lobanov announced his resignation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
