<DOCNO> AP880930-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-District-Abortion     09-30 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-District-Abortion,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>District's Budget Hits Snag On Abortion Question</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Thursday voted to withhold $530
million in federal financing from the District of Columbia and to
bar the city from spending its own tax dollars if it uses public
funds to finance poor women's abortions in most cases.
   The House, while considering the district's $3.2 billion budget
for the 1989 fiscal year that starts Saturday, by voice vote
approved an amendment that would limit the district's spending on
Medicaid abortions to those cases in which the mother's life is in
jeopardy.
   The legislation then was sent back to a House-Senate conference
committee. Approval by the conference committee would send the
measure to the Senate.
   President Reagan has said he would veto the district's spending
package unless the anti-abortion amendment, sponsored by Rep.
Robert Dornan, R-Calif., is included.
   Current law allows the city to use locally generated funds for
Medicaid abortions, and allows federal spending on Medicaid
abortions in cases of rape and incest, ectopic pregnancies, and
when the mother's life is threatened.
   Earlier Thursday, Senate negotiators on the conference committee
had rejected a House proposal that would have simply frozen federal
funds if Medicaid abortions were not restricted to cases in which
the mother's life was threatened.
   The district's Medicaid program financed 3,599 of the 19,942
abortions reported in the city in 1986, according to Douglas
Johnson, a spokesman for the National Right to Life Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
