<DOCNO> AP880930-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TropicalWeather     09-30 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tropical Weather,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hurricane Helene Heads North; Some Strengthening Of Depression
Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a weakening Hurricane Helene raced north through
the mid-Atlantic on Thursday, forecasters tracked a tropical
depression that showed signs of strengthening east of the Caribbean.
   Hurricane Helene's winds of 80 mph kept it slightly above
hurricane status as it moved north-northeast at 48 mph, National
Hurricane Center forecasters said.
   Center meteorologist Jesse Moore said Helene is expected to
become absorbed Friday in a large low-pressure area over the north
Atlantic and its winds will be dispersed.
   ``There will still be some strong winds, but they will be over a
much larger area,'' said Moore. ``It will become a big Atlantic
storm.''
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT Thursday, the hurricane's center was near
latitude 48.5 north and longitude 36.5 west, or about 680 miles
northwest of the westernmost Azores, the center reported. It posed
a threat only to ships.
   Helene, the fourth hurricane of the Atlantic season, will be
classified a hurricane as long as its winds stay above 73 mph.
Spawned last week near the Cape Verde Islands off west Africa, the
hurricane peaked with 140 mph winds before the storm veered north.
   Meanwhile, the 16th tropical depression of the season was 545
miles east-southeast of Barbados and moving west at 17 mph.
   The system that formed Wednesday had winds of about 35 mph
Thursday and some increase is expected, the hurricane center
predicted.
   The hurricane season started June 1 and ends Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
