<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-CIA     09-30 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-CIA,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Sought to Restrict Justice Department Inquiry in CIA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he led the CIA during the Ford
administration, Vice President George Bush battled the Justice
Department in an effort to restrict a criminal investigation of
senior CIA officials, a published report said.
   At the time, a federal grand jury was investigating allegations
that officials working for or with the CIA, including former CIA
Director Richard Helms, lied under oath to Congress about CIA
operations in Chile during the early 1970s.
   Information about the dispute between Bush, the Justice
Department and the Ford White House staff came from newly released
files in the Gerald R. Ford presidential library in Ann Arbor,
Mich., the Los Angeles Times reported in its Friday editions.
   The files showed that in October 1976, citing the need to
protect intelligence sources, Bush repeatedly sought to prevent
some documents from being declassified and CIA witnesses from being
called before a federal grand jury.
   When White House officials reminded Bush that President Ford had
already given a public pledge that his administration would not use
classification or any other means to prevent exposure of illegal
activities, Bush balked, according to the files.
   ``An impasse exists between the Justice Department and Director
George Bush of the CIA,'' White House counsel Philip W. Buchen
wrote to Ford.
   Buchen told the president that if the Justice Department failed
to obtain the disputed information, it ``would abort the pending
investigation and lead to no prosecution.''
   In a memo at the time to another White House official, Bush
said, ``There is no intention on my part or on the part of this
agency to take any action that might reasonably be construed as an
effort to thwart or frustrate the investigation being conducted by
the (Justice) Department.
   ``At the same time, I mean to do whatever is necessary and
appropriate to carry out my statutory mandate to protect
intelligence sources and methods, believing as I do that such
protection is at the heart of the agency's ability to function
effectively,'' he said.
   President Ford instructed Bush to let federal prosecutors have
what they needed.
   The Justice Department investigation eventually resulted in
Helms' 1977 plea of no contest to two criminal charges of failing
to testify ``fully, completely and accurately'' to Congress.
   Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff, said through a spokeswoman
he would withhold comment until seeing the documents. Spokesman
Mark Goodin told The Associated Press late Friday he could not
comment until he had read the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880930-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 0335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen 3rdLd-Writethru a0891 09-30 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0891,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says GOP Would Move Country Back To 19th Century</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UDPATES throughout with speech as delivered.
^By JOHN KING</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen welcomed running mate Michael
Dukakis back to Texas on Thursday and said if their ``radical
right'' rivals win the White House ``we'll be living in the 19th
century instead of the 20th century.''
   The Texas senator introduced Dukakis at a $1.2 million
Democratic Party fund-raiser in Dallas after appearing with him to
formally accept the endorsement of the Combined Law Enforcement
Association of Texas, the state's largest police organization.
   At that gathering, Bentsen joked about Republican presidential
nominee George Bush's claim to Texas as his adopted home state.
Bush's legal residence is a hotel suite in Houston.
   Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential nominee, asked
presidential nominee Dukakis if he had checked into their hotel yet
and then deadpanned: ``In some people's mind that makes you a
Texan.''
   At the fund-raiser, Bentsen said Bush has been a partner in an
administration that hurt Texas by failing to adopt a national
energy policy and attacked the vice president and other Republicans
for questioning the patriotism of Dukakis, whom he introduced as
``a patriot for Massachusetts.''
   ``This election is about much more than waving the flag,''
Bentsen said. ``The question is what are we going to do together to
make us even prouder of our allegiance for the next four, for the
next eight and for the next 12 years from now when our children are
ready to the future.''
   Bentsen said Dukakis would provide activist leadership from the
Oval Office and, in an apparent swipe at President Reagan, said
that if he and Dukakis are elected there will be no ``falling
asleep at the switch while second-level aides run the show.''
   Bentsen said he was eager to debate GOP counterpart Dan Quayle
next week and characterized the Indiana senator as having ``a
radical-right agenda'' out of the mainstream of American voters.
   ``He doesn't even know what century he lives in,'' Bentsen said
in a gibe at a recent gaffe in which Quayle said he did not live in
this century. ``And believe me, if they get their way, we'll be
living in the 19th century instead of the 20th century.''
   Bentsen in recent days has been leading the counterattack to GOP
charges that Dukakis is out of the mainstream by accusing Bush of
pandering to the arch-conservative wing of his party in selecting
Quayle as his running mate.
   Bentsen came to Texas from Nashville, Tenn., where he visited a
middle school to reiterate Dukakis' support for the nation's space
program and urge the students to consider becoming scientists and
astronauts.
   Bentsen had planned to stay at the school and watch the launch
on television with the schoolchildren, but he left after liftoff
was delayed.
   Sharing a small seat with his wife, Beryl Ann, and surrounded by
staff and reporters, Bentsen watched the launch on television at
the Nashville airport before leaving the city for Texas,.
   ``It's a great morning,'' he said as Discovery soared into
orbit. ``It looks perfect.''
   At the school, Bentsen said the shuttle launch ``marks a new
beginning in our space program.''
   ``It is a good beginning but there are more challenges ahead of
us,'' he said.
   He told the students Dukakis was committed to the shuttle
program and to a permanently manned U.S. space station. Dukakis
also has promised to revive a Cabinet-level space council and to
put Bentsen in charge of it.
   ``Machines can go into space, but really only people can explore
space, probing for its secrets and reaching for the stars,''
Bentsen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
