<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:BaseballMovies ADV22   09-30 1081</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Baseball Movies, ADV 22,1112</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday AMs, Sept 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Diamond Is a Studio's Best Friend, At Long Last</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The success of this summer's ``Bull Durham''
has helped lead the way to an outpouring of movies about baseball,
once considered box-office poison by the moguls who ran the
Hollywood studios.
   During its first month of release, ``Bull Durham,'' a funny,
sexy account of minor-league baseball starring Kevin Costner and
Susan Sarandon, scored $26 million in ticket sales in the United
States and Canada. The Orion release, written and directed by
former bush league player Ron Shelton, has been followed by ``Eight
Men Out'' and ``Stealing Home.''
   ``Eight Men Out,'' John Sayles' drama about baseball's greatest
scandal, the sellout by members of the 1919 Chicago White Sox,
received a warm welcome from critics. Stars include Charlie Sheen,
D.B. Sweeney, John Cusack and Christopher Lloyd.
   Jodie Foster won raves for her performance in ``Stealing Home,''
the story of a minor league ballplayer seeking a comeback after
years on the skids. TV's Mark Harmon co-stars.
   Upcoming baseball movies include:
   _ ``Major League,'' with Charlie Sheen and Tom Berenger as
members of a hapless team who suddenly become winners, Rocky-style.
   _ ``The Scout,'' Anson Williams directing Rodney Dangerfield as
a baseball scout who uncovers a potential superstar. It is filming
this fall.
   _ ``Shoeless Joe,'' filming in Dubuque, Iowa, with Kevin
Costner, James Earl Jones, Amy Madigan and Burt Lancaster.
According to writer-director Phil Alden Robinson, it is not really
a baseball movie.
   Based on a novel by W.P. Kinsella, it concerns a farmer
(Costner) who is told by a spirit that Shoeless Joe Jackson of
Black Sox fame will come back to life if he builds a diamond in a
cornfield.
   _ ``Trading Hearts,'' already playing in a few regions, a
romance about a pitcher (Raul Julia), who is cut from spring
training.
   Producer Herb Jaffe said ``Trading Hearts'' also is not a
baseball picture.
   That's a hangover from the long-held belief that baseball
strikes out in theaters. The arguments most often heard over the
years are that baseball is incomprehensible to foreign audiences,
and that women, who make up a large part of movie audiences, will
not want to see films about baseball.
   Thom Mount, producer of ``Bull Durham'' and part owner of the
minor league Durham, N.C., Bulls, encountered such prejudice when
he sought a releasing company.
   ``Five studios turned us down before Orion picked up `Bull
Durham,''' he said. ``We were told simply that baseball pictures
don't make money.'' He attributed the film's success to the appeal
of Costner.
   ``Also, young women are impressed with the role Susan Sarandon
plays _ a strong, vital, liberated character.''
   By attracting the female audience, ``Bull Durham'' appears to
have solved one of Hollywood's prejudices. It remains to be seen
whether it can also appeal to foreign moviegoers; there is hope in
baseball-crazy Japan, and the game has been spreading to other
countries as well. Given the reasonable cost _ $9 million _ ``Bull
Durham'' is assured of a profit in the domestic market alone.
   A survey of baseball movies over the years indicates that the
studios' anti-baseball attitude may have been justified. Even the
box-office luster of Robert Redford couldn't convert the
allegorical ``The Natural'' into a winner.
   The best-remembered of baseball movies, ``The Pride of the
Yankees,'' with Gary Cooper as Lou Gehrig, was another commercial
disappointment.
   Many other biographical films have failed to excite the
movie-going public, especially women:
   ``The Winning Team,'' with Ronald Reagan as Grover Cleveland
Alexander; ``The Babe Ruth Story,'' William Bendix as the great
Bambino; ``The Stratton Story,'' James Stewart as Monty Stratton,
who staged a comeback after losing a leg; ``The Pride of St.
Louis,'' Dan Dailey Jr. as Dizzy Dean; ``The Jackie Robinson
Story,'' in which the black pioneer in the major leagues played
himself; ``Fear Strikes Out,'' Anthony Perkins as Jim Piersall,
victim of mental illness.
   Baseball musicals have proved to be only middling hits: ``Damn
Yankees'' with Tab Hunter and Gwen Verdon; ``Take Me Out to the
Ballgame,'' with Gene Kelly, Esther Williams and Frank Sinatra. The
same with comedies: ``Alibi Ike'' (Joe E. Brown); ``Rhubarb'' (Ray
Milland); ``It Happens Every Spring'' (Ray Milland).
   The difficulty of selling a baseball movie to the studios is
illustrated with ``Eight Men Out,'' produced, oddly enough, by
three women: Barbara Boyle, Midge Sanford and Sara Pillsbury. A
book about the White Sox scandal was optioned in 1980, but the film
was not made until this year.
   ``We couldn't get a development deal anywhere,'' Pillsbury said.
``The story had three strikes against it: The subject was
undeniably baseball; it was an ensemble piece; it was period and
hence expensive. We were told that baseball pictures had never been
successful, especially overseas.''
   The producers finally made a deal with Orion Pictures, which
also sponsored ``Bull Durham'' and ``The Scout.''
   Pillsbury thinks ``Eight Men Out'' will appeal to women.
   ``Baseball is simply the arena that the story takes place in,''
she said. ``It's more of a human story which is all the more
exciting because it is true.''
   ``The Scout'' also had a tortuous route to the screen. The film
actually went into production in 1982 with Peter Falk as star, then
was suspended. Earlier this year Orion sent it to Kathy
Lymberopoulos, producer and associate of Rodney Dangerfield.
   The story, she said, centers mainly on a baseball scout's life
and less on the game itself. As to any feminine prejudice against
baseball, she added, ``I love baseball, and so do a lot of women.
You look around a ballpark today and you'll see about
half-and-half, men and women.''
   What do the players themselves think of baseball movies? Here's
Lou Johnson, 53, star of the Los Angeles Dodgers in the 1960s and
now doing community service, lecturing against alcohol and drug
abuse:
   ``I've liked some of them, like the Lou Gehrig story, Roy
Campanella (TV movie) and Jackie Robinson, `Bingo Long' and `The
Natural.' But you're not going to get an accurate picture of
baseball out of movies. There's got to be a lot of fantasizing.
They give you what the public wants, not what is real.
   ``I especially liked `Bingo Long' because it was about the Negro
American League, and I could identify with it. It captured the
particular social life and lifestyle that we all went through,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
