<DOCNO> AP880930-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:BaseballFan ADV06   09-30 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Baseball Fan, ADV06,0530</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday AMs, Oct. 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-AP Arts: Baseball Movies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Take Me Out to the Tenplex: A Baseball Fan Goes to the Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's so, Joe.
   The baseball movie, long relegated to Hollywood's minor leagues,
is the winner of 1988's cinematic comeback of the year award. From
summer smash ``Bull Durham'' to critical rave ``Eight Men Out,''
baseball movies are back.
   And so what if ``Stealing Home,'' the Mark Harmon-Jodie Foster
entry in the baseball movie race, was almost universally panned?
Two out of three means Hollywood is batting .667 this year.
   The bounce back of baseball has prompted musings on the subject
in The Washington Post, The New York Times and Newsweek. Actor
Kevin Costner delivered the Most Valuable Performance in ``Durham''
as veteran minor league catcher Crash Davis, but an assortment of
stars suited up this year: Mark Harmon, Charlie Sheen and D.B.
Sweeney, to name a few.
   Costner and Sheen will do it again for movies coming out next
year. The switch-hitting Costner will appear in ``Shoeless Joe,''
playing a farmer under the sway of ``Black Sox'' star Joe Jackson's
ghost, while Sheen will be joined by ``L.A. Law'' star Corbin
Bernsen in ``Major League.''
   But why this return of the ballplayer as movie star after years
without any horsehide hits?
   _ The `R' rating. Gary Cooper as Lou Gehrig, who was married in
``Pride of the Yankees,'' never enjoyed the off-field activities of
Durham Bulls rookie righthander Nuke LaLoosh. And if Susan Sarandon
had played Mrs. Gehrig, Lou might have been the luckiest man on the
face of the Earth.
   _ The popularity of baseball. Virtually everybody has played or
watched the American Pastime. Major league attendance increases
every year _ in fact, you can expect that announcement from
outgoing commissioner Peter Ueberroth within weeks of the season's
finish this year.
   _ The ``I-Can-Do-That'' Syndrome. This factor is best described
by National Lampoon editor Matty Simmons: ``Any 5-foot-3, 270-pound
slob can watch George Bell blast a Roger Clemens 95-mph fastball
into northern Quebec and say to himself, `I can do that.' Why?
Because baseball players look like human beings. They look like
they belong behind a 7-Eleven counter.''
   Think about it. Can't you picture New York Mets phenom Gregg
Jefferies serving up a cold Slurpee and a Big Gulp? Now try to
imagine New York Giants rookie Jumbo Elliot, 6-foot-6, 305 pounds,
doing the same thing.
   As Simmons points out, Elliot could BE a 7-Eleven counter.
   There's one more big reason: the movies are better. In the past,
most baseball movies focused on one player, one star. There was
Jimmy Stewart as one-legged pitcher Monty Stratton. And Anthony
``Psycho'' Perkins as outfielder Jimmy Piersall. Or Ronald Reagan
playing hurler Grover Cleveland Alexander before his career really
took off.
   ``Bull Durham'' was the product of writer-director Ron Shelton,
who spent five years kicking around the minor leagues in the
Baltimore Orioles organization. ``Eight Men Out'' was done by John
Sayles, a die-hard baseball fan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
