<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0542</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has approved a $46.6 billion money
bill for the nation's farm programs, including for the first time a
ceiling on a major export program that has boosted overseas sales
of agricultural products.
   The House passed the measure, produced this week by a
House-Senate conference committee, Thursday by a vote of 353-35 and
sent it to the Senate.
   In a major development, House and Senate negotiators decided to
cap expenditures under the Export Enhancement Program, a major
export subsidy, at $770 million in the upcoming fiscal year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products in
September rose 0.7 percent from August, including the highest wheat
prices in almost seven years, the Agriculture Department says.
   But the rise from August to September was the smallest monthly
increase since the drought began cutting 1988 harvest prospects and
triggered rising prices last spring, the government said Thursday.
   Mostly as a result of the drought and searing heat, U.S. grain
production is expected to be down 31 percent from last year's
harvest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the International Monetary Fund has
praised the United States for its help in renewing efforts to
stabilize world currency exchange markets.
   As the annual meeting of the IMF and World Bank ended Thursday,
IMF chief Michel Camdessus cited U.S. support for cooperation among
the seven major industrial countries in sustaining income growth
and money rates.
   The so-called Group of Seven includes Japan, West Germany,
Britain, France, Italy, Canada and the United States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Bank of New York has handed
a victory to the Japanese securities industry by designating a unit
of Japan's Yamaichi Securities Co. as a primary dealer in U.S.
government securities.
   The decision was criticized Thursday as ``ill-timed and
ill-advised'' by Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., the author of
recent legislation calling on the New York Fed to deny
primary-dealer status to institutions whose home countries deny
equal access to U.S. firms.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Still battling to acquire Macmillan Inc.,
British media magnate Robert Maxwell has boosted his tender offer
for the publishing and information concern to $2.51 billion.
   Maxwell's offer on Thursday is up from $2.4 billion and tops the
cash-and-stock offer Macmillan accepted earlier in the week from
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., a prominent buyout firm.
   Maxwell said he will pay shareholders $90.25 in cash for each
Macmillan share, up from $86.80 a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has blocked the $2.6 billion
merger of the Lucky and Alpha Beta supermarket chains pending a
trial, saying the deal would ``substantially lessen competition''
in violation of antitrust laws.
   U.S. District Judge David Kenyon said Thursday that citizens of
California would be ``substantially and irreparably harmed'' if he
did not block the merger.
   California Attorney General John Van de Kamp has said the merger
would kill competition and thus drive up prices at the checkout
stand. The companies said the deal would cut costs by allowing for
a more efficient operation.
