<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RomanianCar     09-30 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Romanian Car,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flamboyant Car Dealer Backs Out Of Romanian Car Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACO, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maine's best-known automobile dealer has
backed out of a plan to import Romanian-built cars but his partners
will go ahead with the deal, taking possession of the first
shipment by the end of the year, according to a spokesman.
   Saco car dealer ``Jolly John'' Pulsifer said business
commitments forced him to cancel his plans to be nationwide
distributor for the four-wheel drive Aro Hunter 244, which is
manufactured in a government-owned plant near Bucharest.
   ``I'm out of the deal,'' said Pulsifer, whose nickname and his
string of car dealerships in this southern Maine city have made him
well-known throughout Maine and in neighboring states.
   ``The retailing business is getting exceedingly competitive and
needs more and more of my time. ...I gotta make decisions _ where
can I split my time the best? I can't afford to be a distributor.''
   His former partners in the American Compliance Corp. of
Scarborough, entrepreneur Arman Quaranto and developer Gavin
Ruotolo, still plan to import the car. They would be the nation's
only Aro importers, according to American Compliance marketing
director Sam Surprise.
   The four-door, four-cylinder Aro is powered by a Ford engine and
will sell for under $10,000. It will be marketed as a
less-expensive competitor to vehicles such as the Toyota 4Runner
and Nissan Pathfinder.
   The first shipment of 125 cars is expected to arrive in
Davisville, R.I., in November or December, Surprise said. He also
said he hoped 6,000 of the cars would be available within a year.
   Surprise said the cars would be sold by dealers throughout New
England, and as far west as Philadelphia. No dealers have yet
signed contracts to sell the cars, but Surprise said he expects
eventually to have 20 dealers selling the Aro.
   The Aro has a 30-year history as the working vehicle of the
Romanian Army. It also has been sold in China, Italy, Peru and
Portugal.
</TEXT>
