<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0020,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady At Slightly Lower Levels, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to CORRECT that July indicators fell. Pick
up 3rd graf pvs, However, dealers ... A version moving on general
news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was steady at slightly lower
levels in early European trading today. Gold prices also fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar could receive a boost
after the release later today of the U.S. Index of Leading Economic
Indicators. Traders said the average expectation for the August
indicators was a rise of 0.2 percent compared with a 0.8 percent
fall in July.
   However, dealers said fears of central-bank intervention were
still strong.
   In Frankfurt, traders said many corporate customers appeared to
have filled their end-of-the-month requirements are were
withdrawing from trading.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.05 yen to a closing 134.30. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 134.40 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates: 1.8795 West German marks, down from 1.8823; 1.5895 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5930; 6.3940 French francs, down from 6.4055;
2.11795 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1210; 1,400.45 Italian lire,
down from 1,402.60; and 1.2160 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2175.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6865, compared with
$1.6825 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $396.25 an ounce and at
midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $396.15. Both were down from Thursday's late
bid of $397.75 an ounce.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $396.40 an ounce, down from $397.50
bid late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.47 to close at a bid $399.16
an ounce.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.16 an
ounce, down from Thursday's $6.20.
</TEXT>
