<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Rice     09-30 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Rice,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Officials Speak Out Against Bilateral Rice Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan said that foreign access to the country's
tightly restricted rice market should be discussed at a
multilateral forum rather than just between the United States and
Japan, according to reports Friday.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita sent a letter to President
Reagan urging that the issue be discussed at the Uruguay Round of
trade talks under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, a
world trade body, the Japan Broadcasting Corp. reported.
   And the Foreign Ministry said that Japanese Ambassador Nobuo
Matsunaga met with Secretary of State George Shultz in Washington
to express concern about the rice issue.
   Matsunaga said U.S. demands that Japan's market be opened to
foreign rice were ``not simply a question of procedures'' under the
U.S. Trade Act, but rather ``a political issue of extreme gravity
affecting the basis of Japan-U.S. relations,'' the ministry said.
   In September, the U.S. Rice Millers' Association filed a
complaint with the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative
demanding access to Japan's rice market. Matsunaga asked Shultz to
promptly dismiss the petition, the ministry said.
   Japan maintains it should be allowed to maintain
self-sufficiency in rice because of its status as a basic foodstuff.
</TEXT>
