<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GrandMetropolitan 2ndLd-Writethru   09-30 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grand Metropolitan, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met In Deal To Sell Hotel Chain</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to remove extra `it.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC said today it has agreed to
sell its Inter-Continental hotel chain to the Seibu Saison Group of
Japan for $2.27 billion in cash.
   Grand Met said it also would explore joint ventures with Seibu
Saison in such areas as retailing, food, and property.
   ``Both companies are determined to use their combined skills and
experience to achieve maximum advantage in selected world
markets,'' the company said in a statement.
   The deal marks one of the largest Japanese acquisitions outside
of Japan. Heading that list is Bridgestone Corp.'s $2.6 billion
acquisition of Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. earlier this year and
Sony Corp.'s $2 billion purchase of CBS Records in 1987.
   Grand Met, the world's largest spirits company, produces
Smirnoff vodka and J & B Scotch and has interests in food and
retailing in addition to hotels. Its other businesses include Alpo
petfood and Pearle vision centers.
   Seibu Saison is one of Japan's leading operators of department
stores and supermarkets.
   Grand Met said it would achieve an after-tax profit of 500
million pounds, or $845 million, from the sale of the 100-hotel
Inter-Continental chain, which it purchased from Pan American
Airways in 1981 for $500 million.
   A Grand Met spokesman said the company likely would use the
proceeds for a future acquisition.
   Grand Met Chairman Allan Sheppard said the sale ``provides Grand
Metropolitan with a major opportunity to pursue its foods, drinks
and retailing strategies into the 1990s.''
   The company currently is embroiled in a contested bid for Irish
Distillers Group PLC, Ireland's leading whisky maker, for which
Grand Met has offered around $465 million.
   Jonathan Goble, an analyst at the London investment firm
Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd., said, ``Their objective is to expand
their presence in branded, consumer non-durable businesses.''
   The Grand Met spokesman, who wasn't identified in accordance
with British practice, said a joint venture with Seibu Saison Group
gives Grand Met ``an entree into Japan in those areas we're
interested in.''
   Grand Metropolitan's major presence in Japan is now in spirits.
One possible area of cooperation could involve franchising of Grand
Met's food and liquor brands through Seibu Saison Group's
substantial retail outlets, the spokesman said.
   Inter-Continental, headquartered in Montvale, N.J., runs hotels
in 47 countries. Among its best-known properties are the recently
refurbished Willard in Washington, the Mark Hopkins in San
Francisco, the Mayfair in London and the Carlton in Cannes, France.
The company also runs the 13-hotel Forum Hotels chain.
   In the year ended Sept. 30, 1987, Inter-Continental had
operating profit of 37.9 million pounds, or $64 million. Seibu
Saison has annual sales of more than 12 billion pounds, or $20
billion, Grand Met said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
