<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ControlData     09-30 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Control Data,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Control Data Folding ETA Systems Into Mainframe Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. has folded its
supercomputer business, ETA Systems Inc., into its mainframe
operations.
   The move could mean layoffs at the unit and pose a serious
setback for ETA, the Wall Street Journal reported Friday.
   Control Data also is reassigning Carl S. Ledbetter, the
president of ETA, to a marketing position within a new computer
products division. Ledbetter, 39, who came to Control Data two
years ago to run ETA, did not return phone calls Friday.
   Control Data officials wouldn't comment on possible layoffs and
other cost reductions at ETA, which is based in St. Paul.
   Control Data said that Gil D. Williams, vice president of the
computer products division, would oversee ETA and that the
supercomputer unit's vice president of operations, Al Moschner,
would assume responsibility for technical development and
administration.
   ETA was merged into a new computer products division without any
announcement in June, the Journal reported. The company disclosed
the move in response to a reporter's questions.
   In recent years, Control Data's mainframe computer business has
slipped. It serves mainly scientific niche markets and has lost
ground to larger domestic rivals.
   First-half revenue for the computer systems and services group
grew modestly and chip-production problems are delaying shipments
of a new machine, the Journal reported. As a result, an improvement
isn't expected now before the fourth quarter.
   Merging ETA with other computer operations discouraged some
analysts.
</TEXT>
