<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
mostly higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade in cautious
trading ahead of this afternoon's quarterly grain stocks report.
   Most of the early gains were attributed to position-balancing
ahead of the Agriculture Department report. The report will
indicate final soybean and corn stocks for the marketing year that
ended Aug. 31 and first-quarter usage of wheat, which is marketed
on a June-through-May yearly basis.
   The report was expected to show a continued drawdown of stocks
from levels a year earlier, analysts said.
   But it also could indicate that the higher prices caused by the
summer drought led to some slackening of demand during the
June-August period, said Jon Horton, an analyst in Chicago with
Research Department Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was 2{ cents to 4} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.16\ a bushel; corn was }
cent to 1} cents higher with December at $2.88\ a bushel; oats were
1{ cents lower to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.44{ a bushel;
soybeans were 3 cents lower to 7 cents higher with November at
$8.15 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange ahead of this afternoon's quarterly
USDA hogs-and-pigs report.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .13 cent higher with October at
71.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .23 cent
higher with October at 81.60 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent
lower to .15 cent higher with October at 39.60 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .25 cent lower to .75 cent higher with
February at 50.25 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures closed mixed on Thursday while pork futures
advanced.
</TEXT>
