<1ST_LINE>u f PM-USG-Masonite     09-30 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USG-Masonite,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Paper to Acquire Masonite Corp. from USG</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Paper Co. will buy the USG Corp.
subsidiary Masonite Corp. for about $400 million cash, the
companies announced today.
   Masonite, headquartered in Chicago, is one of the world's
largest producers of composite wood products for the home
construction and furniture industries, with sales last year of $529
million.
   International Paper, based in Purchase, N.Y., and one of the
biggest U.S. manufacturers, has been trying in recent years to
upgrade its wood-products and related businesses, the company said
in a statement.
   Masonite is attractive because of its strong brand name and its
demonstrated technical and product development capabilities, the
statement said.
   ``Over the years, Masonite has pioneered a number of important
products for the markets it serves,'' said John A. Georges,
chairman and chief executive officer of International Paper.
``These products include laminated panels for the furniture
industry and molded door facings, which are leaders in their
respective markets and have considerable long-term growth
potential.''
   Robert J. Day, chairman and chief executive officer of USG
Corp., said, ``We are pleased with International Paper's enthusiasm
for Masonite's leadership position in the production of wood
composite products.''
   He indicated that Masonite is one of several businesses USG is
selling as part of its previously announced restructuring efforts.
Others include Kinkead Industries, The Marlite Division, and the
Construction Metals business.
   The sale of Masonite is expected to be completed by Oct. 31, the
companies said.
</TEXT>
