<DOCNO> AP880930-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-88 1249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru   09-30 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Prices Slide Further</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to show crude plummets to $13.25 a barrel;
picks up 5th graf pvs, October heating ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures plummeted to their lowest
level in more than two years today as more negative news from OPEC
sent the market into a frenzy.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for November
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, hit
a low of $13.25 a barrel at midday.
   The last time the near-month contract closed below that level
was on Aug. 1, 1986, when it reached $11.55 a barrel. Prices had
fallen below $14 a barrel several times in recent weeks but
rebounded before trading sessions ended.
   ``The story is a complete breakdown in OPEC's discipline,'' said
Peter Beutel, an oil analyst with Elders Futures Inc.
   The November crude contract dropped 19 cents Thursday to settle
at $13.92. That was the lowest settlement price for a near-month
contract since $13.73 price of Oct. 29, 1986.
   Analysts said statements from OPEC Secretary General Subroto
that Saudi Arabia was increasing its oil output sent the market
into a frenzy.
   Subroto's acknowledgement that world oil prices probably would
be weak for the long-term indicated the unlikelihood that
discipline would be restored anytime soon, analysts said.
   Saudi Arabia, the largest producer in the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, has taken the lead in the past in
bringing other members back to their assigned quotas.
   Saudi Arabia is said to have recently joined the United Arab
Emirates, Kuwait and Iraq in exceeding their quota, leading to
speculation that the Saudis are trying a new strategy to force OPEC
members to rein in oil production.
   But Subroto said in an interview that the move could send prices
into a tailspin, to as low as $5 a barrel, if the Saudis used their
available capacity.
   In other trading Thursday, prices for refined oil products rose.
Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery closed up 0.25
cent at 46.42 cents a gallon. Other contract months were lower.
   October heating oil rose 0.04 cent to 39.54 cents a gallon, and
other monthly contracts also advanced.
   Analysts said the gains in gasoline stemmed from the recent
hurricane threat in the Gulf of Mexico when refineries and oil rigs
halted operations.
   API statistics released Tuesday showed that although gasoline
inventories were up 2.2 million barrels on a weekly basis to 219
million barrels, they were 10 million barrels below the same period
a year earlier.
   Brokers said crude prices continued deteriorating, reflecting
investor concern over the surplus of oil on world markets.
   ``It's a continuation of the same old junk we've seen for the
last four weeks,'' said Bud Degorgue, a trader with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   Analysts have said there is an excess of more than 1 million
barrels a day of oil on world markets. Recent meetings of members
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries have not
resulted in any concrete steps to restrain output, pushing prices
lower.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
