<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gained more ground today,
extending Thursday's rally as the pace of trading picked up.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 33.78 points on
Thursday, rose another 12.09 to 2,131.40 by 2 p.m. today on Wall
Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 9 to 5 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 887 up, 508 down and
477 unchanged.
   Analysts said many traders were pleased to see stock prices show
signs of life Thursday after a protracted period of little movement
on low volume.
   But they also said many market participants remained skeptical
that any fundamental shift had taken place in investors' mood.
   The government reported this morning that the index of leading
economic indicators rose 0.4 percent in August.
   The index, which is designed to detect future economic trends,
has been bouncing around erratically this year, and brokers said
investors were reluctant to infer much from its latest monthly,
finances and activities.
   If the church shuts its doors, Denys plans to stay in the parish
and continue his own outreach to his flock of 250 Dutch, Belgian,
Filipino and Latvian immigrants.
   But Denys, 68, fears his other mission _ organizing weekend
spiritual retreats to help struggling youths in the predominantly
black neighborhood _ will die.
   ``We're going to try to change the recommendation,'' he said.
``We still have a little time.''
   Szoka has said the appeals process could save some parishes from
being closed.
   For Denys, himself a Belgian immigrant, his appeal is his only
hope of persuading Szoka to spare his ethnic congregation in a city
that boasts the nation's largest settlement of Flemish Americans
from Belgium.
   To survive the winnowing process, a church must have a yearly
income of $100,000 with at least half collected in offerings. Our
Lady of Sorrows earns half that, but the minister said members have
kept the church free of debt.
   ``We always make ends meet,'' Denys said.
   He said the archdiocese built a new sanctuary 21 years ago, and
just last week the church won a city beautification award after
volunteers landscaped the yard.
   ``They were willing to build a church here, and now they're
willing to close it?'' Denys said.
   Gillespie, a church member since 1959, said she'll cling to her
rosary and her faith and believe in a miraculous solution to the
church's dilemma.
   ``When you trust in God, things happen,'' she said.
