<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Inter-Continental Bjt   09-30 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inter-Continental, Bjt,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saison of Japan To Buy Inter-Continental Hotels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC said Friday it was selling
its Inter-Continental hotel chain to Seibu Saison Group of Japan
for $2.27 billion in cash in one of the largest foreign
acquisitions by a Japanese company.
   Both companies also agreed to explore joint ventures in areas
such as retailing, food, and real estate.
   Grand Met said the Inter-Continental sale will give it an
after-tax profit of 500 million pounds, or around $845 million,
most of which will be used for future acquisitons. It bought the
100-hotel chain from Pan American Airways in 1981 for $500 million.
   Inter-Continental, based in Montvale, N.J., runs hotels in 47
countries. Among its best-known properties are the recently
refurbished Willard in Washington, the Mark Hopkins in San
Francisco, the Mayfair in London and the Carlton in Cannes, France.
   Grand Met Chairman Allan Sheppard said the sale ``provides Grand
Metropolitan with a major opportunity to pursue its foods, drinks
and retailing strategies into the 1990s,'' a plan outlined in a
recently announced restructuring.
   The company currently is embroiled in a contested bid for Irish
Distillers Group PLC, Ireland's leading whisky maker, for which
Grand Met has offered around $465 million.
   Grand Met, the world's largest spirits company, makes Smirnoff
vodka and J & B Scotch and has interests in food and retailing in
addition to hotels. Its other businesses include Alpo petfood and
Pearle vision centers. Annual sales total about $10 billion.
   Seibu Saison has interests in real estate, leisure hotels,
restaurants and food manufacturing. It has annual sales of about
$20 billion.
   Japanese companies have taken advantage of the strength of
Japan's economy and the Japanese yen in recent years to emerge as
big buyers of foreign companies and real estate.
   The Inter-Continental deal marks one of the largest Japanese
acquisitions outside of Japan. Heading that list is Bridgestone
Corp.'s $2.6 billion acquisition of Firestone Tire & Rubber Co.
earlier this year and Sony Corp.'s $2 billion purchase of CBS
Records in 1987.
   ``This is an important and logical step in the
internationalization of our hotel and other group interests,'' said
Tatsuo Aoki, a Seibu Saison director. ``Access to Grand
Metropolitan's wide interests in many sectors and our own retail
strengths in Japan form the basis of an excellent alliance.''
   A Grand Met spokesman said joint ventures with Seibu Saison
gives the London company ``an entree into Japan in those areas
we're interested in.''
   Grand Met's major presence in Japan is now in spirits. One
possible area of cooperation could involve franchising of Grand
Met's food and liquor brands through Seibu Saison Group's
substantial retail outlets, the spokesman said.
   Jonathan Goble, an analyst at the London investment firm
Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd., said, ``Their objective is to expand
their presence in branded, consumer non-durable businesses.''
   The sale of Inter-Continental is scheduled to be completed Dec.
15, subject to the approval of Grand Met shareholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
