<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Commuter-Probe 2ndLd-Writethru f0061 09-30 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Commuter-Probe, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0061,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Probe Finds Falsified Records, Management Problems</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8, The FAA, with 4 grafs to update with FAA
saying South Pacific still holds commmuter certificate, contrary to
agency's earlier announcement, and FAA clarification of status of
Texas National; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal inspection of 35 commuter airlines
has produced nearly a dozen cases of records being falsified and
problems with managing maintenance and operations.
   The special inspections by the Federal Aviation Administration
were announced last March and covered about 20 percent of the
commuter airline industry, which last year carried more than 31
million passengers.
   It was prompted by concern over a spate of commuter aircraft
accidents in which 56 people were killed during a four-month period
in late l987 and early 1988.
   A report on the inspections is scheduled to be completed by
December, but FAA officials provided a broad description of the
findings at a congressional hearing earlier this week and in
interviews Thursday.
   According to the agency, of the 35 commuter carriers inspected,
one airline _ Air New Orleans _ has voluntarily surrendered its
operating license and another, which was not identified, may be
forced to shut down.
   The FAA said six other airlines voluntarily turned in their
operating certificates as commuter carriers before an FAA
inspection of their operations could get under way, although two of
them denied the report.
   The FAA identified the airlines as Arctic Circle Air, AvAir,
Dade Helicopter Jet, Exec Express, Texas National Air and Grand
Canyon Airlines.
   The agency on Thursday had said a seventh carrier, South Pacific
Island Airways, also had surrendered its commuter operating license
but FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said today that upon further checking
it had been determined that the airline had not done so and
continues to operate commuter flights in American Samoa.
   Meanwhile, Texas National denied that it had relinquished its
commuter license. But Farrar said FAA records show the airline had
surrendered its certificate that had allowed it to provide
scheduled commuter service, although he said the airline continues
to provide on-demand air taxi service.
   Brian Loflin, corporate communications director for Fairchild
Aircraft Corp. of San Antonio, Texas, said today that subsidiary
Texas National got out of the commuter business in August but did
not surrender its certificate and continues as a charter service.
   Glenn Schaab, president of AvAir, said that airline surrendered
its certificate to the FAA in June, but the action had ``absolutely
nothing'' to do with the impending FAA inspection of the
financially struggling carrier.
   ``We had sold the flight operations portion of the company ...
and didn't need the certificate anymore,'' Schaab said in a
telephone interview from Raleigh, N.C.
   A sightseeing aircraft belonging to Grand Canyon Airlines
collided with a helicopter over the Grand Canyon in June 1986,
resulting in 25 deaths. It was not clear whether Grand Canyon's
surrender of its commuter certificate affects its sightseeing
operation.
   The FAA said at least three of the carriers _ AvAir, Dade
Helicopter Jet and South Pacific Island _ already had been under
Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings, in which a company seeks court
protection from its creditors until it can develop a plan to get
its finances in order.
   AvAir last year carried 351,522 passengers and was the 30th
largest commuter in the country, according to a ranking by the
Regional Airline Association.
   None of the other airlines subject to the inspections was
identified.
   Commuter airlines, which normally fly aircraft of 30 seats or
fewer, have taken on an increasingly important role in air travel
since many of the larger airlines no longer fly into small
communities.
   In testimony before a House investigations subcommittee on
Wednesday, FAA officials said as many as 200 enforcement actions
may come out of the inspections of the 35 airlines.
   John S. Kern, acting deputy associate administrator for
regulations and certification, told the panel that in some cases
irregularities were immediately corrected by the airlines ``and in
some instances enforcement actions have been initiated.''
   Kern provided no details as to the infractions found at the
commuter airlines, but described the findings in broad terms,
saying a detailed report was expected to be available by December.
   He said the inspections focused on management, maintenance,
quality control procedures and record keeping because preliminary
studies indicated those to be likely problem areas.
</TEXT>
