<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Eastern 2ndLd-Writethru f0158 09-30 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0158,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Eastern Decision to Lay Off 3,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 5-8, The three-judge, with further quotes; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today upheld Eastern
Airlines' decision to lay off about 3,000 employees when it
eliminated service to 14 cities, ruling that an injunction against
the furloughs was illegal.
   The ruling by the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here struck down
a decision last month by a lower court judge who had barred the
financially troubled airline from carrying out the layoffs.
   The three-judge panel ruled unanimously that the layoffs were
not an unlawful change in working conditions under the Railway
Labor Act, which controls labor relations in the airline industry.
   The court also concluded that the dispute between Eastern and
the unions ``was a minor one under the Railway Labor Act.
Accordingly, the district court was without jurisdiction to enter a
preliminary status quo injunction under Section 6 of the act.''
   The three-judge panel rejected the union's contention that the
layoffs were part of an illegal campaign by Eastern's parent, Texas
Air Corp., to undercut the power of organized labor at the
financially troubled carrier.
   The unions ``have directed our attention to nothing that would
undermine Eastern's claim that legitimate business concerns provide
an ample reason for these reductions,'' the court said.
   The judges noted there is not a claim ``that Eastern has
tailored its reductions so as to impose a differential impact on
union members. Indeed it appears that the furloughs affect union
members and non-members in roughly their propotions of Eastern's
workforce.''
   There was no immediate comment from Eastern or representatives
of the three unions that brought the suit.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker last month allowed Eastern
to stop service to 14 cities and close its Kansas City hub but he
barred the carrier from proceeding with the layoffs without
negotiating the cuts with its unions.
   The appeals court had stayed Parker's order and allowed Eastern
to furlough the employees provided it post a $4.7 million bond to
cover a month's pay in case the unions prevailed.
   The financially troubled airline, which was purchased in 1986 by
Texas Air Corp., had contended that it had not violated federal
labor law provisions that it maintain current working conditions
when it announced the layoffs in July.
   The company cited a previous layoff since 1980 as evidence of a
pattern of lawful furloughs.
   But three unions, the International Association of Machinists
and Aerospace Workers, the Air Line Pilots Association, and the
Transport Workers Union of America, contended that layoffs were
part of a union-busting campaign orchestrated by Texas Air's
chairman, Frank Lorenzo.
   The company contended that in order for it to survive it needed
the freedom to exercise legitimate business judgments, such as
deciding to go ahead with the layoffs.
   The elimination of service to 14 cities is part of Eastern's
attempt to streamline its operations and concentrate on its most
profitable routes along the East Coast and to Latin America.
   The airline contends the service cuts will result in annual
savings of $50 million in operating and $7 million payroll expenses.
   Service was eliminated to Albuquerque, N.M., Fort de France,
Martinique; Las Vegas, Nev.; Minneapolis-St. Paul; Oklahoma City;
Omaha, Neb.; Dallas; Point-a-Pitre, Guadeloupe; Reno, Nev.; San
Antonio, Texas; San Diego; St. Lucia, West Indies; Tuscon, Ariz.;
and Tulsa, Okla.
</TEXT>
