<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices closed modestly higher but
corn, oats and soybeans finished mixed Friday on the Chicago Board
of Trade in cautious trading ahead of the Agriculture Department's
report on U.S. grain stocks.
   Analysts attributed virtually all the activity to
position-balancing in advance of the quarterly grain stocks report.
   ``I didn't hear a thing'' about any other factors that
influenced trading during the session, said Steve Freed, grain
market analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   The report showed soybean stocks at 302 million bushels, down
from 655 million in the June report and 436 million a year earlier.
   The USDA estimated corn stocks at 4.26 billion bushels, down
from 5.83 billion on June 1 and 4.88 billion a year earlier.
   Wheat stocks were estimated at 2.24 billion bushels, compared
with 1.27 billion in June and 2.96 billion a year earlier.
   The soybean figure was well above most pre-report estimates and
traders pronounced it bearish for soybean prices. The corn and
wheat figures fell at the low end of pre-report estimates and were
said to be bullish.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 3\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.14{ a bushel; corn was 1{
cents lower to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.86{ a bushel;
oats were 4 cents lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.41{ a
bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents lower to 6 cents higher with
November at $8.12 a bushel.
</TEXT>
