<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-30 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Prices Fall On OPEC Leader's Comments</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precede LONDON BC; Subroto, one name, is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply Friday as plunging oil
prices unleashed trader fears that interest rates would fall in the
United States.
   Gold prices also fell as cheaper oil raised the prospect of
lower inflation. Gold, traditionally bought as a hedge against
inflation, was quoted at $394 a troy ounce at Republic National
Bank in New York at 4 p.m. EDT, down from $396.50 late Thursday.
   Oil futures tumbled after the secretary-general of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, Subroto, said crude
prices could plunge to $5 a barrel if Saudi Arabia switches to full
production capacity.
   Subroto said the Saudis might increase production to convince
OPEC members who violate their export quotas that all producers
would lose if they did not honor their OPEC output ceilings.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the price for the near-term
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude,
dropped 55 cents to close at $13.37 a 42-gallon barrel.
   Oil futures have been skidding recently because of the
oversupply of crude on world markets, so the prospect of full
output by the Saudis, the world's largest oil producer, raised the
possibility of a collapse in prices.
   ``The low oil prices dominated the market today,'' said Ronald
Holzer, chief dealer at Harris Trust & Co. in Chicago.
   Oil prices are a barometer of inflation. Lower inflation usually
leads to lower interest rates, which is a bearish sign for the
dollar.
   Overseas, dealers also attributed the dollar's slide to comments
about the U.S. currency by Federal Reserve Board Governor Martha
Seger. She said a sharp rise in the dollar would put the brakes on
U.S. economic expansion.
   Her comments caught foreign exchange markets by surprise and
spurred a dollar selloff late in the European trading day.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.05 yen to a closing 134.30 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 134.40 yen, and in New York, it slumped to
133.75 yen from late Thursday's 134.37.
   In London, the dollar dropped against the British pound. It cost
$1.6905 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.6825 late
Thursday. In New York, the pound climbed to $1.6935 from $1.6810
late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.8690 West German marks, down from
1.88265; 1.5830 Swiss francs, down from 1.59425; 6.3595 French
francs, down from 6.4065; 1,393.50 Italian lire, down from
1,402.25; and 1.21675 Canadian dollars, down from 1.21825.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8725 West German marks, down from 1.8823; 1.5830
Swiss francs, down from 1.5930; 6.3700 French francs, down from
6.4055; 2.1185 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1210; 1,396.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,402.60; 1.2171 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2175.
   Precious-metals dealers said gold prices seem unlikely to revive
to $400 per troy ounce in the near future.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold fell to $394.40 a
troy ounce from late Thursday's $396.80.
   Gold dropped in London to a late bid price of $394.45 a troy
ounce, compared with late Thursday's $397.75, and in Zurich, the
metal closed at a bid $396, compared with $397.50 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.47 to close at a bid $399.16.
   Silver fell to $6.135 a troy ounce on the Comex in New York from
late Thursday's $6.173. In London, silver traded at a late bid
price of $6.14 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $6.20.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
